<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Biotech Firm Buys Cloning Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                       *Asociated Press Writer    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Geron Corp., a small biotech firm, has  
bought Roslin Bio-Med, the company formed by the Scottish 
scientists who cloned Dolly the sheep, putting researchers in three 
promising areas of genetic engineering under one corporate roof. 
</P>
<P>
	The combination of patents owned by the two companies should  
attract new partners, adding to Geron's $49 million investment, 
executives at the Menlo Park-based company said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Individually, the companies' technologies ``have the potential  
to significantly improve our ability to treat and even cure many 
diseases. Together, that potential is enhanced dramatically,'' said 
Dr. Ian Wilmut, who created Dolly and will lead the Geron research 
with collaborator John Clark. 
</P>
<P>
	Geron has patented breakthrough technologies in the use of stem  
cells from human embryos, which it hopes can be grown into tissues 
for use as transplants. It also has patented a way of cloning the 
``cellular immortalizing enzyme,'' which enables otherwise mortal 
cells to replicate and live on extensively. 
</P>
<P>
	Roslin patented the method scientists around the world now use  
to clone animals. The new Geron subsidiary will combine the three 
patented methods and try to generate genetically matched human 
cells and tissues that can be replicated extensively and used to 
repair organ damage from degenerative diseases such as diabetes, 
Parkinson's disease, cancer and heart disease. 
</P>
<P>
	If Geron Bio-Med's theories prove successful, someone needing a  
transplant could get customized tissues grown in the lab that would 
not require anti-rejection drugs, said Dr. Thomas Okarma, Geron's 
vice president for research and development. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, given the patents held by Geron and Roslin, if such  
a process proves profitable, ``We have it locked up,'' Okarma said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Evan Snyder, an expert in stem-cell research at Harvard  
University, called Geron Bio-Med's research ``exciting in terms of 
its prospects,'' but he scoffed at Okarma's assertion that the 
company will own a new generation of genetic engineering 
applications. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm always leery of anyone who claims that they've cornered  
the market on the key to repairing organs, that there's no other 
way of doing it without having to go through them. I don't think 
that's true,'' Snyder said. 
</P>
<P>
	Geron bought all outstanding shares of Roslin Bio-Med for 2.1  
million shares of Geron common stock, worth roughly $28 million 
Tuesday. Geron also is investing about $21 million in applied 
research at the new subsidiary, and is looking for new business 
partners. 
</P>
<P>
	That may be difficult, if such investors aren't willing to wait  
years before realizing any profits, said Caroline Copithorne, an 
analyst who follows the biotech industry for Prudential Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they've now done is capture a lot of potential, having  
the patents, but it's so far from getting to products, you're not 
going to get a lot of investor interest today,'' she added. 
``There's a lot of interesting science and patents that never 
become a product.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
