<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs. Yen, Down Vs. Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen Tuesday amid  
worries the Japanese government won't expand efforts to revive 
Japan's ailing economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar fell against the euro in muted trading after the new  
currency recovered from troubling remarks by the European Union's 
chief central banker. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 120.85  
Japanese yen, up from 120.31 yen late Monday. The euro rose against 
the dollar, trading at $1.0617, up from $1.0567. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders bought dollars and sold yen after Japanese Prime  
Minister Keizo Obuchi, during a state visit in Washington on 
Monday, said that he saw no need for further programs to jump start 
his country's recessionary economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Without more help, analysts said, Japanese financial  
institutions might fail to recover despite government steps such as 
authorizing funds for yen-starved banks that undertake certain 
reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what caused the dollar to break'' higher into 120 yen  
territory, rising during trading as high as 121.28 yen, said Thomas 
Arnold, chief foreign exchange dealer at Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the euro fell after reports quoting Wim Duisenberg,  
president of the European Central Bank, as saying ``there are no 
concerns'' about the euro's weakness against the dollar. The ECB 
issues the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	But Grant Wilson, a foreign exchange analyst at Mellon Bank in  
Pittsburgh, said traders are sure that individual European central 
banks have been quietly intervening on the euro's behalf, buying 
enough small amounts to bolster the new currency. 
</P>
<P>
	With that in mind, traders reconsidered their positions and  
bought more euros, Grant said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 1.5110 Swiss francs, down from 1.5236;  
and 1.4529 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4470 late Monday. The 
British pound was quoted at $1.6292, up from $1.6093. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro no  
longer are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed 
rate. Based on the euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8422 German 
marks, down from 1.8508; 6.1784 French francs, down from 6.2073; 
and 1,823.74 Italian lire, up from 1,831.50. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
