<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Newspaper Circulation Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Despite some gains by larger newspapers, overall  
daily newspaper circulation declined by 0.5 percent in the six 
months ending in March, an industry association reported. Sunday 
circulation fell by 1.0 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The top ten papers with circulations over half a million  
reported a gain of 0.02 percent over the same six-month period a 
year ago, according to data released by the Audit Bureau of 
Circulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading papers reporting circulation increases included USA  
Today, The New York Times, The Washington Post, the Los Angeles 
Times, Newsday and the Daily News of New York. The Chicago Tribune 
reported gains in its Wednesday, Thursday and Friday editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Smaller papers generally reported declines. According to an  
analysis of the Audit Bureau's data by the Newspaper Association of 
America, the 30 papers with circulations between 250,000 and 
500,000 posted a decline of 0.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The 67 papers between 100,000 and 250,000 daily circulation  
declined 0.1 percent, and the 111 papers between 50,000 and 100,000 
declined by 0.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Concerned by the long-term decline in newspaper readership, the  
Newspaper Association has launched an effort to boost readership at 
a time when consumers face more choices for getting news. 
</P>
<P>
	The first phase of the NAA's campaign was officially launched  
last week at the group's annual convention under the guidance of 
Sergio Zyman, a former marketing executive for Coca-Cola Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Commenting on the ABC figures, NAA president and CEO John F.  
Sturm said: ``The newspaper industry is strong financially. Now, we 
recognize both the need and the opportunity to invest our resources 
in growing readership. Our concerns over stagnant circulation and 
readership figures were the impetus behind the industry-wide 
Readership Initiative, designed to build our share of audience and 
advertising.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
