<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	43 Die in Midwest Tornadoes  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The death toll stood at 43 today after  
tornadoes destroyed entire neighborhoods in Oklahoma and Kansas. 
Oklahoma City assistant fire chief Jon Hansen said the damage 
``looks like the Murrah Building,'' which was destroyed in a 1995 
bombing. The number of houses destroyed in the Oklahoma City area 
approached 2,000. Hospitals in the metro area treated 563 people 
for tornado-related injuries, police said. President Clinton 
declared 11 Oklahoma counties and one in Kansas federal disaster 
areas. Crews were seeking survivors and cleaning up damage. 

</P>
<P>
	Willey Says Clinton Was 'Forceful'  
</P>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- Former White House volunteer Kathleen  
Willey testified today that President Clinton was ``very forceful'' 
in an unwanted sexual advance in 1993. Mrs. Willey testified for 
the prosecution in the trial of her former friend, Julie Hiatt 
Steele. She said Clinton backed her against a wall and ``tried to 
kiss me. He was very forceful. His hands were all over me.'' 
Clinton has denied the allegation under oath. Ms. Steele is charged 
with lying to investigators to undercut Mrs. Willey's story. 

</P>
<P>
	American Jet Downs Yugoslav Fighter  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A MiG-29 fighter jet was shot down  
by NATO in a dogfight over Serbia today. As NATO claimed its most 
successful attacks, the alliance's top general acknowledged the 
airstrikes have failed to stem the ethnic cleansing campaign in 
Kosovo. Gen. Klaus Naumann, head of NATO's military arm, said the 
air operation ``has slowed down the efforts of Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic's instruments for ethnic cleansing'' but ``we 
cannot stop such a thing entirely.'' Milosevic today met with 
several top army commanders, and said the Kosovo Liberation Army 
had been ``fully defeated.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Freed POW Thanked Serb Guards  
</P>
<P>
	LANDSTUHL, Germany (AP) -- Freed American POW Christopher Stone  
gave his Serbian guards a thank you note before he and two other 
servicemen were released. The Pentagon said today that Stone's note 
thanked the guards for the way they treated him. Also today, 
doctors at a U.S. military hospital gave the three servicemen clean 
bills of health, saying no further medical care was needed. The 
soldiers were being given 30 days of leave, then were likely to 
return to their units based in Germany. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Heads to Europe for Update  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton headed to NATO headquarters  
in Belgium today for an update on the air campaign in Yugoslavia as 
Russia's mediator for the Balkans persisted in opposing the allied 
bombardment and a proposed heavily armed peacekeeping force for 
Kosovo. Before departing, Clinton welcomed ``every diplomatic 
possibility for the Serbian authorities to meet the requirements 
NATO has articulated,'' but insisted that he would not back away 
from the alliance's demands, particularly on the issue of returning 
refugees to Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Honors Rosa Parks  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton signed a bill today to give  
civil rights heroine Rosa Parks a Congressional Gold Medal. The 
move will bestow Congress' highest recognition on the 86-year-old 
Parks, whose refusal in December 1955 to give up her seat to a 
white man in Montgomery, Ala., inspired civil rights advocates 
across the country. Parks' arrest set off a lengthy bus boycott led 
by Martin Luther King Jr. and provoked a Supreme Court challenge to 
Montgomery's segregation law. 

</P>
<P>
	Goldman Sachs Shares Up 43 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Newly minted shares of Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co.  
soared 33 percent in their first day of trading today as investors 
welcomed Wall Street's elite investment bank into the public arena. 
Goldman's shares, which trade under the symbol GS, rose to $70.37 1/2, 
a gain of $17.37 1/2 from the $53 price set in yesterday's initial 
public offering of stock. The jump gave Goldman a market value of 
$38.6 billion, instantly making the company worth more than Merrill 
Lynch &AMP; Co. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Off 128.58  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks ended considerably lower today with the  
Dow Jones industrial average down 128.58 to close at 10,886.11. The 
Nasdaq composite index fell 50.45 to 2,485.13. Declining issues 
outnumbered advancers 1,598-1,383 on the NYSE. 

</P>
<P>
	Cubs Beat Rockies 13-12  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Mickey Morandini's shallow ninth-inning fly fell  
in for a game-winning single today as the Chicago Cubs blew a 
six-run lead and then rallied twice to beat the Colorado Rockies 
13-12. The Cubs hit five homers but trailed 12-11 in the ninth 
after Colorado's Darryl Hamilton hit an RBI single off Rod Beck 
(2-2). Jose Hernandez walked off Jerry DiPoto (0-1) to start the 
ninth and scored on Tyler Houston's RBI double to right center. 
Lance Johnson grounded out with Houston moving to third and 
Morandini's fly into right center fell in front of Larry Walker. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  

</P>
</TEXT>
