<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 03:25:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Hockey Player Steve Chiasson Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Accident investigators believe excessive  
speed and alcohol might have contributed to the death of Carolina 
Hurricanes defenseman Steve Chiasson. 
</P>
<P>
	The 32-year-old Chiasson was killed early Monday after he lost  
control of his pickup truck on a north Raleigh road. Chiasson, who 
wasn't wearing a seat belt, was thrown from the vehicle when it 
rolled. 
</P>
<P>
	The Highway Patrol said Chiasson was traveling above the 55-mph  
speed limit. Trooper K.L. Horne said he was awaiting results of a 
blood test before commenting on whether alcohol played a role. 
</P>
<P>
	``That has not been ruled out, but it has not been confirmed,''  
he told The News &AMP; Observer of Raleigh. 
</P>
<P>
	Horne said the official accident report would be available  
today, but that results of a blood-alcohol test will not be 
available for 2-3 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Team members and members of Chiasson's family planned to hold a  
private memorial service for him today. The team will fly to Canada 
for Chiasson's funeral, tentatively scheduled for Thursday or 
Friday. It will be held in Peterborough, Ontario, the small town 
near Toronto where Chiasson grew up. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened about 4:15 a.m., just hours after the  
Hurricanes were eliminated from the Stanley Cup playoffs in a 2-0 
loss at Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Team spokesman Chris Brown said two cases of beer and water,  
sports drinks, milk and vegetable juice were served on the team's 
charter flight from Boston to Raleigh. He didn't know how much 
beer, if any, Chiasson drank. 
</P>
<P>
	After the plane landed about 1 a.m. at Raleigh-Durham  
International Airport, the players got into their vehicles and 
dispersed, Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	One source close to the team told The News &AMP; Observer that  
Chiasson and some other players went to a player's home after the 
airport. 
</P>
<P>
	The wreck came almost two years after an automobile accident  
involving Chiasson's former Detroit Red Wings teammate Vladimir 
Konstantinov, Detroit's Vyacheslav Fetisov and the team masseur. 
The three were injured in June 1997 after a celebration of the Red 
Wings' first Stanley Cup in 42 years, won six days earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Konstantinov sustained severe head injuries that ended his  
career, and the masseur, Sergei Mnatsakanov, also was seriously 
injured. Fetisov had minor injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference Monday, team officials already trying to  
cope with being eliminated from the playoffs said they had lost a 
family member. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you work together in our environment, you have a family  
among players and an extended family among wives and children that 
go to school together and play on sports teams together,'' Carolina 
coach Paul Maurice said. ``.... It's a very painful time for all of 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a tragedy that is impossible to put into words,'' said  
Jim Rutherford, president and general manager of the franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Chiasson spent eight years with the Red Wings before being  
traded to the Calgary Flames in 1994 and then, in 1997, to the 
Hartford Whalers, who later became the Hurricanes. He played in his 
first NHL All-Star game in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``Steve was a member of the Red Wings' family for several years  
and continued to be a close friend to individual players and staff, 
as well as the organization,'' the Detroit team said. ``We are 
deeply saddened by this tragic loss. Our thoughts and prayers are 
with Steve's family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chiasson had shoulder surgery in January and played in only 28  
regular season games, scoring once and adding eight assists. The 
surgery was expected to end his season, but he returned to play all 
six playoff games for the Hurricanes, scoring a goal and two 
assists. 
</P>
<P>
	Chiasson is survived by his wife, Susan, two sons and a  
daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	``When a young life ends prematurely, when a young family loses  
a husband and a father, words cannot begin to express our sorrow,'' 
NHL commissioner Gary Bettman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
