<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Decline; Dow Falls 128.58 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks ended sharply lower Tuesday as a runup in  
interest rates prompted investors to reverse a buying spree on 
Monday that sent the Dow industrials above 11,000 for the first 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 128.58 to 10,886.11.  
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators gave ground after a mixed morning. The  
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 ended down 22.63 at 1,332.00, while the 
Nasdaq composite index fell 50.46 to 2,485.12. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's loss in the Dow shaved off more than half of Monday's  
225-point gain to a record 11,014.69, though many traders had 
expected a retreat after the leap from 10,000 past 11,000. Having 
taken just 24 trading days, that advance represented the fastest 
rise ever between 1,000-point milestones. 
</P>
<P>
	But as interest rates continued to rise in the bond market,  
pushing the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond up to 5.71 percent 
from 5.65 percent late Monday, investors became more concerned 
about the possible effect on corporate earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	``The interest rate problem is a problem that can take  
everything down,'' said Robert Robbins, senior vice president and 
market strategist at The Robinson-Humphrey Co. Inc. of Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Friday, when the long bond yield shot up to 5.66 percent  
from Thursday's 5.52 percent, investors dismissed it as a 
``knee-jerk response'' to a report that the nation's economy had 
expanded by a blistering 4.5 percent in the first three months of 
the year, Robbins said. 
</P>
<P>
	But with rates higher again on Tuesday, ``people get concerned  
about earnings,'' Robbins said. Higher rates would be unwelcome to 
stock investors because they could put downward pressure on 
corporate earnings and, by extension, on stock prices. 
</P>
<P>
	And because stocks are trading at very expensive levels right  
now, they are vulnerable to anything that can jeopardize earnings, 
Robbins noted. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond yields rose after two more reports Tuesday reinforced a  
strong economic outlook. The Conference Board reported that a key 
gauge of future economic activity rose for the sixth straight month 
in March. The research group's index of leading economic indicators 
rose 0.1 percent in March, pushed higher in part by rising stock 
prices. Although the figure was in line with economists' 
predictions, it was worrisome to investors who believe that if the 
economy keeps expanding, interest rates will rise. 
</P>
<P>
	In a second confirmation that the housing market remains robust,  
the Commerce Department reported that completion of privately owned 
housing units rose 12.6 percent in March, the fastest pace since 
April 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Both figures fed fears that the Federal Reserve might be  
inclined to raise interest rates in a bid to cool the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer shares, which often fall when rising interest rates  
push consumer financing costs higher, took the biggest hits among 
blue-chip Dow components. General Motors fell 4 3/4 to 89, after the 
carmaker reported disappointing April sales figures. Procter &AMP; 
Gamble slid 2 1/2 to 91 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks also fell as interest rates rose. American  
Express lost 6 1/4 to 127 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	One exception in the financial services sector was Goldman  
Sachs. The investment bank's shares soared on the Big Board in very 
heavy volume of more than 22 million shares, second only to America 
Online. Goldman shares closed their first day of trading at 70 3/8, up 
17 3/8 from an initial offering price of $53. The investment firm sold 
69 million shares in an initial public offering on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks held firm throughout the morning but buckled  
under selling pressure in the afternoon. Microsoft led the Nasdaq 
components lower, dropping 1 13/16 to 78 1/16. America Online was a 
big loser on the Big Board, shedding 6 to 127 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-7 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange. Consolidated volume was heavy at 1.12 
billion shares, up from Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 8.08 to 636.10, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index declined 0.97 to 785.70. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies eased 0.69 to 432.59. 
</P>
<P>
	In foreign markets, the Tokyo bourse was closed for the second  
of three holidays and will resume trading on Thursday. In Europe, 
the FT-SE index in London rose 0.08 percent, the DAX in Frankfurt 
rose 0.11 percent, but the CAC in Paris fell 0.10 percent. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
