<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO: No Evidence Jets Struck Bus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO has no evidence that allied  
warplanes struck a bus full of women and children in Kosovo, a NATO 
spokesman said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav media said 20 people died and 43 were injured in the  
daylight attack Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said NATO commanders made a thorough  
check of all gun cameras from planes operating in the area and 
interviewed all pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can find no evidence of any NATO involvement in this  
incident,'' Shea said. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, suggested  
there may have been other causes for the incident. One official 
noted that there had been skirmishes in the area between Yugoslav 
forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army, describing it as prime 
``ambush country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bus was attacked on a road 12 miles north of the Kosovo city  
of Pec, said a Montenegrin government official, speaking on 
condition of anonymity. Belgrade radio and television stations said 
20 people were killed and 43 injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Three civilian and two police cars also were destroyed. NATO's  
target was thought to have been a nearby police and army 
checkpoint, the Montena-fax news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shea said NATO aircraft struck overnight at both Yugoslav  
military and police forces in Kosovo, the southern province of 
Serbia, the dominant republic in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Targets in Kosovo included armored vehicles, artillery, radar,  
command posts, air defense and troops. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are cutting those forces off,'' Shea said. He said the  
allies also are pursuing strategic targets outside Kosovo, such as 
communication links, radio relay stations, satellite communications 
and electrical, ammunition and fuel supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	The NATO spokesman insisted that Yugoslav President Slobodan  
Milosevic must agree to the alliance's five conditions before the 
bombing will stop, including an end to Yugoslav military action in 
Kosovo, withdrawal of army and police forces from the province, an 
international military presence, the unconditional return of 
refugees and a willingness to work toward a political solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
