<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Revives Disaster Aid Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A stalled package of aid for Central American  
disaster victims and U.S. farmers is getting new life on Capitol 
Hill, thanks to the congressional fight over the confrontation with 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Central America legislation, dormant but technically in  
conference between the House and Senate, is likely to become the 
vehicle for billions of dollars for the conflict with Yugoslavia. 
Adding the Yugoslavia money to that conference report would speed 
consideration of the defense money and eliminate the possibility of 
amendments, underlining Republican leaders' concerns that 
otherwise, a lengthy, divisive Senate debate over President 
Clinton's Balkans policies would result. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really don't have time'' to consider the Yugoslavia  
spending legislation separately, Senate Appropriations Committee 
Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, told reporters Tuesday. ``The 
Department of Defense is running out of money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House, which has rules that let it move quickly, plans to  
vote on a $12.9 billion version of the Yugoslavia measure on 
Thursday. That amount is twice what Clinton has requested. 
</P>
<P>
	After House passage, which is considered likely, the Senate  
would never vote on a separate Yugoslavia bill. Negotiations 
between the two chambers over the package's size would begin, with 
the compromise placed into the Central America measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders hope to send Clinton a package late next week that many  
participants expect will include about $9 billion for the 
confrontation over Kosovo, plus aid for Central America and U.S. 
farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	The House approved $1.3 billion for Central America and farmers  
on March 24. The Senate passed a $2.4 billion measure the next day. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration officials and Democratic lawmakers urged  
GOP leaders to rush a compromise bill to the president so the money 
could move quickly to Central American victims of Hurricane Mitch 
and to American farmers hurt by low commodity prices. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Central America legislation has gone nowhere. It has  
been slowed by disputes between the two chambers, and between 
Congress and Clinton, over GOP proposals to cut other programs to 
pay for the measure and over Senate provisions dealing with tobacco 
settlement money and help for the steel, oil and mining industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, many Republicans have shown little enthusiasm for a  
package dominated by foreign aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that the Central America measure has been legislatively  
resurrected, Democrats tried pressuring Republicans to move the 
legislation on Tuesday by emphasizing its aid for American farmers. 
The House version has $152 million, the Senate bill $592 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to get help out to farmers and ranchers now,'' said  
Senate Majority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., who held a news 
conference with rural bankers and a half-dozen Senate Democrats. He 
said that without the aid, ``we could lose 20 to 30 percent of our 
producers in the coming year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said  
they expect language in the Senate's Central America bill to 
survive that would forbid the federal government from sharing any 
of the $246 billion tobacco companies agreed to pay the states to 
settle health-related lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, that language and the GOP's proposed spending cuts  
have drawn White House warnings that Clinton would veto the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle said if acceptable spending cuts were worked out, he  
would urge the president to sign the bill and fight over tobacco 
another day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
