<DOCNO> APW19990504.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 11:25:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Opening Statements in Louima Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Four white police officers conspired to violate  
the civil rights of a black Haitian immigrant, with two of them 
turning a police station bathroom into a bloody torture chamber, a 
prosecutor charged this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Kenneth Thompson, making his opening  
statement in the highly charged brutality trial, described in 
graphic detail how a handcuffed Abner Louima was battered inside 
the 70th Precinct in Brooklyn. 
</P>
<P>
	The Aug. 9, 1997, beating, which left Louima hospitalized with  
severe internal injuries, drew national attention and prompted 
widespread anti-police brutality demonstrations in the city. 
</P>
<P>
	``Inside that bathroom, Abner Louima suffered more than a  
beating,'' Thompson told the jury of seven men and five women. 
``Ladies and gentlemen, Abner Louima was tortured inside that 
bathroom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the brutal attack, Officer Justin Volpe allegedly  
rammed a wooden stick into Louima's rectum, tearing up the victim's 
insides, while officer Charles Schwarz allegedly held him down. The 
stick, smeared with blood and feces, was then smashed into Louima's 
mouth, the prosecutor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe sat impassively at the defense table with his four  
co-defendants as Thompson pointed him out as ``the man who violated 
Abner Louima's civil rights and his body.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys were expected to begin their opening  
statements later today. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the prosecutor, the officers became enraged because  
they thought that Louima had sucker-punched Volpe during a brawl 
outside a Brooklyn nightclub. The attacker was actually Louima's 
cousin, who was wearing a similar outfit, the prosecutor said. 
</P>
<P>
	The case ``is not about white vs. black, or about the New York  
City police department,'' Thompson said. ``This trial is about an 
escalation of violence that started on the streets of Brooklyn and 
ended on the floor of the 70th Precinct.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Eugene Nickerson gave preliminary  
instructions to the anonymous jury -- made up of eight whites, three 
Hispanics and one black -- this morning before opening statements. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial is expected to last six to eight weeks.  
</P>
<P>
	Volpe, 27; Schwarz, 33; and fellow officers Thomas Bruder, 33,  
and Thomas Wiese, 35, are charged with violating Louima's civil 
rights. The four allegedly beat him after his arrest outside the 
nightclub before the second incident in the bathroom in which only 
Volpe and Schwarz are charged. 
</P>
<P>
	A fifth officer, Sgt. Michael Bellomo, 37, is charged with  
helping cover up the attacks. If convicted, Bellomo, Bruder and 
Wiese face up to 10 years in prison. Volpe and Schwarz could 
receive a maximum of life in prison without parole because of the 
sexual nature of the alleged bathroom attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Louima, who has recovered from his injuries and is expected to  
be the government's star witness, has alleged in a 
multimillion-dollar civil suit that police used racial slurs during 
the assault. But in picking a jury, the judge repeatedly reminded 
prospective jurors that the federal indictments against the 
officers made no mention of race. 
</P>
<P>
	``They haven't been accused of racism at all,'' the judge said.  
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Stephen Worth signaled Monday that he plans to  
attack Louima's credibility by arguing that his story was 
influenced by the controversial activist the Rev. Al Sharpton, who 
rushed to his hospital bedside, and famed defense attorney Johnnie 
Cochran Jr., who is representing him in the civil suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Worth told the judge he wanted to note in opening arguments that  
Cochran was present when prosecutors took Louima into the courtroom 
one Saturday for coaching. 
</P>
<P>
	But the judge ruled that Worth could not mention Sharpton and  
Cochran or that his courtroom was used to prepare a witness. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I had known about it, it wouldn't have been held here,''  
the judge said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 17:13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Times Steps Up Online Presence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As part of an effort to beef up its online  
operations, The New York Times is planning to offer speedier 
updates to its own stories on its Web site, the newspaper's 
publisher said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Sulzberger, Jr., in a speech at an online media  
conference in San Francisco, said the newspaper also plans other 
steps to make its already successful site more current and useful. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this spirit of constant renewal, our Web site is now  
updated every 10 minutes throughout the day,'' Sulzberger said. 
``We now have a plan in the newsroom to begin offering continuous 
news from The New York Times on important stories throughout the 
day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sulzberger also said that since opening its site free of charge  
to overseas users last July, it has added an average of 4,500 new 
international users each day, for a total of 1 million foreign 
users. The Web site now has an overall total of 7 million 
registered users, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast to dire predictions about the future of newspapers  
from tech gurus like Intel Corp. chairman Andy Grove, Sulzberger 
said newspapers would play in important role in helping Internet 
users filter out noise when searching for useful information. 
</P>
<P>
	``People will continue to need a trustworthy guide through all  
the raw data dumps that are proliferating on the Web,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Newspapers -- either in print or electronic -- and their  
journalists will always be needed to make discreet, intelligent 
judgments about what is truthful, what is factual, what is relevant 
and what is trustworthy. This is what a newspaper does and what it 
will always do,'' he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 13:45:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Sought Steele Affidavit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- One of President Clinton's private  
lawyers clashed with Kenneth Starr's prosecutors Tuesday, saying he 
asked a Virginia woman to sign an affidavit helpful to the 
president but exerted ``no pressure'' on her. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman, Julie Hiatt Steele, is on trial, accused of  
obstructing Starr's inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitch Ettinger interviewed Ms. Steele in January 1998 -- soon  
after accounts of the Monica Lewinsky affair became public -- and 
then asked her to sign a document undercutting the story of 
Kathleen Willey, who had accused the president of making an 
unwelcome sexual advance. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton had denied Mrs. Willey's account in a deposition.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey, who told her story in a national TV interview last  
year, was in the federal courthouse waiting to testify as Ettinger 
took the stand on the trial's second day. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele, of Richmond is charged with lying to FBI agents and  
Starr's grand juries about Mrs. Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	Ettinger insisted that he exerted ``no pressure'' to persuade a  
reluctant Ms. Steele to turn in a signed version of what she had 
told him: that Mrs. Willey had urged her to lie to a magazine 
reporter to support Mrs. Willey's story of a sexual advance in the 
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	The affidavit was Ms. Steele's first sworn statement on the  
matter. She had previously given two conflicting accounts to the 
Newsweek reporter. 
</P>
<P>
	Verbally sparring with the president's lawyer, prosecutor David  
Barger suggested that Ms. Steele's affidavit was an important 
document that Clinton could have used to his advantage in the Paula 
Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, which the president eventually 
settled for $850,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Ettinger said ``I don't know of anyone'' at the law firm  
representing the president who tried to persuade Ms. Steele to sign 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	On cross-examination, Ms. Steele's lawyer, Nancy Luque,  
suggested that Ms. Steele went forward with the affidavit after a 
few weeks of hesitation simply because she wanted to set the record 
straight. Ms. Steele signed the document around the time she 
switched attorneys, hiring Luque. 
</P>
<P>
	Barger raised the possibility that the president's lawyers might  
have arranged for Luque to replace Ms. Steele's Richmond, Va., 
attorneys. Ettinger said he knew nothing about that. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele said in her affidavit that she first heard of an  
alleged sexual advance by Clinton in 1997 when Mrs. Willey tried to 
get her to lie about it. 
</P>
<P>
	But friends of Ms. Steele's called as witnesses have testified  
that Ms. Steele told them about the alleged incident between Mrs. 
Willey and Clinton prior to 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey has said she told Ms. Steele about the incident just  
hours after it happened in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele has said she told her false story to Newsweek  
reporter Michael Isikoff in 1997 as a favor for her friend but soon 
recanted it. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors have argued that Ms. Steele lied to ally herself  
with the president, as well as to make pictures of Mrs. Willey and 
the president that she was selling more marketable. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Starr investigated Mrs. Willey's allegation against the  
president, the independent counsel decided not to include the 
matter in his report about the president's relationship with Ms. 
Lewinsky, which led to a Senate impeachment trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele is the only person indicted by Starr's office in  
connection with the sex-and-lies investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
