<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 18:13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tornado Leaves Areas in Ruins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WICHITA, Kan. (AP) -- The sun was shining and the wind was  
picking up Tuesday over Lake Shore Mobile Home Park, where a small, 
manmade lake was brimming with the remnants of people's lives. 
</P>
<P>
	A mobile home floated upside down in the nameless lake. Wreckage  
drifted past. Clothing hung on trees. 
</P>
<P>
	Randy Rohlman picked up clothing near his trailer, which had  
been squashed by the roof of his neighbor's home. He had gone to a 
bookstore a few minutes before a tornado hit Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I hadn't gone there I might not be around,'' he said.  
``Boy, a lot of that stuff is buried. What a mess. I'm going to 
have to dig it out piece by piece.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tornado did serious damage in Kansas, killing five people  
and injuring 100 others. Two of those killed were from the trailer 
park. The other three were from Haysville and included a 
one-month-old boy. 
</P>
<P>
	Spawned by the same storm system Monday that produced even  
deadlier tornadoes across the state line in Oklahoma, the Kansas 
tornado cut a path 12 miles long and 3 miles wide in southern 
Wichita and suburban Haysville. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 8,000 buildings were damaged. Of those, more than  
1,100 were destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is crazy,'' Eric Peterson, a recent transplant from  
Seattle, said of the ruin that included a tree thrown into his 
bedroom in Haysville, just south of Wichita. ``I have been in 
typhoons in the South Pacific and in hurricanes, but this tops 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	National Guard troops joined about 200 state and local police in  
the area and dogs were used to search the wreckage for possible 
additional victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Peterson and his wife, Julie, grabbed their 5-year-old son  
before the twister struck and ran to a shelter. Their one-story 
rented home was still standing, despite a damaged roof. Their boy's 
wooden swing set had been picked up and hurled into a yard four 
houses away. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 150 houses, 27 businesses and three churches were  
damaged or destroyed in Haysville. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen people -- two customers and 11 employees -- were inside  
Leeker's, a Haysville grocery store, Monday night when assistant 
manager Pat Leeker received a call from his wife, who warned him 
that a tornado was expected to strike any minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Leeker locked the front door to keep anyone else from entering,  
then all 13 headed into the 18-by-25 foot produce cooler. They were 
on the floor, hands covering their heads, when the tornado roared 
over about five minutes later. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just happened so quick,'' Leeker said. The group emerged to  
find tiles fallen from the ceiling and water sloshing on the floor 
-- but no damage to the store's windows. 
</P>
<P>
	In southern Wichita, about 270 homes and businesses were  
damaged, including about 100 homes in two lakeside trailer parks. 
</P>
<P>
	Back at the lake, Misty and David Seeber walked along a shore  
with trees stripped bare, picking through the pile of broken wood 
and twisted metal that used to be their home. 
</P>
<P>
	It was her 22nd birthday on Tuesday. The couple found some  
wedding pictures and her wedding dress and were looking for David's 
wedding ring. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can find his wedding ring, we'll be happy,'' she said.  
``We're very lucky somebody's watching over us.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Associated Press newswoman Roxana Hegeman  
contributed to this story. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
