<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Off 120.58  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks ended considerably lower today, as a  
runup in interest rates prompted investors to reverse yesterday's 
buying spree that sent the Dow industrials above 11,000 for the 
first time. The Dow Jones industrial average was down 120.58 at 
10,886.11 today. Broader stock indicators gave ground after a mixed 
morning. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 22.63 to 1,332, and the 
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 50.45 to 2,485.13. 
Today's loss in the Dow was more than half of Monday's 225-point 
gain to 11,014.69. As interest rates continued to rise in the bond 
market, pushing the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond up to 5.72 
percent from 5.65 percent late Monday, investors became more 
concerned about the effect that could have on corporate earnings. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close :  
Dow Industrials:        10886.11 - 128.58
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1383  Declines 1598  Unchgd  583
NYSE Volume:         925,870,000
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online127 3/8   - 5 3/4
S&AMP;P 500:         1332.00 - 22.63
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          785.70  -   0.97
Nasdaq Composite Index       2,485.13  -  50.45
Gold(final) -    $285.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.

</P>
<P>
	Goldman Sachs Stock Soars  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Newly minted shares of Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co.  
soared to 70 1/8 today from an initial public offering price of 53. It 
was trading under the ticker symbol GS and leading volume on the 
New York Stock Exchange. Requests for shares totaled more than 10 
times the amount Goldman had offered. Goldman Sachs ended its 
130-year run as a private partnership after selling 69 million 
shares that raised $3.66 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Indicators Rise Again  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rising stock prices and signs of a backlog in  
the delivery of orders by vendors pushed a key gauge of future 
economic activity higher for the sixth straight month in March. The 
Conference Board, a private research group, reported today that its 
Index of Leading Economic Indicators rose 0.1 percent to 107.3, up 
from a revised level of 107.2 in February. 

</P>
<P>
	Online Broker Accountability Urged  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government's top securities regulator,  
noting that ads for online trading often resemble lottery 
commercials, is urging Internet brokerages to better warn their 
customers about the risks that come with investing on the Internet. 
Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, 
said today that an SEC review of online brokerage account 
agreements found that ``almost none'' of them discuss trading risks 
or what customers should do if there is a computer system outage. 

</P>
<P>
	Kodak CFO Harry Kavetas Dies  
</P>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Eastman Kodak Co. chief financial officer  
Harry L. Kavetas, who helped engineer nearly 20,000 job cuts at the 
photography company to counter Japanese gains in the U.S. market, 
died today at age 61. Kavetas suffered an apparent heart attack at 
his home. A longtime executive at IBM Corp., Kavetas took a brief 
early retirement at the end of 1993 after being passed over for a 
top post by new IBM chief executive Louis V. Gerstner. He was hired 
as Kodak's chief financial officer in February 1994. By the end of 
this year, Kodak expects to trim more than $1 billion in costs by 
eliminating almost one-fifth of its worldwide payroll of 100,500. 
The company has seen a sharp rebound in sales and profits in recent 
months. 

</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola To Acquire Orangina Brand  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Coca-Cola Co. has signed a $758 million deal to  
acquire the soft drink brand Orangina from French beverage company 
Pernod Ricard -- an acquisition blocked by France for nearly 18 
months. The companies announced that the new agreement is intended 
to respond to the concerns of French competition authorities by 
excluding Coca-Cola from distributing Orangina in French 
restaurants, bars and hotels for 10 years. The restriction does not 
apply to Coke's rights to sell Orangina in other countries. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Proposes Privacy Controls  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today proposed legislation  
to protect consumers against information-sharing among banks, 
insurance companies and security firms. Clinton noted that 
consumers receive 4 billion unsolicited credit card offers every 
year and that some people are duped by the small print. The 
legislation would require financial institutions to inform 
consumers of plans to share or sell their personal financial 
information and give consumers the power to stop such a transfer. 
Credit-card offers would be required to prominently disclose when 
their low ``teaser rates'' expire. Also today, Clinton reiterated 
his support for the Community Reinvestment Act, which spurs banks 
to lend in underdeveloped communities. 

</P>
<P>
	Dutch Co. To Purchase Wang Global  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Wang Global is being acquired by a Dutch company  
Getronics NV for $2 billion in cash. The union with Getronics will 
form the largest computer services company in Europe and one of the 
five largest in the world, company officials said today. The 
combined company is expected to have annual revenues of about $5 
billion, with 33,000 employees and operations in more than 44 
countries. Under terms of the agreement, Getronics will purchase 
Wang for $29.25 a share, as well as warrants, options and other 
securities. 

</P>
<P>
	FCC Chief Eyes Web Smut Protections  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Communications Commission Chairman  
Bill Kennard today that schools and libraries should have policies 
protecting children from smut and other inappropriate material on 
the Internet in order to receive federal money to subsidize access. 
The Clinton administration is pushing the proposal. Last month, the 
Commerce Department urged the FCC, which oversees the Internet 
subsidies program, to require public schools and libraries to have 
such policies in place if they want to receive the subsidies. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford Recalls Expeditions, Navigators  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. is recalling about 57,200  
of its 1999 Expeditions and Navigators because of a problem that 
could cause the wheels to fall off. The recall of the two sport 
utility vehicles affects models with optional 17-inch 
chrome-finished steel wheels. Ford said some wheels might not have 
enough contact with the hub, which could cause vibration or result 
in the wheel and tire falling off. Dealers will tighten the wheels 
and install a label with tightening instructions on each wheel at 
no expense to owners. 

</P>
<P>
	Sara Lee Makes Bid for Coffee Co.  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sara Lee Corp. launched a hostile takeover bid  
for Chock full o'Nuts Corp. as it seeks to expand its coffee 
business. The offer announced today to shareholders is essentially 
the same as Sara Lee's $223 million cash offer that was rejected by 
the Chock full o'Nuts board. Sara Lee is offering $10.50 cash for 
each Chock full o'Nuts share, $1,275.82 for bonds due in 2012 and 
$1,344.43 for bonds due in 2006. The maker of Ball Park hot dogs, 
Coach leather goods and other products said its offer depended on 
getting at least two-thirds of the approximately 10.8 million 
shares outstanding and a repeal of formidable takeover defenses 
initiated by the board of Chock full o'Nuts. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
