<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornado Damage Worries Insurers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- While residents combed through debris from the  
tornadoes that ripped through Oklahoma and Kansas Monday, insurance 
companies anticipating drastic losses made their first overtures to 
the battered region. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's major insurers were all preparing special  
catastrophe teams to travel to the area. Some claims adjusters 
arrived Tuesday and were beginning to evaluate the damage, but many 
others stayed away for another day, awaiting a lull in the 
wrenching weather. 
</P>
<P>
	While cost estimates of the damage won't be available for  
several days, the size and ferocity of the storms led many to 
believe the losses will be the steepest ever caused by a tornado. 
</P>
<P>
	The costliest tornado on record struck Xenia, Ohio in 1974,  
causing $400 million in property damage, according to the Property 
Claim Services unit of the New York-based Insurance Services Office 
Inc. Adjusted for inflation, that's about $1.3 billion, the group 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The costliest storm on record was Hurricane Andrew, which caused  
about $16 billion in property losses in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 2,000 houses in the Oklahoma City area were destroyed  
by the tornadoes. Wichita, Kan., also sustained heavy losses. 
</P>
<P>
	``We studied 37 mid-sized to large catastrophes last year,''  
said John Eager, director of claims services for the National 
Association of Independent Insurers. ``I don't remember any that 
were as devastating as this one seems to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many areas remained off-limits to insurance workers Tuesday  
afternoon as rescue workers searched for survivors. Travelers 
Property and Casualty, which plans to have a dozen workers in the 
damaged regions by Wednesday morning, said another 40 would arrive 
later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first step is to assess the whole area, and then we'll see  
what else we need to do,'' said Ray Stone, catastrophe manager for 
the insurance giant. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hartford, a Connecticut-based insurer, had some adjusters at  
work in Oklahoma on Tuesday, but also anticipated a heavier 
workload later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Erwin, a spokesman for the Insurance Information  
Institute, said insurance companies typically wait a bit before 
they fully mobilize after a catastrophe. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are initially in shock,'' he said. ``It's OK to let  
them be in shock for a while, then go in and help them rebuild.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
