<HEADLINE> Poll: Bush Holds Big Lead Over Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush has taken a strong lead over  
Elizabeth Dole in New Hampshire in the race for the Republican 
presidential nomination, and retains a big advantage nationally, 
according to two polls released Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Democratic side, Vice President Al Gore has expanded his  
lead over Bill Bradley, former senator from New Jersey, according 
to a national poll of Democrats by CNN-USA Today-Gallup. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore had 66 percent in the poll, while Bradley had 23 percent.  
In mid-April, Bradley trailed Gore 54 percent to 34 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll is evidence of Gore's growing strength among Democrats,  
said his spokesman, Roger Salazar. ``As people get to know him 
better, we should only gain ground,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush leads Gore in a theoretical head-to-head match by 56  
percent to 40 percent, in the CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll, about the 
same lead Bush has held over Gore since February. 
</P>
<P>
	A New Hampshire poll taken by the University of New Hampshire  
for CNN-WMUR, shows Bush, the Texas governor, at 37 percent, 
followed by Dole, a former Red Cross president, at 16 percent. Sen. 
John McCain of Arizona, who has improved his standing, is now 
challenging Dole for second with 14 percent. A poll taken in 
January had Bush and Dole in a statistical dead heat. 
</P>
<P>
	Among New Hampshire Democrats, Gore was favored by 68 percent  
and Bradley by 23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the national poll of Republicans, Bush was favored by 42  
percent and Dole by 24 percent. In mid April, Bush led Dole by a 53 
percent-16 percent margin. 
</P>
<P>
	Mindy Tucker, a spokeswoman for the Bush campaign, said the  
governor won't be traveling nationally until mid June because the 
Texas legislature is meeting until the end of May. 
</P>
<P>
	But she noted the campaign has pulled together its New Hampshire  
organization in the last month and Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., 
endorsed Bush in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll of 411 Republicans and 492  
Democrats was taken Friday through Sunday and has an error margin 
of plus or minus 5 percentage points for each group. The New 
Hampshire poll of 279 likely Republican voters had a margin of 
error of plus or minus 6 percentage points, while the poll of 202 
likely Democratic voters had a margin of error of plus or minus 7 
percent. That poll was taken April 26-May 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
