<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Emotional Reunions for Ex-POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANDSTUHL, Germany (AP) -- Happily reunited with their families,  
three U.S. Army soldiers got a clean bill of health today after a 
month of captivity in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Checkups of the soldiers at a U.S. military hospital in Germany  
have revealed fractured ribs and a broken nose, raising questions 
about how they were treated during their capture and imprisonment. 
</P>
<P>
	But Col. Mack Blanton, chief of clinical services at Landstuhl  
Regional Medical Center, said today ``they require no further 
in-patient care or treatment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They've had a comprehensive medical evaluation and they are  
fine and in good health,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army refused comment on how the injuries were sustained,  
citing the continuing investigation into the circumstances of their 
March 31 capture on the Yugoslav-Macedonia border. 
</P>
<P>
	Before arriving at Landstuhl on Sunday from the Yugoslav capital  
of Belgrade, the soldiers told reporters their scars and bruises 
stemmed from their capture, but said they were generally treated 
well after that. 
</P>
<P>
	The soldiers remained at the hospital today to spend more time  
with their families and readjust. Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon 
said the three soldiers would undergo debriefings in Germany for 
two or three more days. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial debriefings have reaffirmed U.S. officials' belief  
that the soldiers were captured inside Macedonia, Bacon said. Serb 
authorities have claimed the three were in Serb territory when 
captured. 
</P>
<P>
	After taking 30 days of leave, the soldiers were likely to  
return to their units based in Germany, Bacon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid hugs, laughter and tears of joy, the servicemen were  
reunited with family members at Landstuhl on their first full day 
of freedom Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	After private reunions, Staff Sgts. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los  
Angeles and Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., Spec. 
Steven Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas, and their families 
stepped onto a sunny hospital balcony decorated with flags. 
</P>
<P>
	Beaming and holding on to each other, they waved briefly to  
reporters and photographers across the street. 
</P>
<P>
	The families were to remain in Germany for a few days with the  
soldiers. That raised the possibility of a meeting with President 
Clinton, who was expected Wednesday in Germany for a previously 
planned visit to U.S. troops. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton would like to  
meet with the three servicemen but he did not want to delay their 
return home. 
</P>
<P>
	Medical tests revealed that Ramirez had two fractured ribs, one  
on each side, and Stone had a fractured nose. Blanton said the 
fractures were already starting to heal and required no treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	After being released in Belgrade on Sunday, the soldiers  
traveled by bus to Croatia and then were flown to Germany, 
accompanied by civil rights leader Jesse Jackson, who had 
negotiated their release with Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson hoped Clinton would reciprocate by offering a respite  
from airstrikes, now in their sixth week. But NATO refused. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson met with Clinton on Monday and discussed a letter from  
Milosevic with proposals to resolve the crisis over Kosovo. Jackson 
also asked Clinton to release two Yugoslav prisoners of war as a 
goodwill gesture. There was no immediate response to the request 
from the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Expressing his gratitude to Jackson, Clinton said he was pleased  
at the soldiers' release but added the United States cannot forget 
the plight of the thousands of refugees forced out of Kosovo by 
Yugoslav forces. 
</P>
<P>
	``When will these people see their home again, with the safety  
and rights Mr. Milosevic has often pledged but never delivered?'' 
Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
