<HEADLINE> Hi-Tech Political Arm Gets New Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO (AP) -- A top lawyer for Netscape Communications who  
played a prominent role in the federal government's antitrust 
lawsuit against Microsoft Corp. was named president of the 
Technology Network on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Netscape and archrival Microsoft are members of influential  
TechNet, the high-tech industry's bipartisan political arm. As 
TechNet president, Roberta Katz will now represent both companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is Roberta's past life, and she is now in a role that  
focuses totally on industry issues common to all high-tech 
companies,'' said Reed Hastings, the outgoing first president. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastings is leaving to run an Internet startup firm that offers  
online video rental services. 
</P>
<P>
	Under his leadership, 2-year-old TechNet emerged as a powerful  
player in state and federal politics and policy-making. 
</P>
<P>
	TechNet was formed after the industry fought Proposition 211, an  
unsuccessful initiative on California's November 1996 ballot that 
would have made it easier for shareholders to sue companies when 
the stock price drops. 
</P>
<P>
	In its suit, the Justice Department accused Microsoft of  
unfairly using the dominance of its Windows operating system to 
make inroads into the Internet browser market, where it competes 
with Netscape. 
</P>
<P>
	Netscape was recently acquired by America Online Inc. for nearly  
$10 billion, a move that Microsoft contends means that competition 
is thriving in the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial has been in recess since Feb. 26 and is not expected  
to resume before May 24. Katz will have no further involvement in 
the case. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
