<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Callaway Pondering Another Lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Callaway Golf's battlefield seems to be moving from the fairways  
to the courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Four months after he filed a lawsuit against Orlimar alleging  
patent infringement and unfair trade practices, founder and 
chairman Ely Callaway is thinking about taking another case to the 
Federal Trade Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind this complaint is what is -- and isn't -- in the bag.  
</P>
<P>
	Without naming names, Callaway referred to Ted Tryba carrying an  
Orlimar bag during the Nissan Open, where he shot a 61 in the third 
round, and Dudley Hart carrying an Adams bag and wearing the cap in 
the Greater Greensboro Classic, where he tied for fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Darrell Survey, neither player had a single  
club from the respective company in the bag that week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know there's been a lot of hanky-panky going on for years,  
but I've never seen anything quite this blatant,'' Callaway said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is our current thinking that probably the only way to  
eliminate these types of deceptive and misleading advertising and 
promotional practices by a few of our competitors is to bring our 
complaint directly to the Federal Trade Commission.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Go ahead, said the founder of Adams Golf.  
</P>
<P>
	``Ely is just trying to protect his franchise,'' Barney Adams  
said. ``This is much ado about nothing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adams said Hart carries the Tight Lies 4-wood, but when he got  
to Greensboro and saw the fast conditions decided to use a 3-wood 
that week. Adams didn't have one ready with his specifications. 
</P>
<P>
	Callaway also accused Adams of using Nick Faldo in its  
infomercial for the SC Series driver, but not using one in the MCI 
Classic. Adams said Faldo wanted to change his specs on the driver 
that week, but noted that Faldo used the Adams driver the week 
before (the Masters) and after (the Spanish Open). 
</P>
<P>
	``What Ely has chosen to do in this case is pick and choose,''  
Adams said. ``As a result, he's guilty of being as deceptive as 
he's accusing us of being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Orlimar co-chairman Rich Oldenburg says Tryba is not one of its  
staff players and ``is free to carry any bag he chooses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not paying him an endorsement and we're not using him in  
our advertisements,'' Oldenburg said, although he added that Tryba 
is working with some of the clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Callaway says all but one of its 45 staff players carry at least  
10 clubs. The exception is Paul Azinger, who carries only the 
fairway metals and has a logo that says just that on the bag. 
</P>
<P>
	Ping requires its professionals to carry at least 12 clubs,  
including the putter. If a player uses the Ping ISI driver, he only 
has to carry 11 clubs plus the putter. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Ely wants to change the tour to 10-club contracts, my  
answer is don't talk to me,'' Adams said. ``Go talk to guys like 
IMG. They're the ones who set the deals.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LOVE HURTS:* Davis Love III had a strong stretch the last few  
months, getting into contention in the Bay Hill Invitational and 
The Players Championship and finishing second in the Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	But it has taken a toll. Love withdrew from the MCI Classic with  
back problems, then decided against going to Japan to defend his 
title in the Chunichi Crowns. 
</P>
<P>
	The next question is how soon he will recover. Love has pulled  
out of this week's Compaq Classic in New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STROKE START:* The American Stroke Challenge got off to a  
rousing start in New York's Central Park when Nancy Lopez holed a 
20-yard chip worth $50,000 and Corey Pavin made one worth $10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to their birdies during the Monday exhibition, they  
raised $93,500 for the American Stroke Association. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of it will come from tournaments in the month of May.  
Bayer Aspirin will donate $1,500 for every birdie they make on 
tour. The goal is to raise $250,000 by the end of the month. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *OPEN ENTRIES:* A record 7,889 people have entered qualifying  
for the U.S. Open at Pinehurst, an increase of 772 from 1998.	   More than 2,500 arrived on the last three days before the April 
28 deadline, and 404 were turned down because they either had a 
poor record in past qualifiers or had a handicap index higher than 
1.4. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HAPPY THE SECOND:* Se Ri Pak is looking for a little peace and  
quiet in her life, which was bad news for the beagle she got last 
year and named ``Happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During a preview of the U.S. Women's Open at Old Waverly Golf  
Club in Mississippi, the defending champion introduced her new best 
friend -- a 7-month old miniature schnauzer. 
</P>
<P>
	``At first, I had a beagle, but she was too rough. Tear  
everything up,'' Pak said. ``She didn't want to sleep when time to 
sleep. I needed a quiet dog.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The name of the new dog? Happy, of course.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DIVOTS:* According to the Darrell Survey, more players used  
Softspikes than metal spikes in the Greater Greensboro Classic, the 
first time that's happened in PGA Tour history. ... Stuart Appleby 
has won all three of his PGA Tour events on TPC courses -- Heron Bay 
(Honda Classic), Avenel (Kemper Open) and The Woodlands (Houston 
Open). ... The U.S. Senior Open at Des Moines Golf and Country Club 
is a sellout for the first time in its 20-year history. Officials 
expect 30,000 a day at first major golf event in Iowa since the 
1963 U.S. Amateur. ... Brandie Burton had surgery on her right 
shoulder to remove excess scar tissue and won't be able to defend 
her title in the du Maurier Classic the last weekend in July. ... 
Barry Cheesman has played every PGA Tour event for which he has 
been eligible this year, a total of 15. ... Jim Furyk will be host 
of the Exelon Invitational Golf Tournament on Sept. 13 at Wyncote 
Golf Club in Oxford, Pa., to benefit the Junior Achievement of 
Delaware Valley. Davis Love III and Justin Leonard are among those 
expected to play. ... Nick Price is playing New Orleans this week 
for the first time since 1987. 
</P>
