<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coppola Teams With Nostradamus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Please mention Francis Ford Coppola  
prominently in connection with ``First Wave,'' urges Chris 
Brancato, creator of the new Sci-Fi Channel series about alien 
invaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider it done. Coppola, the series' executive producer,  
certainly is a name worth noting. Let's toss in another: 
Nostradamus, a guy who could have made a killing in the psychic hot 
line business and whose ancient writings are central to ``First 
Wave.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But what viewers might find more intriguing is a number, 66,  
which is the number of episodes the Sci-Fi Channel has ordered. 
Become attached to ``First Wave'' and you can feel reasonably 
secure it will be around for at least three seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	That in itself is practically science fiction when it comes to  
the TV business, in which networks increasingly buy as few episodes 
as possible and bail out as quickly as possible if a show isn't an 
overnight hit. 
</P>
<P>
	The commitment to ``First Wave'' is part of Sci-Fi Channel's  
increased emphasis on original shows, said Bonnie Hammer, senior 
vice president for programming. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven Spielberg is producing a 20-hour alien-abduction  
miniseries called ``Taken,'' with a reported budget of at least $40 
million, set for late 2000. ``Farscape,'' an outer space series 
from Jim Henson Co. and Hallmark Entertainment, began in March. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the past number of years, the channel's done very well,''  
said Hammer. ``But with this new regime since (Barry) Diller's 
taken over, a lot of money is going into the channel to grow it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Diller is chairman of Sci-Fi Channel parent company USA Networks  
Inc., which came under his control in 1997 when his HSN Inc. (owner 
of Home Shopping Network) bought most of Universal Studios' TV 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Brancato has no qualms about playing second fiddle to Hollywood  
godfathers like Diller and Coppola. ``I'm happy to sacrifice 
myself,'' he said, a contented beneficiary of their celebrity. 
</P>
<P>
	Make no mistake, however; ``First Wave'' is his baby.  
</P>
<P>
	The series (which debuted in March and airs 10 p.m. EDT Friday)  
stars Sebastian Spence as Cade Foster, a reformed burglar whose 
staid life is shattered when he discovers undercover aliens are 
preparing Earth for a massive invasion. 
</P>
<P>
	Foster also learns he has survived grueling experiments aimed at  
testing the strength of the human spirit. Now he's on the run from 
the invaders and from the authorities, who want him for the murder 
of his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	The murder, of course, was the aliens' doing. Besides, any guy  
named Cade has to be a true-blue hero. 
</P>
<P>
	Guiding Foster are the predictions of Nostradamus, the  
16th-century physician and occultist whose vision of an invasion 
from above is, in ``First Wave,'' interpreted as warning of an 
alien attack. 
</P>
<P>
	The series is part ``The Fugitive,'' part ``The X-Files.''  
Fortunately, ``First Wave'' has a bit of the dark humor found in 
the latter, leavening what could otherwise be a ponderous brew. 
</P>
<P>
	In one scene, for example, an alien notes that a weak Earthling  
lasted a mere two weeks under testing; he was a tobacco industry 
lobbyist. 
</P>
<P>
	Brancato acknowledges that aliens vs. us is hardly new to  
science fiction. 
</P>
<P>
	``The aliens are here, they want to take over -- yeah, yeah,  
yeah. You've heard that a thousand times before,'' he said. ``What 
I think makes our show different is the fact that they're here as 
an advance team. The second wave, which would be a full-scale 
military launch by these aliens, is something they're not even sure 
they can win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In trying to save his species, Foster gets to learn about it as  
well, ``which is what you want to be doing in a sci-fi show,'' 
Brancato said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have episodes about greed and about people's desire to  
get younger and all sorts of fun, 'Twilight Zone'-type of premises 
and subjects,'' he said. ``So if the aliens are doing an experiment 
trying to rile up skinheads in some mountain community, we can put 
Cade Foster in that situation and explore that aspect of 
humanity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brancato's credits include an ``X-Files'' script and the film  
``Species II,'' as well as two movies that are not sci-fi, 
``Hoodlum'' and the upcoming 1960s drama ``Weathermen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adding gloss to the series is the dishy Spence, a Canadian who  
appeared in the films ``The Boys of St. Vincent'' (1994) and 
``Firestorm'' (1998), and the Showtime series ``Fast Track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``First Wave'' had an unusual beginning. It was sold overseas by  
co-producer Pearson Television International before it found a U.S. 
home, and began airing last year in Canada, South Africa and a 
half-dozen other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``The business model behind the show is groundbreaking in some  
respects,'' Brancato said. ``The foreign potential allowed a 
company to go ahead and make it without securing a U.S. broadcaster 
in advance. We were making the show come hell or high water even 
if, in the worst-case scenario, it was never even shown here.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	ANCIENT ART: Centuries before European explorers ventured out to  
sea, Polynesians had sailed to the far corners of the Pacific. The 
resurgence of this ancient seagoing tradition is explored in 
``Wayfinders: A Pacific Odyssey,'' 10 p.m. EDT Thursday, May 6, on 
PBS (check local listings). Gail K. Evenari's film follows a 
community of Pacific Islanders as they build traditional canoes, 
learn how to navigate by the stars and embark on a 2,000-mile 
voyage. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org  

</P>
</TEXT>
