<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disaster Declaration After Tornadoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton acted swiftly today to  
declare 11 Oklahoma counties and one county in Kansas disaster 
areas, a move that he said would help in ``speeding the way for 
federal aid'' to areas damaged by tornadoes. 
</P>
<P>
	A White House official said Clinton would travel to Oklahoma  
City on Saturday to review the destruction. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the most powerful tornadoes ever recorded swept  
through these states last night,'' Clinton said today. ``Whole 
communities have been leveled. ... A lot of our fellow Americans 
have had everything taken from them in those two states, and I know 
they will be in your prayers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating had requested the federal emergency  
declaration in a letter delivered to the White House overnight. The 
president approved that request this morning and acted this morning 
to facilitate relief to Sedgwick County in Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, also dispatched James Lee Witt, head of the Federal  
Emergency Management Agency, to Oklahoma City this morning and 
released a statement: 
</P>
<P>
	The designated Oklahoma counties are: Caddo, Cleveland, Creek,  
Grady, McClain, Oklahoma, Kingfisher, Lincoln, Logan, Pottawatomie 
and Tulsa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
