<DOCNO> APW19990504.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 16:53:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates' Kendall Calls `5-0-5-0' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Jason Kendall's ``5-0-5-0'' is one of the most  
unusual batting lines in a box score. 
</P>
<P>
	Kendall's performance Monday night against San Francisco marked  
only the eighth time since 1970 a major league player had at least 
five hits in a game without scoring or driving a run. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Monday, the last player to do it was Jeff Blauser of  
Atlanta on June 10, 1996, against the New York Mets. The last 
Pirates player to do it was Matty Alou against Hall of Famer 
pitcher Juan Marichal of the Giants on Aug. 19, 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Kent of the Giants also had five hits Monday, but he had  
five RBIs and scored twice while becoming the 19th player in 
franchise history to hit for the cycle. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates' 9-8 win was only their second victory in the last  
92 games they trailed entering the ninth inning. The Pirates, who 
trailed 8-5, hadn't erased a three-run deficit in the ninth inning 
since July 22, 1993, when they trailed 7-4 before scoring four 
times to beat the Atlanta Braves 8-7. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time NL players on opposing teams had five hits  
in a nine-inning game since Johnny Bench of the Reds went 5-for-6 
and Deron Johnson of the Philadelphia Phillies was 5-for-6 in a 
19-17 Cincinnati victory on Aug. 3, 1969. 
</P>
<P>
	Kendall said it might have been the Pirates' most exciting game  
since the 10-inning no-hitter by Cordova and Ricardo Rincon against 
the Houston Astros in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of the best I've ever played in,'' he said. ``More  
than anything else, it gives us a lot of confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It lets you know you have guys who can get big hits for you,''  
Pirates manager Gene Lamont said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates already have won four times in their final at-bat;  
they had only eight such victories last season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
