<HEADLINE> N.Korea Soccer Team To Train in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- To prepare for their first appearance in the  
Women's World Cup, the North Korean team will train in northern New 
Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Michael F. Coyne, president of Evergreen Sports  
Management in Cleveland, said Tuesday the squad will arrive the 
first week of June and stay at the Legends Resort and County Club 
in Vernon. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not yet know if the team would have any public  
appearances in New Jersey, but said it might stage an exhibition 
and youth clinic in Canton, Ohio, before continuing west for its 
first game, June 20 against Nigeria in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	The team may want to limit its exposure for a competitive  
advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one really knows that much about the team,'' Coyne said.  
``They haven't played that much outside of North Korea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 16-nation tournament begins June 19 with two games at Giants  
Stadium East Rutherford, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Korean delegation includes 28 players and coaches,  
plus several others Coyne believes are ``trainers and 
administrative people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did not think the North Koreans were bringing security  
officers to prevent defections from the closed Communist society. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've never expressed a concern about that,'' Coyne said.  
</P>
<P>
	Although many in the delegation are probably making their first  
trip to the United States, Coyne said, ``They have not expressed a 
desire to do any touring at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sussex County site was chosen at the suggestion of the  
Korean Businessmen's Federation of America, which knew Coyne from 
his work with Michael Ri, a 7-foot-9 North Korean basketball player 
who played recently in Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	A federation representative was not available for comment  
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey has a sizeable Korean population, concentrated in the  
north in Bergen County. 
</P>
</TEXT>
