<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 23:05:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MLS Yellow Card Flurry Explained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It was a matter of styles, not disrespect for  
American soccer, that led Scottish referee Stuart Dougal to issue 
11 yellow cards and one red in Saturday night's MLS match between 
Chicago and D.C. United. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some referees have the forte of being good player managers,  
others go to the card right away,'' MLS vice president of game 
operations Joe Machnik said Tuesday. ``The fact that Mr. Dougal 
issued 10 cards I think showed he is a very technical referee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's a lack of respect at all.''  
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't the opinion of D.C. United president and general  
manager Kevin Payne, who verbally lashed out at Dougal and MLS 
after his team's 3-2 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't understand why we need to go 4,000 miles to get a  
referee that poor,'' Payne said. ``This referee clearly has no 
respect for our league and he should be sent home. I'll be happy to 
pay for his flight home. ... If he ever did this in Scotland, he'd 
never referee again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those remarks and others earned Payne a $15,000 fine from MLS  
commissioner Doug Logan, who called the comments ``intemperate'' 
and ``inappropriate''. 
</P>
<P>
	Logan, who said he spoke to Payne by telephone on Tuesday and  
received e-mail from the D.C. United boss, said Washington's 
executive apologized and was remorseful for his comments and 
actions. 
</P>
<P>
	Logan did not say whether he would consider reducing the fine.  
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's game was the last of three officiated by Dougal, the  
fourth foreign official to come to the United States to referee 
games as part of MLS' referee exchange program. 
</P>
<P>
	Comments by some foreign players and officials not affiliated  
with MLS have convinced several MLS officials that many outside the 
United States don't respect the league or its level of play. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago coach Bob Bradley questioned the red card issued to D.C.  
United defender Brian Kamler in the 16th minute. While praising the 
exchange program, Bradley chided Dougal by saying Saturday's game 
wasn't its best example. 
</P>
<P>
	In his three games, Dougal, a referee since 1985 and a FIFA  
referee in 1996, issued 26 yellow cards plus the one red. Twice in 
Saturday's match he yellow-carded a player twice, resulting in 
their ejection. 
</P>
<P>
	His average of 8.6 yellow cards a game is nearly triple the MLS  
number of cautions per game (3.16) over its first three-plus 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, it is not the Bundesliga, it's not the Serie A, but the  
foreign referees have a lot of respect for MLS, especially for the 
technical ability of the players,'' U.S. Soccer Federation director 
of officials Esse Baharmast said. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. federation on Tuesday issued a statement distancing  
itself from Payne, a member of the federation's board of directors. 
The federation expressed support for the exchange program, which 
also has seen MLS referees officiate in Spain, Japan and the United 
Arab Emirates, with another trip to Scotland scheduled for later 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``No doubt, part of the challenge of starting a league was that  
this was their game, not our game,'' Logan said. ``There is a 
significant amount of skepticism. 
</P>
<P>
	``As time goes on, we're gaining more and more respect. Part of  
the growth process is gaining respect. I don't see a lack of 
respect from (the foreign) referees. The comments we're getting 
have been pretty complimentary.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
