<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Aid for Tornado Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal emergency and Red Cross workers are on  
the scene, with more on the way, to assist the victims of the 
tornadoes in Kansas and Oklahoma. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Emergency Management Agency ``started sending people  
once it became obvious how serious it is,'' Deputy Director Mike 
Walker said. Director James Lee Witt is there and FEMA will 
coordinate the work of 27 federal agencies and the Red Cross, 
Walker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Darren Irby said the Red Cross has set up 10 emergency  
shelters in Oklahoma and three in Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	It has also sent a dozen emergency response vehicles to provide  
food for tornado victims in the two states. Each of these vehicles 
is capable of providing 5,000 meals a day, Irby said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Cross is also sending damage assessment teams who go  
street by street to determine how large the recovery operation is 
going to be and what additional help is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker said FEMA has deployed teams to assist victims obtain  
temporary housing and begin work toward long-term recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The Small Business Administration will provide both business and  
home loans, he said, and the Public Health Service is sending a 
portable morgue from Rockville, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	The Defense Department will airlift needed supplies, Walker  
said, such as food and bottled water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
