<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 12:45:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kodak CFO Harry Kavetas Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Eastman Kodak Co. chief financial officer  
Harry L. Kavetas, who helped engineer nearly 20,000 job cuts at the 
photography company to counter Japanese gains in the U.S. market, 
died Tuesday at age 61. 
</P>
<P>
	Kavetas suffered an apparent heart attack at his home.  
</P>
<P>
	A longtime executive at International Business Machines Corp.,  
Kavetas took a brief early retirement at the end of 1993 after 
being passed over for a top post by new IBM chief executive Louis 
V. Gerstner. 
</P>
<P>
	He was hired as Kodak's chief financial officer in February  
1994, filling a post left vacant since an avid cost-cutter, 
Christopher Steffen, quit nine months earlier in a 
headline-grabbing dispute over financial policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Steffen's departure led to a management shakeup and a new  
strategy to slash overhead by laying off 10,000 workers. Kavetas 
took over with much of that new policy in place, which was aimed at 
defending Kodak's mainstay photographic businesses from assault by 
Japanese nemesis Fuji. 
</P>
<P>
	But in 1997, Kavetas and his boss, CEO George Fisher, resorted  
to even deeper cutbacks when Fuji slashed film prices in the United 
States and grabbed market share on Kodak's dominant home turf. 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of this year, Kodak expects to trim more than $1  
billion in costs by eliminating almost one-fifth of its worldwide 
payroll of 100,500. The company has seen a sharp rebound in sales 
and profits in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	``Harry believed in Kodak and he was absolutely dedicated to his  
role and to the revitalization of the company,'' Fisher said. ``We 
will miss him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kavetas joined IBM in 1961, was appointed chief of IBM Credit in  
1986 and was elected an IBM vice president in 1989. Under his 
management, IBM Credit grew from $5.7 billion in assets and $118 
million in profits to $10 billion in assets and $220 million in 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	At Kodak, Kavetas was appointed executive vice president in  
September 1994 and elected to the board of directors in May 1997. 
Kodak named his deputy, Jesse J. Greene Jr., as acting chief 
financial officer. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Springfield, Ill., Kavetas held a bachelor's degree  
in finance and economics from the University of Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his widow, Sue; three children, Betsy, Kathy  
and James; and three grandchildren, Jimmy, William and Ellen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 05:49:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gumbel Set To Return to Morning TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bryant Gumbel's farewell to morning television  
was apparently short-lived. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years after leaving as co-host of NBC's ``Today'' show,  
Gumbel is expected to take the helm of CBS's last-place morning 
show, ``This Morning.'' The network plans to announce the decision 
at a news conference later today, network executives speaking on 
condition of anonymity said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS is not likely to reveal a co-host for Gumbel. Network  
executives have reportedly considered ABC's Elizabeth Vargas and 
Deborah Norville, who was briefly Gumbel's partner on ``Today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gumbel has largely been off the air since the cancellation of  
his newsmagazine, ``Public Eye with Bryant Gumbel,'' last year. He 
left ``Today'' after 15 years in 1997 to sign a lucrative contract 
with CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	His agent, Ed Hookstratten, did not immediately return a call  
for comment on Monday. CBS would not discuss its news conference 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``This Morning'' has run a consistent third in the ratings  
behind ``Today'' and ABC's ``Good Morning America.'' The ABC show 
raised the stakes in the morning news competition earlier this year 
when it brought Charles Gibson and Diane Sawyer in as temporary 
hosts. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS also intends to unveil plans today to build a new storefront  
studio for ``This Morning.'' It will be similar to the Rockefeller 
Center studio used by ``Today,'' the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ratings for ``Today'' blossomed after it began televising from a  
studio with a window to the street in Rockefeller Center. ABC 
subsequently began building a Times Square studio, and CBS hopes to 
use space on Fifth Avenue near Central Park. It is expected to be 
ready in late fall or early winter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
