<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	More punishing severe thunderstorms -- including a few strong  
tornadoes -- were expected over parts of the South again today while 
rain clouds hung over most of the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Low pressure was expected to continue drifting across New  
England, spiraling moisture and clouds from the Northwest to 
Pennsylvania. Temperatures were forecast to dip below seasonable 
averages. 
</P>
<P>
	To the west, a cloudy system moving over the central Plains was  
forecast to head into the western Great Lakes and along the 
Mississippi Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain, hail and possible thunderstorms were expected across areas  
of Wisconsin to Louisiana, and filling into areas of Michigan, the 
Mississippi Valley and Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	A cold front extending from the Dakotas through northern Texas  
was forecast to head eastward, pushing thunderstorms into the 
Dakotas, Oklahoma, Louisiana and Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Several powerful tornadoes roared across Oklahoma and Kansas on  
Monday, killing dozens of people and bringing destruction to cities 
and small communities alike. 
</P>
<P>
	Scattered showers were forecast across much of the north-central  
states again today. The western areas of Kansas through west Texas 
could escape the worst rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Early today, several lines of storms were moving through the  
Dallas-Fort Worth area. Numerous power outages were reported as 
high winds toppled power lines and lightning struck lines. 
</P>
<P>
	A trough of low pressure was forecast to continue to hang along  
the Rocky Mountain states through the upper Southwest. Cloudy skies 
were dawning over Idaho and Montana, through Wyoming, Colorado, and 
upper New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Pacific Northwest, to northern California, partly to  
mostly cloudy skies were expected. Rain was likely in Washington 
and Oregon. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature in the continental United States on  
Monday was 82 degrees at Kingsville, Texas. The low was 28 degrees 
at Mullen Pass, Idaho, and Berlin, N.H. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast to reach the 50s along the Pacific  
Northwest, the Rockies, Dakotas, Nebraska and Kansas; the 60s and 
70s from New York through Pennsylvania to New England, and the 
Great Lakes through the Ohio Valley; the 80s in the Southeast, 
Arizona, California and Oklahoma; and some 90s in southern portions 
of Texas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
