<DOCNO> APW19990504.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 08:45:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CBS Brings Gumbel to Mornings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bryant Gumbel's farewell to morning television  
was short-lived. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS announced today that Gumbel, host of the ``Today'' show on  
NBC for 15 years before leaving in 1997, will return to the time 
slot this fall, teaming with a former ``Today'' executive and 
broadcasting from a new storefront studio in Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	Gumbel will face the challenge of lifting a show that has been  
the doormat for decades in the morning TV ratings race. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Friedman, who was executive producer of ``Today'' twice  
during Gumbel's time as host, will run the revamped ``This 
Morning'' when it debuts in November. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS is also taking a leaf from NBC in announcing plans to build  
a studio in the General Motors Building on Fifth Avenue in 
Manhattan. ``Today'' assumed its dominant role in the ratings when 
it opened a studio with windows to the street at Rockefeller Center 
in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although I never planned on making a return to morning  
television, I think it's where I belong and I know it's where I'm 
most comfortable,'' Gumbel said in a statement today. 
</P>
<P>
	Gumbel signed a $5 million contract with CBS two years ago but  
was a man without a job when his newsmagazine, ``Public Eye with 
Bryant Gumbel,'' was canceled last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today'' continues to dominate in the increasingly lucrative  
morning television race, and ABC appeared to stop its decline in 
January when it named Charles Gibson and Diane Sawyer as co-hosts. 
ABC is building a new studio for ``Good Morning America'' in Times 
Square, but it's not clear how long Gibson and Sawyer will continue 
on the show. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS did not name a co-anchor for Gumbel. Network executives have  
reportedly considered ABC's Elizabeth Vargas and Deborah Norville, 
who was briefly Gumbel's partner on ``Today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was no word on the future of Jane Robelot and Mark McEwen,  
the current hosts of ``This Morning.'' Al Berman, the show's 
current executive producer, will keep his job but work for 
Friedman. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not naive about the difficulty of the challenges that lie  
ahead, but I am enthused about the extent of CBS's commitment to 
what Steve and I want to do and optimistic about our future,'' 
Gumbel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Friedman has been manager of CBS's New York City station for the  
past two years. He was executive producer of ``Today'' from 1979 to 
1987 and again from 1993 to 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
