<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wall St. Firm Chief Admits Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The president of a Wall Street currency trading  
firm has pleaded guilty to federal charges that he defrauded 
investors of more than $1 million by pocketing their money rather 
than investing it. 
</P>
<P>
	Ian Fulton Roberts, 31, of Manhattan, admitted to U.S. District  
Magistrate Judge Andrew J. Peck Monday that he lied to customers of 
his company, Fulton Whitney Inc., telling them he would invest 
their money. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he spent it on himself and on payroll and expenses for  
his business, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts, who was arrested a year ago, pleaded guilty to one  
count of mail fraud, which could carry a sentence of up to five 
years in prison and a fine of up to $2 million, along with 
mandatory restitution. 
</P>
<P>
	He will be sentenced on Aug. 3.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
