<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Co. To Purchase Wang Global </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Wang Global, the pioneering computer maker whose  
fortunes swung from industry powerhouse to bankruptcy, is being 
acquired by Dutch company Getronics NV for $2 billion in cash. 
</P>
<P>
	The union with Getronics will form the largest computer services  
company in Europe and one of the five largest in the world, company 
officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company is expected to have annual revenues of  
about $5 billion, with 33,000 employees and operations in more than 
44 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the agreement, Getronics will purchase Wang for  
$29.25 a share, as well as warrants, options and other securities. 
Shares of Wang surged to $28.62 1/2, up $3.12 1/2, in trading on the 
Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	Wang peaked in the mid 1980s when it manufactured word  
processors and closet-sized ``minicomputers,'' but it stumbled 
badly later in the decade when it failed to negotiate the computing 
world's transition to modern networked and desktop computers. 
</P>
<P>
	The company was founded in 1951 by An Wang, a Chinese immigrant  
who came to the United States to earn a Ph.D. at Harvard 
University. Then known as Wang Laboratories, the firm began with 
Wang's $600 in savings. 
</P>
<P>
	The company went public in 1967 to finance its expansion in the  
calculator market, but sold that business in the mid-1970s to begin 
making word processors and minicomputers. Wang sales rose from $543 
million in 1980 to $2.4 billion in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	But as personal computers became the workplace standard and the  
company began to slide, An Wang announced a host of new products -- 
many of which did not exist -- in an effort to stem the tide of 
customers switching to other technologies. 
</P>
<P>
	The company lost credibility with customers, and it lost $1.9  
billion from 1989 to 1992, when it declared bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	An Wang died from cancer of the esophagus in 1990.  
</P>
<P>
	Wang emerged from Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization in 1993  
with chairman and CEO Joseph Tucci at the helm, and reinvented 
itself as a computer services provider, setting up, maintaining and 
helping companies run computer networks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Billerica-based company, about 17 miles north of Boston, now  
has annualized revenues of $3.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Getronics, based in Amsterdam, currently has no presence in the  
United States. It has about 11,000 employees and provides 
information and computer services in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Getronics had $1.65 billion in revenue in 1998.  
</P>
<P>
	A person close to the deal said talks began last year to merge  
the two companies. The source, who would only speak on condition of 
anonymity, said Getronics was looking to expand globally so it 
could continue to provide services for companies that are growing 
increasingly large and more complicated. 
</P>
<P>
	Wang, whose stock had been trading sluggishly in the $20 range  
in recent months, was hoping to increase share prices, said the 
person, adding that Getronics executives believe earnings will rise 
at Wang in the next two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Wang bought Olsy Group, the computer services  
division of Italy's Olivetti SpA in a $390 billion deal. The 
transaction left Olivetti, currently involved in a massive bid to 
take over Telecom Italia SpA, with about 17 percent of Wang's 
stock. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the merger with Getronics came as Wang announced a net  
loss for the first quarter. The company posted a net loss of $57.7 
million, or $1.25 per share, on revenues of $789 million for the 
three months ended March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Whitney, an analyst with Boston-based Advest Inc.,  
called the combination a good match. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a nice mix of services and there is not a lot of  
overlap,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitney said he thought Getronics made a wise investment by  
acquiring Wang. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think (Wang) reinvented themselves with a very good strategy  
focused on providing those services,'' Whitney said. ``I have them 
scheduled to turn a profit next quarter. I think they've turned the 
corner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's deal is subject to regulatory and Wang shareholder  
approval. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
