<HEADLINE> Flea Market Rembrandt Etchings Sold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- A woman who bought an old book for  
$1 at a Netherlands flea market found etchings inside by Dutch 
master Rembrandt that sold for $50,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman bought the book last month in the central Dutch city  
of Utrecht. She found the etchings pressed between the pages along 
with a third etching by one of Rembrandt's students. 
</P>
<P>
	Cashing in on her good fortune, she sold Rembrandt's ``The  
pastry cook'' for $30,000 and ``Beggar with woman'' for $20,000 to 
an anonymous German collector, the Dutch daily Algemeen Dagblad 
reported Tuesday. The student's etching went to the same 
Berlin-based dealer for $5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	But the lucky bargain hunter, who was not identified, reportedly  
wanted even more. 
</P>
<P>
	``The family from Utrecht who found the etches were not  
satisfied with the $55,000,'' art dealer Toon Wildeboer told 
Algemeen Dagblad. ``When I asked for my 3 percent commission they 
said I could get a beating instead.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
