<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 11:45:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tony Nominations Too Late for Some </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- What happens now to the Broadway plays and  
musicals that did -- and did not -- receive Tony Award nominations? 
</P>
<P>
	For some like ``Parade,'' which got nine nominations Monday,  
more than any other show, it won't make any difference. The musical 
about a real-life lynching in Georgia in 1915 closed in February 
after a short run. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're thrilled, but a little sad,'' said Bernard Gersten,  
executive producer at Lincoln Center Theater, which helped present 
``Parade.'' ``We know it is good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some shows gave up without a fight. ``Marlene,'' a look at film  
legend Marlene Dietrich, received two nominations including one for 
its star Sian Phillips. Yet it threw in the towel on Sunday, one 
day before the nominations came out. 
</P>
<P>
	For other shows, such as ``Not About Nightingales,'' ``The  
Lonesome West,'' and ``Side Man,'' still running and struggling at 
the box office, there's hope for a boost in ticket sales. 
</P>
<P>
	All three gained best-play nominations and the impetus to carry  
on until at least June 6, when the winners are announced. 
``Nightingales,'' written by Tennessee Williams in 1938 but never 
done on Broadway until now, received a lift. The prison drama got 
six nominations including actor (Corin Redgrave) and director 
(Trevor Nunn) nods. 
</P>
<P>
	The other best-play nominee ``Closer'' will have to sell its  
status as a candidate for best play and not its actors. None of its 
four performers, including Natasha Richardson, got a nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	For ``Amy's View,'' the star -- Oscar winner Judi Dench -- is the  
thing, not the play. She received a nomination, but the play 
didn't. Not that it matters. ``Amy's View'' is a hot ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	So are the season's two big revivals -- ``Death of a Salesman''  
and ``The Iceman Cometh.'' They are going head-to-head for the 
revival award and in the actor category where ``Salesman's'' Brian 
Dennehy faces ``Iceman's'' Kevin Spacey. It's a toss-up as to who 
will win -- but that makes for an exciting horse race. And tickets 
even harder to get. 
</P>
<P>
	Question marks hover over shows that didn't get major  
nominations or none at all. ``The Weir,'' Conor McPherson's small 
Irish pub drama, was blanked. Now it will have fight for attention 
against plays that have nominations to sell. The same goes for 
``The Gershwins' Fascinating Rhythm,'' which wasn't expecting any 
musical nominations -- and didn't get any. 
</P>
<P>
	``Footloose'' also failed to get a best-musical nod, which means  
no production number on the Tony telecast. The four minutes of 
national television exposure will benefit ``Fosse,'' a celebration 
of choreographer Bob Fosse; ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' 
another revue, and ``The Civil War,'' composer Frank Wildhorn's pop 
history pageant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
