<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dismisses EU Report on Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A European Union report that contends a growth  
hormone in American beef may cause cancer is an attempt to delay 
trade obligations to lift a ban on hormone beef, U.S. officials 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	``The supposed new claims are nothing but misleading  
allegations,'' said Peter Scher, America's trade negotiator on 
agricultural matters, calling the report a ``blatant attempt'' by 
the EU to delay abiding by its trade obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the EU does not lift this ban, we will retaliate this  
summer,'' Scher told a Senate subcommittee Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a report released Monday, the EU's Scientific Committee on  
Veterinary Measures said the hormone 17 beta-oestradiol -- one of 
six growth hormones in American beef -- ``has to be considered as a 
complete carcinogen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It exerts both tumor initiating and tumor promoting effects,''  
the report said. ``In plain language, this means that even small 
additional doses of residues of this hormone in meat, arising from 
its use as a growth promoter in cattle, has an inherent risk of 
causing cancer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was inadequate data to make a definitive finding on other  
growth hormones used in U.S. beef, the scientific committee said. 
But it said exposure to small levels of residues in meat and meat 
products ``carries risks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman and U.S. Trade Representative  
Charlene Barshefsky said the EU had issued ``yet another misleading 
report.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It repeats the same unsubstantiated arguments that the EU has  
already made before the (World Trade Organization) panel of 
experts, which were flatly rejected by the panel,'' they said in a 
joint statement. ``The issue is the EU's refusal to comply with the 
WTO rulings and its unwillingness to honor its international 
obligations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	EU spokesman Gerard Kiely countered Tuesday that the United  
States is wrong to criticize the report before reading the entire 
document, which will be made available later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unwise to dismiss scientific evidence. The United States  
should wait for the full report,'' Kiely said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 90 percent of American cattle producers feed hormones  
approved by the Food and Drug Administration to cattle to make them 
grow faster and bigger. 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO ruled a year ago that the EU ban on hormone-treated beef  
was illegal and must be lifted by May 13. It said the EU's ban was 
not supported by the proper risk analysis. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1989, the U.S. has exported only hormone-free beef to the  
EU because of the ban. The U.S. industry has put the lost export 
sales at $500 million annually. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration is threatening to impose 100 percent  
tariffs on more than $900 million worth of European products in 
retaliation for the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of importers have argued that certain products should be  
excluded from the tariffs because of economic harm to their 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration in late May or early June will release the  
final list of goods that will be subject to the punitive tariffs, 
Scher said. 
</P>
<P>
	EU spokesman Pietro Petrucci has said the 20-member European  
Commission will examine the scientific committee's report and 
decide by May 13 whether to ask the WTO for an extension of the 
ban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
