<HEADLINE> Lisa Ling Wins Seat on 'The View' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After seven years in high schools -- lots of them  
-- Lisa Ling will be getting some postgraduate work in television. 
</P>
<P>
	The California native was announced as the winner Monday in the  
highly public competition for the fifth seat on daytime TV's ``The 
View.'' The 26-year-old replaces Debbie Matenopolous, who was let 
go at the end of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ling's the ``young one,'' with her under-age 30 status a chief  
qualification. She joins the ABC show's other members Joy Behar, 
Star Jones, Meredith Vieira and Barbara Walters. 
</P>
<P>
	She's worked for the past seven years on Channel One, the  
satellite news service beamed into high schools and middle schools 
across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Ling, who came onto the show's set Monday trailing a marching  
band, says her toughest task now is to find an apartment in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	She beat out two other finalists: Fox sports anchor Lauren  
Sanchez and Rachel Campos, a former cast member of MTV's ``Real 
World.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
