<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed higher across the  
board Tuesday on the back of another record rally overnight on Wall 
Street, with the key index in Bangkok soaring 10 percent to its 
highest level in more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese financial markets remained closed Tuesday for a  
national holiday. The markets, which will also be closed Wednesday, 
reopen Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai share prices soared as investor sentiment was bolstered by  
Moody's Investors Service's decision to change its outlook for 
Thailand's debt ratings to positive from stable, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stock Exchange of Thailand, or SET, index surged 46.40  
points, or 10.3 percent to 505.75, its highest level since March, 
19, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia shares closed sharply higher for a second day, boosted  
by positive domestic economic news and Wall Street's 
record-breaking performance overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index rose 4.75 percent,  
or 24.883 points, to a 15-month high of 548.241. On Monday, the 
index had surged almost 6 percent after the government said 
Indonesia's economy grew 1.34 percent in the first three months of 
1999 from the previous quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta bourse also got a boost from the Dow Jones  
Industrial Average's 2.1 percent surge to 11,014.69 Monday, a 
record high and the fastest move between 1,000-point milestones in 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	In Taipei, shares prices also soared in reaction to overnight  
gains on Wall Street. The benchmark Weighted Stock Price Index rose 
204.78 points, or 2.8 percent, to 7,588.04. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwanese investors take their cues from U.S. stock markets  
because of the close manufacturing ties between Taiwanese companies 
and those in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysian shares continued to surge following an interest rate  
cut on Monday and overnight gains in U.S. stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange's Composite Index rose 20.35  
points, or 3 percent, to 698.23. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 222.62 points,  
or 1.7 percent, closing at 13,559.69. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said share prices opened sharply higher, with the key  
index soaring more than 350 points in early trading in reaction to 
record gains on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong shares fell back slightly later in the session on  
selective profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed higher. The  
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 9.63 points, or 0.4 percent, 
to 2,266.90. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher, with the main index  
posting its strongest finish in 21 months in reaction to Wall 
Street's record gains Monday, traders said. The 30-company 
Philippine Stock Exchange Index, or PSE Index, rose 18.10 points, 
or 0.7 percent, to 2,464.84. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed higher as resource stocks  
chalked up another session of hefty gains. The All Ordinaries Index 
rose 9.4 points, or 0.3 percent, to 3,083.9. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed higher, boosted by sharp gains  
overnight on Wall Street. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index 
rose 14.64 points, or 1.9 percent, to 771.17. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed mostly higher. The benchmark  
Straits Times Index rose 33.66 points, or 1.8 percent, to 1,931.90. 
</P>
</TEXT>
