<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 00:42:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury: Execute California Murderer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- One of the longest and costliest murder  
cases in California history came to a close when a jury recommended 
the death penalty for a man convicted of killing 11 people in a 
sex-and-torture spree at a mountain cabin in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fight is over,'' said Sharon Sellitto, whose brother was  
believed to be one of the victims. ``We won. I can't believe it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The same jury that in February convicted Charles Ng of killing  
11 people in the grisly murders recommended the death sentence 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	After a widely publicized manhunt, Ng's legal case hung in limbo  
for years while he first fought extradition from Canada, then filed 
a series of motions that lengthened the case. He hired and fired 
attorneys and for a time represented himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Ng's lawyer said the 38-year-old defendant virtually wrote his  
own ticket to a death sentence when he decided to testify in the 
guilt phase of his trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``When our client decided against our wishes to take the witness  
stand we felt tactically that wasn't a particularly wise choice on 
his part,'' said attorney William G. Kelley. 
</P>
<P>
	Before that, Kelley had focused jurors' attention on Leonard  
Lake, the psychopathic killer who recruited Ng as his lieutenant in 
a mid-1980s siege of sexual torture, bondage and killing that 
reduced victims to charred fragments buried around a Sierra 
foothills cabin. 
</P>
<P>
	Ng denied killing anyone and said he didn't know Lake planned to  
kill. But jurors watched graphic videotapes in which Lake and Ng 
were seen tormenting bound women. In one of them, a woman pleads 
for her baby and Ng coldly replies that the baby is ``sleeping like 
a rock.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The defense suggested during the trial that Lake, who committed  
suicide in 1985, always intended to make Ng the fall guy. 
</P>
<P>
	Orange County Superior Court Judge John J. Ryan can accept the  
jury's decision or reduce the sentence to life in prison without 
parole. Kelley said he expects the judge to accept the jury's 
recommendation at the June 29 sentencing. 
</P>
<P>
	The final cost to taxpayers is expected to reach $14 million,  
according to unofficial estimates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 01:32:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AOL Exec Dropped Few Hints of Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A blunt-spoken executive from America Online  
described on the witness stand last fall his company's previous 
failed efforts to forge an alliance with Netscape, the Internet 
software pioneer. 
</P>
<P>
	But what is emerging publicly for the first time is the  
revelation that even as David Colburn was testifying in the 
Microsoft trial, AOL was again secretly negotiating with Netscape 
in a remarkable deal that weeks later coalesced into a $9.9 billion 
merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft disclosed Monday it will call Colburn, who appeared  
unshaven and wearing cowboy boots during earlier testimony, back to 
the trial as a hostile witness. He will be one of the six final 
witnesses during the upcoming rebuttal phase of the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft said it will press Colburn about the implications, if  
any, of AOL's extraordinary purchase of Netscape on both the 
high-tech industry and the trial. The case is expected to resume 
later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The government, in turn, said it will call Garry Norris, a  
former director at IBM's personal computer division, who negotiated 
Windows contracts with Microsoft and is expected to testify about 
the company's alleged bullying practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Colburn, four of the rebuttal witnesses already have  
appeared in the courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	But armed with information only recently made public about the  
merger, Microsoft will have pointed questions for Colburn. In court 
papers, lawyers indicated they will ask him about the 
``completeness and candor'' of his previous testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Netscape's former chief financial officer, Peter Currie,  
acknowledged last week in a deposition that talks with AOL began in 
late August, even though the sale wasn't publicly disclosed until 
late in November. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's now clear that Colburn dropped few hints about the  
pending purchase even as he was cross-examined over two days late 
in October -- during the peak of AOL's sensitive negotiations with 
Netscape. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft lawyer John Warden quizzed Colburn about AOL's  
previous attempts in late 1995 to combine forces against Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	Warden read e-mail to AOL from Netscape's co-founder, Marc  
Andreessen, proposing to ``use our unique respective strengths to 
go kick the (expletive) out of the beast from Redmond that wants to 
see us both dead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Is AOL still trying to do what Mr. Andreessen suggested be  
done to the beast from Redmond?'' Warden asked, almost 
prophetically. 
</P>
<P>
	Colburn demured: ``What do you mean specifically?'' Then, he  
added, ``I think what AOL is trying to do, from my perspective, is 
to compete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warden, apparently unaware of the secret talks going on outside  
the courtroom, didn't pursue the line of questioning. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft contends that the new AOL alliance illustrates that  
competition is thriving in the industry and that government 
intervention is unnecessary in such an important sector of the 
booming economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department and 19 states suing Microsoft say the  
deal is irrelevant to charges that the software giant illegally 
maintains a monopoly over the market for computer operating 
systems. 
</P>
<P>
	The government contends that Microsoft, for example, bullies the  
nation's computer makers with restrictions on the sale of Windows, 
and that it sets prices to reward its allies and punish its 
enemies. 
</P>
<P>
	But until Monday's announcement that Norris will testify, a  
curious hole in the government's case has been the lack in its 
lineup of witnesses from any of those computer companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft also will use testimony from Gordon Eubanks, who  
stepped down weeks ago as president and chief executive officer of 
Symantec Corp., which makes a popular anti-virus program and other 
software utilities that run using Microsoft's Windows operating 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	Eubanks, a longtime Microsoft ally, left to become president of  
Oblix Inc., a small computer automation company whose investors 
include Netscape and Novell Inc. -- some of Microsoft's biggest 
rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	Eubanks told The New York Times last year, ``Microsoft has done  
some bad things.'' But he argued that Microsoft's chairman, Bill 
Gates, is a victim of the trend toward tearing down successful 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said it also will call back Edward Felten, a  
Princeton University computer expert. 
</P>
<P>
	The other witnesses will include two economists who stumbled  
through parts of their earlier testimony, Richard Schmalensee, a 
dean at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and MIT 
economist Franklin Fisher. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
