<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Comcast in MediaOne Bidding War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With just two days before the deadline, Comcast  
Corp. is scrambling to put together a higher bid for MediaOne Group 
Inc., the Denver-based cable TV company that is at the heart of one 
of the biggest takeover battles in recent memory. 
</P>
<P>
	Comcast, the No. 3 cable company, has until midnight Thursday to  
beat a $54 billion bid from AT&AMP;T Corp., the long-distance phone 
company that broke up a $48 billion deal between Comcast and 
MediaOne. 
</P>
<P>
	MediaOne is the nation's fourth biggest cable provider. The  
fight for control of its 5 million U.S. cable subscribers and 8.9 
million overseas customers has drawn interest from technology 
titans like Microsoft Corp., America Online Inc., MCI WorldCom and 
even Paul Allen, co-founder of Microsoft, who is starting his own 
cable venture. 
</P>
<P>
	One possibility is that AT&AMP;T and Comcast may make a deal to  
avoid what could be a costly bidding war. The Wall Street Journal 
reported Tuesday night that the two companies have been talking 
about a deal in which Comcast would withdraw from the competition 
for MediaOne in exchange for obtaining 2 million additional cable 
subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	If Comcast does put together a bid, the most likely white knight  
is Microsoft, which is sitting on $22 billion in cash, and wants to 
make the software that will drive interactive television and 
high-speed Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft already has a $1 billion investment in Comcast, and a  
$213 million investment in MediaOne's RoadRunner unit, which offers 
high-speed Internet connections. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle-based software giant, which declined to comment, is  
playing both sides of the fence, negotiating at the same time with 
AT&AMP;T, according to a person familiar with the negotiations. If AT&AMP;T 
is successful in its bid for MediaOne, the long-distance company 
will get access to 60 percent of American homes with cable. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, Microsoft will side with the company that offers it  
the most power, the person said. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, which has long been dissatisfied with its stock  
price, is considering creating a separate stock to track the 
performance of its Internet operations as well as any cable 
investments it might make, the person said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the person added, this is just one of many options the  
company might pursue. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's shares fell $1.81 to $78.06 1/4 on the Nasdaq Stock  
Market, on a day when technology shares fell. 

</P>
</TEXT>
