<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Littleton Changes Rules for Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The classroom-clearing bomb threats, rumors  
and other scares that followed the Littleton, Colo., school 
shooting took their toll. Students spent hours standing outside in 
parking lots and football fields; SAT exams were postponed; some 
schools shut down altogether. 
</P>
<P>
	Apparently none of the threats in the week after the April 20  
Columbine High School shootings were substantiated. But schools 
took to heart what in another time might have been dismissed as 
annoying pranks. 
</P>
<P>
	Copycat threats typically appear about a week after the event  
that inspired them, officials say, but the scale of the Littleton 
attack has changed the rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, you will take every single kind of threat as if you know  
for certain it's going to occur because you don't have any 
choice,'' said Bruce Hunter of the American Association of School 
Administrators. 
</P>
<P>
	Schools nationwide are making the same call, even realizing  
they're at the mercy of copycats with empty threats. The student 
gunmen who shot to death 12 classmates and a teacher before killing 
themselves apparently had planted explosives at the 1,800-student 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some schools have been more sensitive about it, but when it  
comes to security measures there's no such thing as overreacting,'' 
said Deputy Sheriff Jesus Villahermosa of Pierce County, Wash., who 
advises schools on security issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Villahermosa said at least 14 people statewide were arrested  
last week for bomb threats to schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	--An Internet threat of a shooting Friday kept home all but 300  
of the 2,100 students at a suburban Phoenix high school. Students 
feared that the April 30 anniversary of Adolf Hitler's suicide 
would spark a shooting. The Columbine killers struck on Hitler's 
birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	--In Charlotte, N.C., classes and SAT testing at four schools  
were canceled Friday. Police spent the weekend sweeping middle and 
high schools to make sure campuses were safe. 
</P>
<P>
	--District of Columbia schools, which received three days of  
threats last week, had to evacuate all 146 schools one day. 
</P>
<P>
	Teachers can't keep lessons on track because most older students  
simply don't come back to school once it's cleared, said Barbara 
Bullock, president of the Washington Teachers Union. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really interrupting instructional time,'' she said. ``But  
God forbid the day you decide to ignore it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some officials blame the scrutiny. Nervous parents and the news  
media are watching every step, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	``These shootings are not the rule,'' said Villahermosa. ``We  
need to quit focusing on them.'' He added that most school security 
issues involve noncustodial parents, turf battles that bring kids 
from other schools and drug dealing and abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	But since Columbine, said Hunter, ``you can't say that you're  
not going to react anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some students agree.  
</P>
<P>
	``We knew it had to be a fake,'' said Salaah Elbalghiti, 18, a  
senior who spent his entire lunch one day last week in the parking 
lot waiting for a bomb-sweep of Montgomery-Blair High School, in 
Silver Spring, Md., a Washington suburb. ``But kids should not be 
in the building when there's a bomb threat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the short run, they say, they'll have to empty the buildings.  
Long term, they hope peer pressure will take over. Enough canceled 
track meets, tests and band performances might make enough other 
students sick of their peers' pranks. 
</P>
<P>
	Villahermosa nabbed a student who has pulled the fire alarm at  
his school about a dozen times in the past two weeks; some buddies 
turned him in. 
</P>
<P>
	``They just got so tired of it,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Courts are coming down on pranksters, too. An 18-year-old youth,  
who was not a student, faces fines of $2.6 million and jail terms 
totaling 1,782 years on dozens of charges in a phoned bomb threat 
that forced the evacuation of 66 schools in Schuylkill County, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter predicts lawmakers will join schools in fighting threats  
and pranks. A Delaware legislator wants stiffer penalties for bomb 
threats, at least six months in prison for a first time, five years 
after that. 
</P>
<P>
	In Collier County in southwest Florida, officials are offering  
$50 rewards for information on students planning violence. Covering 
the county's 34 schools and 34,000 students for the rest of the 
school year, the policy rewards information leading to the 
confiscation of weapons, firearms, bombs, confirmation of a bomb 
threat or other threat of violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Some worry more about schools' reaction to kids that aren't  
making threats, but are somehow being associated with the Colorado 
tragedy because they're wearing black trench coats, much like the 
killers' social clique. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Civil Liberties Union is representing 11 Brimfield,  
Ohio, students who were suspended for contributing to a Web site 
for so-called Goths, a subculture of black-garbed youths that has 
been associated with the Colorado teens. 
</P>
<P>
	``People just need to really take a deep breath,'' said Ann  
Beeson, a national staff attorney at the ACLU. ``There's a real 
danger that any kid that is not mainstream now is going to be 
considered some kind of threat.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
