<DOCNO> APW19990504.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 02:54:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prostate Blood Test in Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A new blood test combined with one already on the  
market could offer men a cheaper and less invasive way to determine 
their risk for prostate cancer, a new study says. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. William J. Catalona, a professor of urologic surgery at  
Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis who conducted 
the study, said Monday the two tests also catch cancers earlier 
than the traditional timetable for biopsies. 
</P>
<P>
	Every year, an estimated 184,500 American men develop prostate  
cancer and more than 41,000 die from it, according to the American 
Cancer Society. Early detection increases the chances of survival. 
</P>
<P>
	Used in combination, the blood tests could become an early  
alternative to surgery since doctors are cautious about ordering 
biopsies for patients with slightly elevated levels of cancer 
markers, Catalona said. 
</P>
<P>
	Men age 40 and older, and those with high risks of prostate  
cancer, have typically received annual Tandem free 
prostate-specific antigen, or PSA, tests since the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	The PSA test shows when protein levels rise in the bloodstream,  
an indicator of cancer, possibly because it escapes from the 
prostate as tissue is destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	The new test, known as hK2, measures the human kallikrein 2  
enzyme. Both it and the older test were developed by Hybritech Inc. 
of San Diego, which funded Catalona's study. 
</P>
<P>
	Catalona's team studied 937 men. The study showed that the two  
tests used together identified 91 percent of the men who were 
cancer-free and 40 percent of those who had prostate cancer and 
needed further evaluation. 
</P>
<P>
	The combination of tests could help catch as much as 95 percent  
of prostate cancers and reduce needless biopsies in the group by 20 
percent, the researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a need to catch cancer at a more curable level,''  
said Catalona, who added that the hK2 test needs fine-tuning. He 
presented to his findings to a meeting of the American Urological 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Prostate trouble is a common problem for aging men. The  
walnut-sized gland, which is involved in semen production, 
frequently becomes enlarged in older men and is susceptible to 
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, men with an intermediate PSA level of 2.5 to 4  
nanograms per milliliter are often told to wait and have the test 
repeated later instead of having a biopsy immediately. A biopsy is 
more likely to be ordered when the PSA count is 4 or higher. 
</P>
<P>
	An expert not involved in the study said the PSA ranges are not  
an absolute guide to who needs biopsies but are instead a 
weathervane. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. John Whitesel, chief of urology at the University of  
Colorado, said an additional test ``certainly would help us 
diagnose sooner. The earlier we can diagnose, the better chance we 
have to cure the disease.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
