<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 15:15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida, Insurance Co. Settle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida reached a $5.5 million  
settlement with American General Corp. over allegations the 
insurance company's subsidiaries deceived customers into buying 
more-expensive policies with the cash value of their current plans. 
</P>
<P>
	State regulators said Tuesday the settlement was over a practice  
called churning that eight of the Houston-based company's 
subsidiaries allegedly committed in Florida through the 1980s and 
up until about two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Churning describes selling a customer an additional higher-value  
policy and financing the sale by draining the customer's existing 
policy of its cash value, without the customer's full knowledge. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement came as part of a state investigation into  
deceptive sales practices by a number of insurance companies. 
</P>
<P>
	They said that from 1982 through 1997, as many as 207,000  
Floridians may have been deceived by the companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The company didn't admit any wrongdoing in the settlement  
agreement. And the majority of the companies alleged to have taken 
part in the practice weren't owned by American General for the 
whole time state regulators said it was used. 
</P>
<P>
	``American General is very satisfied that the resolution is  
appropriate and fair with the state of Florida,'' said company 
spokesman John Pluhowski. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is the third major insurer to settle with Florida in  
as part of the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Prudential Life Insurance Co. of America agreed to pay Florida a  
$15 million fine in February 1997 to settle charges that its agents 
deceived 128,000 customers into using the value of current policies 
to buy more-expensive ones. 
</P>
<P>
	The Prudential settlement was the largest administrative fine  
ever against a life insurer in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida reached a $6 million settlement with John Hancock Mutual  
Life Insurance in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The American General subsidiaries included in the investigation  
were: Franklin Life Insurance Company; American Franklin Life 
Insurance Co.; The United States Life Insurance Company; All 
American Life Insurance Co.; Old Line Insurance Company of America; 
American General Life and Accident Insurance Co.; American General 
Life Insurance Company in New York and American General Life 
Insurance Company. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
