<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Recalls Expeditions, Navigators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. is recalling about 57,200  
of its 1999 Expeditions and Navigators because of a problem that 
could cause the wheels to fall off. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're aware of one accident with two minor injuries,'' Ford  
spokeswoman Karen Shaughnessy said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The recall of the two sport utility vehicles affects models with  
optional 17-inch chrome-finished steel wheels. Ford said some 
wheels might not have enough contact with the hub, which could 
cause vibration or result in the wheel and tire falling off. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealers will tighten the wheels and install a label with  
tightening instructions on each wheel at no expense to owners. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 23:05:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bulls Wonder, Worry About Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The regular season ends tonight, and for the  
first time in a long while, the Chicago Bulls don't have much to 
show for it. Nothing they'd like to brag about, anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	There's no Central Division crown, no home-court advantage, not  
even a spot in the playoffs. Nope, it's lottery time for the 
defending champs. 
</P>
<P>
	But what if the Bulls hadn't demolished their team after Michael  
Jordan retired? Say Scottie Pippen and the rest of the gang had 
stuck around for one more year, what then? Could Chicago have won 
the East and, possibly, a seventh title? 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe.  
</P>
<P>
	``Just by looking at what's been going on, it's been kind of a  
neck-and-neck run with all of the other teams trying to position 
themselves. No question if we'd kept the team together we'd be 
defending our title again,'' said Dickey Simpkins, one of the few 
Bulls left over from last year's title team. 
</P>
<P>
	Or maybe not.  
</P>
<P>
	``Michael was such a big part in the locker room. He made  
everyone around him better, and filling that hole would have been 
near impossible,'' general manager Jerry Krause said. ``We thought 
we could win a bunch of games, but winning a championship, we did 
not think we had the ability to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krause isn't just defending himself. Remember the first time  
Jordan retired? The Bulls had Pippen, Luc Longley, Steve Kerr, B.J. 
Armstrong, Horace Grant, John Paxson and Bill Cartwright, and they 
still got bounced in the second round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Now add five years to those legs.  
</P>
<P>
	``We would have been probably the oldest team in the league.  
Older teams are more susceptible to injuries than younger teams,'' 
Krause said. ``Not only that, if we had given the contracts it 
would have taken to sign these guys, for the next several years we 
would have then been capped with the oldest team in the league and 
no way to get younger. 
</P>
<P>
	``And one of the worst things I think you can do is come fairly  
close and be old and capped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even with Jordan, the Bulls were showing signs of wear and tear.  
They barely got by Indiana in last year's Eastern Conference 
finals. Not even ``Judge Judy'' could have reconciled coach Phil 
Jackson and Krause. Dennis Rodman was getting weirder -- and that's 
tough to do. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Bulls weren't exactly young, either, with Longley the  
only starter under 30. 
</P>
<P>
	So when Jordan hung up his sneakers in January, the Bulls  
decided it was best to gut the team and start over. The first to go 
was Pippen, who -- feeling underappreciated and underpaid -- was 
looking to leave. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was looking to come out west, so I don't know what would  
have happened,'' said Pippen, who signed a five-year, $67.2 million 
deal with the Rockets. ``I was looking to move on, and that's what 
I did. Whether or not we could have stayed together as a team and 
been successful is difficult to say.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it's not as if any team is lighting up the league. Indiana,  
anointed the favorite before the lockout even ended, has struggled. 
Miami lost to the Bulls over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	In the other conference, the Utah Jazz appear vulnerable, the  
Rockets have yet to live up to their hype and the Los Angeles 
Lakers seem to need therapy. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we would have brought everyone back, who knows?'' said  
former Bull Jud Buechler, now with the Detroit Pistons. ``If there 
weren't any injuries to our team, I think we could have been in the 
mix for sure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the what-ifs don't really matter now. What's done is done,  
said Ron Harper, the only starter left in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't look around and sit back and say, `I'd hoped we had  
our same team here,' '' he said. ``If we would have kept half our 
team here, I think we would have been there. But it didn't happen, 
so life goes on.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:55:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  American Jet Downs Yugoslav Fighter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO downed a Yugoslav MiG-29  
fighter jet in a dogfight over Serbia and struck a hydraulics 
factory, fuel storage depots and armored vehicles today, showing no 
letup in the bombings after President Clinton hinted at a pause in 
air raids. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon officials said a U.S. Air Force F-16 shot down a  
Yugoslav MiG-29 in a high-speed engagement about 2 1/2 miles over 
Serbian airspace. The Russian-designed plane is the best in the 
Yugoslav air force. 
</P>
<P>
	At NATO headquarters, Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz of the German air  
force confirmed that an allied aircraft intercepted and shot down a 
Yugoslav aircraft in ``what pilots call an air-to-air fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO also said its planes bombed a MiG-29 parked at an airfield.  
</P>
<P>
	While Yugoslav aircraft have been struck on the ground at  
various Serbian and Montenegrin airports -- even seen hiding under 
the tails of large commercial airplanes -- the Yugoslav air force 
has avoided confrontations with NATO warplanes for much of the air 
war. 
</P>
<P>
	On the third day of the conflict -- March 26 -- American F-15C  
jets shot down two Yugoslav MiG-29s after they entered 
Bosnia-Herzegovina airspace. 
</P>
<P>
	Most traffic lights were still out today and many residents in  
Belgrade spent a second night in darkness, meanwhile, after the 
power grid was crippled by NATO bombings. Power was restored in 
some parts of the capital today, only to go out again. 
</P>
<P>
	Work crews had struggled Monday to restore electricity to much  
of Yugoslavia after NATO targeted two major power grids late 
Sunday. Power rationing was imposed in the central Serbian city of 
Kragujevac. 
</P>
<P>
	British Air Marshal John Day said the main focus of the latest  
operations were the Serb army and police forces in the field in 
Kosovo, including attacks on tanks, artillery and military 
vehicles. Allied firepower also struck fuel storage facilities and 
bridges. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav media reported that a NATO missile hit a bus Monday in  
Kosovo, killing 20 people and injuring 43. NATO spokesman Jamie 
Shea denied the accounts, saying today that allied commanders had 
checked all gun cameras from planes operating in the area and 
interviewed all pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can find no evidence of any NATO involvement in this  
incident,'' Shea said, suggesting the attack on a rural road near 
Pec that has been blamed on NATO may instead have been the result 
of an ambush. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's classic ambush country,'' Shea said of the area where  
Serb forces and rebels had had heavy skirmishes, adding that the 
bus did not ``seem to have been hit by a missile or a bomb from an 
aircraft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Today's attacks came a day after Clinton said there could be ``a  
bombing pause'' in airstrikes if Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic 
accepted NATO demands for a troop pullout from Kosovo, the return 
of all refugees and deployment of an international security force. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was to fly to Brussels, Belgium, today for an update on  
the air war from Secretary-General Javier Solana at NATO 
headquarters. He was then heading to Germany to meet with U.S. 
troops and some Kosovo refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO launched airstrikes against Yugoslavia on March 24 after  
Milosevic rejected a Western plan to end the fighting in Kosovo, an 
ethnic Albanian-majority province of 2 million residents in Serbia, 
the main Yugoslav republic. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 675,000 ethnic Albanians have poured out of Kosovo  
since the airstrikes began, leading NATO's top general to say today 
that Milosevic could succeed in his campaign of massive deportation 
of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo despite the allied operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Klaus Naumann, a German four-star general and retiring head  
of NATO's military arm, said the air operation ``has slowed down 
the efforts of Milosevic's instruments for ethnic cleansing'' but 
``we cannot stop such a thing entirely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``President Milosevic's mass deportation campaign appears  
achievable,'' he said, adding that while Milosevic cannot defeat 
NATO, he might be able to completely force ethnic Albanians out. 
``I think if he really wants to get them out ... he may have a 
chance to do this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Refugees streaming into Albania bore tales today of Serb forces  
demanding money from them and gunning down those who didn't comply. 
</P>
<P>
	The refugees alleged the killings occurred Sunday night on a  
road in Studime, a village 20 miles northwest of Kosovo's capital 
Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	In about a half-mile stretch, ``I saw bodies on the road and  
some others in the river,'' said Selvie Gorguri, crossing the 
border on a wagon. ``In the road there were many men. There were 
bodies in cars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The refugee accounts could not be independently confirmed.  
</P>
<P>
	Kosova Press, the Kosovo Liberation Army's news agency, said  
about 100 civilians were killed by Serb soldiers in the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	At a U.S. military base in Germany, three American servicemen  
were given a clean bit of health today after being freed Sunday by 
Yugoslav authorities following a peace mission by the Rev. Jesse 
Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	Checkups of the soldiers revealed fractured ribs and a broken  
nose, raising questions about how they were treated during their 
March 31 capture. 
</P>
<P>
	In Moscow, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov called today for an  
immediate halt to the NATO airstrikes. Russia's special envoy to 
the Balkans, Viktor Chernomyrdin, was in Washington today to 
discuss Russian efforts to broker a peace agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Alliance planes that have been conducting more than 600 bombing  
sorties a day were active today, with the Tanjug news agency 
reporting explosions in Pristina and blasts in Vucitrn, 
northwestern Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Attacks also were reported on a factory in the central Serbian  
town of Valjevo, on Vranje near the border with Macedonia, 
Strazevica hill on the outskirts of Belgrade and the Batajnica 
region northwest of the city, where a military airfield is located. 
</P>
<P>
	Cities and towns across Yugoslavia were slowly restoring  
electricity and water after NATO jets blasted power plants in 
strikes aimed at disrupting the Yugoslav military. Serbia lost 70 
percent of its electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	The power plant bombings targeted the Yugoslav army's command  
and control centers and demonstrated that the alliance can ``shut 
off the power system whenever we want,'' Shea said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:55:23 </DATE_TIME>
