<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 01:32:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Welcomes Japan Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In 1963, Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi  
-- still a student -- came to the nation's capital for what turned 
out to be a seminal event leading to his political career: a 
meeting with then-Attorney General Robert F. Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-six years after that fateful trip, the White House  
welcomed Obuchi as guest of honor at a grand spring dinner, where 
the Japanese leader took a seat alongside his mentor's wife, Ethel 
Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can only wonder at the inexplicable manner in which destiny  
plays out,'' remarked Obuchi Monday night, during his official 
toast before a crowd of 340 guests. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a pavilion on the South Lawn filled with signs of  
springtime, President Clinton said the graciousness Obuchi saw in 
Kennedy had indeed made a lasting impression. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see it today reflected in your own decency and  
generosity,'' Clinton said in his toast. 
</P>
<P>
	Legendary pianist Van Cliburn, who has performed for every  
president since Harry Truman, enchanted the audience with his own 
selections including pieces by Chopin, Brahms and Rachmaninoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is a national treasure,'' Clinton said of the virtuoso.  
</P>
<P>
	Guests enjoyed cocktails in the East Room before loading up into  
red trolleys that escorted them to the pavilion. An-indoor garden, 
created with the help of the National Park Service, awaited them. 
Azaleas and lugustrums bedecked the sides of the tent, while fresh 
lilacs and white peonies topped the tables. 
</P>
<P>
	First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton greeted guests in a black and  
white sash presented to her by Mrs. Chizuko Obuchi over a 
floor-length black sequin Donna Karan gown. 
</P>
<P>
	Author Arthur Golden, who penned ``Memoirs of a Geisha,'' Lynda  
Carter of ``Wonder Woman'' fame and actor Sidney Poitier peppered a 
guest list filled mostly with political officials and business 
executives. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the attendees was Saburo Kato, chairman of the Nippon  
Bonsai Association, who earlier in the day gave the two leaders a 
tutorial in horticulture. In the White House Blue Room, adorned for 
the occasion by Bonsai trees brought in from the National 
Arboretum, the pair listened attentively as Kato then explained the 
way the roots grow and the trees curve. Clinton also presented 
Obuchi with a 300-year-old tree as a gift. 
</P>
<P>
	Obuchi, sometimes likened to cold pizza by the Japanese media,  
displayed his warmth and charm to a receptive White House audience. 
Calling his trip a success, Obuchi set forth his major priorities 
for the visit. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only and most serious concern of my delegation and myself  
was whether my ceremonial first pitch at the Chicago Cubs game can 
reach the home plate,'' Obuchi said through a translator. ``My ball 
was nailed into Sammy Sosa's mitt without hitting the ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Ambassador to Japan Tom Foley said that when Obuchi took  
office it was clear he was a ``nice guy,'' yet some questioned 
whether that was what Japan really needed. But the prime minister 
soon proved his political mettle. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's doing very well,'' Foley said. ``He's enjoying the esteem  
of his own citizens as well as of Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, as Obuchi himself noted, things have changed quite a bit  
since his 1963 visit to Washington. Back then, the prime minister 
paid out a hefty $1.50 a night for a room at the YMCA. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, this time no charge,'' quipped the Japanese leader.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
