<DOCNO> APW19990504.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 05:05:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  'Nightingales' Nominated for Tony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- What happens now to the Broadway plays and  
musicals that did -- and did not -- receive Tony Award nominations? 
</P>
<P>
	For some like ``Parade,'' which got nine nominations Monday,  
more than any other show, it won't make any difference. The musical 
about a real-life lynching in Georgia in 1913 closed in February 
after a short run. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're thrilled, but a little sad,'' said Bernard Gersten,  
executive producer at Lincoln Center Theater, which helped present 
``Parade.'' ``We know it is good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some shows gave up without a fight. ``Marlene,'' a look at film  
legend Marlene Dietrich, received two nominations including one for 
its star Sian Phillips. Yet it threw in the towel on Sunday, one 
day before the nominations came out. 
</P>
<P>
	For other shows, such as ``Not About Nightingales,'' ``The  
Lonesome West,'' and ``Side Man,'' still running and struggling at 
the box office, there's hope for a boost in ticket sales. 
</P>
<P>
	All three gained best-play nominations and the impetus to carry  
on until at least June 6, when the winners are announced. 
``Nightingales,'' written by Tennessee Williams in 1938 but never 
done on Broadway until now, received a lift. The prison drama got 
six nominations including actor (Corin Redgrave) and director 
(Trevor Nunn) nods. 
</P>
<P>
	The other best-play nominee ``Closer'' will have to sell its  
status as a candidate for best play and not its actors. None of its 
four performers, including Natasha Richardson, got a nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	For ``Amy's View,'' the star -- Oscar winner Judi Dench -- is the  
thing, not the play. She received a nomination, but the play 
didn't. Not that it matters. ``Amy's View'' is a hot ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	So are the season's two big revivals -- ``Death of a Salesman''  
and ``The Iceman Cometh.'' They are going head-to-head for the 
revival award and in the actor category where ``Salesman's'' Brian 
Dennehy faces ``Iceman's'' Kevin Spacey. It's a toss-up as to who 
will win -- but that makes for an exciting horse race. And tickets 
even harder to get. 
</P>
<P>
	Question marks hover over shows that didn't get major  
nominations or none at all. ``The Weir,'' Conor McPherson's small 
Irish pub drama was blanked. Now it will have fight for attention 
against plays that have nominations to sell. The same goes for 
``The Gershwins' Fascinating Rhythm,'' which wasn't expecting any 
musical nominations -- and didn't get any. 
</P>
<P>
	``Footloose'' also failed to get a best-musical nod, which means  
no production number on the Tony telecast. The four minutes of 
national television exposure will benefit ``Fosse,'' a celebration 
of choreographer Bob Fosse; ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' 
another revue, and ``The Civil War,'' composer Frank Wildhorn's pop 
history pageant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines May Take Control of PAL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- The government is considering a  
temporary takeover of troubled Philippine Airlines to help it look 
for fresh capital and avoid being closed, President Joseph Estrada 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Estrada said the step would be a last resort if PAL chairman  
Lucio Tan is unable to raise the $200 million in new capital needed 
for its rehabilitation plan by an early June deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will take over PAL if that is necessary,'' Estrada told  
reporters. ``The bottom line is, I want to see to it that PAL will 
continue flying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said the government would  
take over PAL's management but would not infuse money into the 
troubled carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Estrada's administration has adopted a policy of not undertaking  
costly bailouts of beleaguered private and state-run companies. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL is mired in debts of more than $2.2 billion, of which more  
than two-thirds are owed to the U.S. and European credit agencies 
which helped finance the airline's ambitious but ill-timed fleet 
modernization program. 
</P>
<P>
	The capital infusion is a key element of a rehabilitation plan  
that also calls for cutting the airline's fleet to 22 planes from 
54 and slashing the labor force to about 3,000 from 8,000. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL submitted additional details of the plan on Tuesday, meeting  
a deadline set by Manila's Securities and Exchange Commission. The 
SEC had earlier rejected the plan for being too vague and failing 
to identify potential investors. 
</P>
<P>
	However, PAL's new document did not identify any interested  
investors other than Tan and did not divulge the basis for its 
future income projections as sought by the SEC. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC will review the filing and decide later whether it is  
sufficient. PAL's management must also meet a June 4 SEC deadline 
for it to come up with the $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	SEC chairman Perfecto Yasay has said he will order the  
liquidation of PAL if the capital is not raised by the deadline and 
other key requirements of the rehabilitation plan are not met. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline's major creditors, including the U.S. Export-Import  
bank and European export credit agencies, initially backed the plan 
but threatened to scuttle it after Tan reassumed direct management 
control of the airline last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The creditors have said they want PAL run by professional  
managers. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan, one of the country's richest men, owns 70 percent of the  
airline and has interests in banking, beer and tobacco. He was a 
major contributor to Estrada's campaign last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan has said he is willing to organize a group of investors to  
raise the $200 million and pledged to provide half of the total 
himself, but the government is uncertain whether he can do so by 
the deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan was set to fly to Germany to try to woo Deutsche Lufthansa  
AG to help recapitalize PAL, Trade and Industry Secretary Jose 
Pardo said. 
</P>
<P>
	As a fallback for Tan's efforts, the government has begun talks  
with two other potential investors, Pardo said, but declined to 
give details. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 22:51:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornado Damage Worries Insurers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The spiraling storms that ripped through  
Oklahoma and Kansas this week were large and ferocious enough to 
cause the worst-ever property losses from tornadoes, insurance 
experts believe. 
</P>
<P>
	While the monetary cost of the tornadoes won't be known for  
several days, insurance companies anticipating drastic losses made 
their first overtures to the battered region Tuesday, sending in 
extra workers and setting up mobile offices to begin collecting 
damage reports. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's major insurers were all preparing special  
catastrophe teams to travel to the area. Some claims adjusters have 
already arrived and are beginning to evaluate the damage, but many 
others stayed away for another day, awaiting a lull in the 
wrenching weather. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 2,000 houses in the Oklahoma City area were destroyed  
by the tornadoes, which ripped through the area Monday. Wichita, 
Kan., also sustained heavy losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Property Claim Services unit of the New York-based Insurance  
Services Office Inc. said the damage could exceed the $1.3 billion, 
inflation-adjusted toll of a tornado that struck Xenia, Ohio in 
1974. 
</P>
<P>
	The costliest storm on record was Hurricane Andrew, which caused  
about $16 billion in property losses in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	In size and intensity, Monday's storm was stunning.  
</P>
<P>
	``We studied 37 mid-sized to large catastrophes last year,''  
said John Eager, director of claims services for the National 
Association of Independent Insurers. ``I don't remember any that 
were as devastating as this one seems to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many areas remained off-limits to insurance workers Tuesday  
afternoon as rescue workers searched for survivors. Travelers 
Property and Casualty, which plans to have a dozen workers in the 
damaged regions by this morning, said another 40 would arrive later 
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first step is to assess the whole area, and then we'll see  
what else we need to do,'' said Ray Stone, catastrophe manager for 
the insurance giant. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hartford, a Connecticut-based insurer, had some adjusters at  
work in Oklahoma on Tuesday, but also anticipated more arriving 
later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Erwin, a spokesman for the Insurance Information  
Institute, said insurance companies typically wait a bit before 
they fully mobilize after a catastrophe. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are initially in shock,'' he said. ``It's OK to let  
them be in shock for a while, then go in and help them rebuild.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Insurance professionals Tuesday offered a number of suggestions  
for people struggling with damaged homes and properties. First off, 
they said, local media can provide information on special hot lines 
or toll-free numbers set up by insurance providers. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said people should generally make only repairs that  
are absolutely necessary, and should photograph or videotape 
damaged property before fixing anything. Adjusters will want to see 
the full extent of the damage. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAII, the independent insurers' group, said people should  
keep detailed list of everything that is damaged or destroyed, and 
should keep receipts for any emergency repairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer advocates encouraged homeowners to check references  
before hiring any contractors, anticipating that natural disasters 
could bring out unscrupulous behavior from people hoping to prey on 
frayed emotions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
