<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornadoes Kill 39 in Midwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Tornadoes tore through Oklahoma and Kansas  
on Monday night, wiping out whole neighborhoods, killing at least 
39 people and injuring hundreds. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 1,000 homes were destroyed in Oklahoma City alone,  
police said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard it, the house started shaking and then the big  
rumble,'' said 74-year-old Katherine Burch, who hid in the bathroom 
of her southwest Oklahoma City home during the storm. ``Glass and 
everything flew in it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Power lines popped, debris flew and sirens blared as the twister  
moved from Chickasha to the heavily populated suburbs of Oklahoma 
City, 50 miles to the northeast. The tornado was part of a storm 
system that moved north into neighboring Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Police and emergency workers combed through the debris as  
darkness fell, searching for survivors while tornado warnings 
remained in effect. Crumpled cars littered two highways. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's real chaotic,'' said Sharla Findley, director of  
community relations at Hillcrest Health Center in Oklahoma City. 
``We've gotten so many patients in I don't know who we have here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 39 deaths, 29 were in Oklahoma, 10 in Kansas.  
</P>
<P>
	Eleven people were killed in Bridge Creek, about 30 miles  
southwest of Oklahoma City, said Ben Frizzell, spokesman for the 
state Office of Emergency Management. He said four others died in 
Midwest City, a suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma City police said at least eight died there. Three  
deaths were reported in Moore, just south of Oklahoma City. Another 
death was reported at Norman Regional Hospital, and two more in 
suburban Del City. 
</P>
<P>
	In neighboring Kansas, 10 were reported dead in Haysville and  
Wichita, about 150 miles due north. Nearly 100 people were reported 
injured. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is worse than what you can see tonight,'' Battalion Chief  
Bob Thompson of the Sedgwick County Fire Department said. ``We'll 
probably find more deaths. I don't think we've seen the end of 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Oklahoma, the Midwest Regional Medical Center said it was  
treating at least 100 injured, as did the Hillcrest Health Center. 
Other hospitals were reporting injured as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``We fear there are many more,'' Frizzell said of possible  
victims. 
</P>
<P>
	A tornado hit a hospital in Stroud, southwest of Tulsa. There  
were no immediate reports of injury from that storm. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got lost in a neighborhood I've driven around for 10 years  
because there's no landmarks anymore,'' said Sgt. Jody Suit of Del 
City. ``Out of one square mile, I'd say about one fourth of it is 
gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Suit estimated 750 houses were heavily damaged or destroyed in  
Del City. 
</P>
<P>
	The tornado was one of several that formed over a five-hour  
period beginning in southwest Oklahoma and stretching northeast. 
The National Severe Storms Lab in Norman said the tornado may have 
been a mile wide at times. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is just the perfect type of atmosphere, very unstable and  
with wind shear, to create supercells,'' said National Weather 
Service forecaster David Andra. 
</P>
<P>
	He said forecasters expected the Oklahoma City twister to be  
categorized as at least F-4, the second-strongest tornado 
classification with winds between 207 mph and 260 mph. There were 
at least three tornado warnings still in effect at 10:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Several mobile homes in south Wichita were blown into a lake and  
several other homes were damaged, said Fred Irvin of the Sedgwick 
County Emergency Preparedness Office. Irvin said multiple injuries 
were reported in both Wichita and Haysville. 
</P>
<P>
	Chad Harris' mobile home was demolished with eight people  
inside. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no trailer,'' Harris, 19, said. ``We all rolled in it.  
It was the worst experience in my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two people in the trailer were in critical condition.  
</P>
<P>
	Courtney Karr, 13, said she saw the bay windows in her house  
cave in and the tornado swirling inside the house. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was freaked out at that point. I was scared for my life,''  
Courtney said. ``I've seen it on TV, but seeing it with my own 
eyes, tearing up my own home ... it is hard to explain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Television reports in Oklahoma City showed hundreds of destroyed  
homes. Heavy damage was reported in Moore, where rows of houses 
were destroyed and scores of trucks overturned. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the worst storm devastation I have ever heard of,''  
Gov. Frank Keating said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keating declared a state of emergency and activated two elements  
of the National Guard to assist in Moore and Chickasha. 
</P>
<P>
	In Moore, natural gas leaked from several locations and power  
lines and piles of carpet were everywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's gone,'' LeeAnn Richardson of Moore said as she looked  
toward where her home once stood. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Richardson said she and others were watching the weather on  
television when they decided to run into the storm cellar after 
clouds rolled in and rain poured down. Sixteen people and four pets 
were in there with her. 
</P>
<P>
	All survived without injury, but: ``We opened up and everything  
was gone,'' Ms. Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The twister was first reported about 5:50 p.m., but had not  
caused significant damage to homes until moving closer to Oklahoma 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruth Seymore sat on the tailgate of a pickup truck being used as  
a treatment center by a Red Cross volunteer in Moore. Injured 
people waited for ambulances. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything fell in on me,'' Ms. Seymore said of her home,  
where she hid in a closet. ``They couldn't hardly get me out of 
there. I couldn't get anybody to find me. I kept hollering `Help!' 
'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Del City, Mary Pat Faris wore a nightgown at the high school  
where she waited for word about missing family members. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard it. I heard the popping and then I heard the trees  
crunching and then my house was gone,'' said Ms. Faris, who 
weathered the storm in her bathtub. 
</P>
</TEXT>
