<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Racists Convicted of Murderous Plot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A jury that convicted two white  
supremacists of murder in a plot to overthrow the government and 
create a whites-only nation now must decide whether to recommend 
the death sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury of nine blacks and three whites convicted Chevie Kehoe  
and Daniel Lee on Tuesday of racketeering, conspiracy and murder. 
The sentencing phase begins Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kehoe, of Colville, Wash., and Lee, of Yukon, Okla., both 26,  
sat expressionless as they listened to the guilty verdicts. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors said the men pursued their dream of an  
all-white republic by stockpiling military-style weapons, robbing 
several people and suffocating gun dealer William Mueller, his wife 
and her 8-year-old daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevie and brother Cheyne Kehoe first entered the public eye in  
1997, following a videotaped shootout with police in Ohio. Cheyne 
Kehoe later helped authorities find his brother. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors deliberated about 13 hours before returning the verdicts.  
They reviewed transcripts of two key prosecution witnesses -- 
Kehoe's mother, Gloria Kehoe, and brother Cheyne -- and they watched 
a videotape of the 1997 shootout. 
</P>
<P>
	The mother and brother both testified that Kehoe had described  
how he and Lee suffocated the three victims in the northwest 
Arkansas town of Tilly in January 1996 and threw their bodies into 
a river. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Kehoe was the leader of the enterprise and  
recruited Lee to carry out his orders. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers argued that, while Kehoe and Lee may have had  
offensive beliefs, they didn't act criminally on them or have the 
means to do what prosecutors claim. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlene Branch, the mother of murder victim Nancy Mueller, said  
she would testify during the sentencing phase. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to be a Christian and think of killing somebody,''  
she said. ``But I don't see any other answer. I don't want them out 
influencing anyone else.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
