<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reviews May Free INS Detainees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Release may be near for some of the 3,500  
criminal immigrants caught in detention limbo: They've been held 
behind bars, in some cases for years, but they're not deportable 
because their homelands won't take them back. 
</P>
<P>
	Immigration and Naturalization Service Commissioner Doris  
Meissner has ordered INS district offices to institute regular case 
reviews for all long-term detainees who cannot be repatriated 
because the United States lacks deportation agreements with their 
homelands. Most of these detainees, known in some circles as 
``lifers,'' are from Cuba, Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos. 
</P>
<P>
	The reviews will prompt releases, although the INS says it  
cannot estimate how many. 
</P>
<P>
	``INS' priority is keeping our communities safe, and no one will  
be released if he or she is deemed to pose a threat to public 
safety,'' Meissner said in a statement. ``Release decisions will 
consider criminal and immigration violations, history of violence 
while incarcerated, evidence of rehabilitation and ties to the 
community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meissner's directive, announced late Friday, came as INS was  
contending with a high-profile protest in Miami. The parents of 
four Cuban ex-convicts in INS custody agreed Monday to end their 
47-day hunger strike protesting the indefinite detention of their 
sons and other long-term detainees after wrangling additional 
concessions from INS. 
</P>
<P>
	Immigrant advocates welcomed the mandatory reviews.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is a long overdue and important policy change,'' said  
Allyson Collins, a senior researcher with Human Rights Watch, which 
has strongly criticized INS' detention policies. ``The INS has been 
violating international human rights standards prohibiting 
arbitrary detention by holding these detainees indefinitely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee's immigration  
panel denounced the new policy, unfurled against the backdrop of 
continuing INS difficulties in housing an increasing detention 
population. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why is the INS' response to a shortage of detention beds  
always to release convicted criminals into our communities?'' said 
Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas. ``Is this the best the Clinton 
administration can do for the public it is supposed to serve?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The administration ``should be held accountable for every  
released deportable criminal who hurts another innocent victim,'' 
Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, INS spokeswoman Maria Cardona said Tuesday: ``We  
will under no circumstances release anybody who we believe is a 
threat to society.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Passage of a sweeping immigration law in 1996 placed new  
pressures on INS' detention network, which now houses 16,400 
people, triple the number of five years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress mandated that INS detain virtually all noncitizens  
whose criminal convictions have made them deportable, ending the 
agency's discretion to release criminal immigrants believed to pose 
no risk. Lawmakers also broadened the definition of crimes 
triggering deportation and included provisions to cover convictions 
prior to the 1996 law's passage. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., who visited the Miami protesters over  
the weekend, has pledged to seek reform of the 1996 law. So has 
Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart, R-Fla., who has particularly deplored the 
retroactivity rules. 
</P>
<P>
	A frequent INS critic said the administration had little choice  
but to confront the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somebody who is a shoplifter and can't go back to Vietnam -- I  
don't know, is it really sensible to keep that guy locked up 
forever?'' asked Mark Krikorian, executive director of the Center 
for Immigration Studies, which favors reduced immigration rates. 
``It is perfectly appropriate, I think, for us to answer that 
question, `Yes,' only for those people who pose threats to the 
community.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
