<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Chief Eyes Web Smut Protections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's top telecommunications regulator  
said Tuesday that schools and libraries should have policies 
protecting children from smut and other inappropriate material on 
the Internet in order to receive federal money to subsidize access. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration is pushing the proposal.  
</P>
<P>
	``This idea makes a lot of sense,'' said Federal Communications  
Commission Chairman Bill Kennard, a Clinton appointee. ``As schools 
around the country think about how they are going to use technology 
in the classroom, they should also think about how to use it 
responsibly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the Commerce Department urged the FCC, which  
oversees the Internet subsidies program, to require public schools 
and libraries to have such policies in place if they want to 
receive the subsidies. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislation pending in the Senate, however, would be tougher and  
require schools and libraries to install such computer software in 
return for receiving the subsidies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 14:25:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Proposes Privacy Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Contending many privacy laws have been  
overtaken by the information age, President Clinton urged Congress 
on Tuesday to bolster the rights of consumers when banks and other 
financial companies seek to share or sell information about them. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said too many consumers ``have fallen victim to abusive  
practices'' and the rule changes would give them ``the tools and 
the confidence they need to fully participate in a thriving but 
highly complex 21st century economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president's proposal comes at a time when mergers and  
consolidations have melded financial institutions of all kinds and 
given banks unprecedented access to their customers' financial and 
medical records. 
</P>
<P>
	``You should not have to worry that the results of your latest  
physical will be used to deny your application for a mortgage or a 
credit card,'' Clinton said in a ceremony in the old Executive 
Office Building. 
</P>
<P>
	The basic principle of his proposal would give Americans the  
right to decide whether information about them held by banks, 
insurance firms or securities companies is shared or sold. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all know that technology and competition have  
revolutionized the financial services industry,'' the president 
said. ``But many people ... don't have the knowledge to properly 
evaluate what is truly a dizzying array of options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president also defended the Community Reinvestment Act  
against efforts of Senate Republicans to weaken it. 
</P>
<P>
	The act, which gives banks incentives to lend money in poor  
communities, has been in effect for 20 years. But Clinton said he 
is proud that more than 90 percent of the funds provided under the 
act have come in the last six years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has not done anything to hurt bank profits, and we ought to  
stay with it,'' the president said of the law. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton plan, which follows the outlines of legislation  
introduced in January by Sen. Paul Sarbanes D-Md., has these main 
components: 
</P>
<P>
	--Require banks and other financial institutions to tell  
consumers when they plan to share or sell their personal financial 
information, and give consumers the power to stop such a transfer. 
</P>
<P>
	--Restrict any sharing of medical information within a financial  
conglomerate. ``As banks and insurance firms merge, for example, 
consumers should not fear that the results of a physical exam could 
be used to make a credit decision,'' a White House statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Require credit-card offers of low ``teaser rates'' to  
prominently disclose when those rates expire and how costly 
repayment can be if only minimum monthly payments are made. 
</P>
<P>
	--Increase the Securities and Exchange Commission budget by $16.5  
million in the coming fiscal year to boost the surveillance and 
prosecution of fraud in stock market and other financial 
transactions over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals were hailed by a number of consumer groups.  
</P>
<P>
	``The administration's proposals, if enacted, would go a long  
way to help inject honest and fair dealing into a marketplace that 
increasingly fails to meet the needs of modest and lower income 
consumers,'' said a joint statement by the Consumer Federation of 
America and the Consumers Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 06:55:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Dead, Up to 100 Injured in Kansas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WICHITA, Kan. (AP) -- The howling storm ripped the roof off the  
Karr home as the family huddled in terror and disbelief. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was freaked out at that point. I was scared for my life,''  
said 13-year-old Courtney Karr, who cowered with her 15-year-old 
sister, Jessie, and their parents as a killer tornado ripped their 
house apart. 
</P>
<P>
	Five people were killed and up to 100 people were injured by  
Monday night's twister in Wichita and its southern suburb of 
Haysville. Tornadoes spawned by the same storm killed more people 
in the Oklahoma City area 150 miles south. 
</P>
<P>
	Emergency officials surveyed the damage today and rescue workers  
went door-to-door looking for people who might be trapped or 
injured. Bob Thompson, a battalion chief for the Sedgwick County 
Fire Department, said there was a chance the death toll could rise. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we've seen the end of it,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Courtney watched in horror as the wind blew in the bay windows  
of her family's home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen it on TV, but seeing it with my own eyes, tearing up  
my own home ... it is hard to explain,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The family was trapped in the basement for about half an hour  
until the storm subsided. 
</P>
<P>
	The twister cut a path 3 1/4 miles wide and 10 miles long through  
Haysville and southern Wichita. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the destruction was in Haysville, where parts of the  
older business district were demolished, including a bank, real 
estate company, chiropractor's office, a 10-unit apartment complex 
and several homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Railroad tracks were uprooted and sheet metal was wrapped around  
trees near the ruins of the two-block long Norland Plastics plant. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Bill Graves declared Sedgwick County a disaster area early  
today and ordered out the National Guard, which set up a temporary 
morgue and an aid station. 
</P>
<P>
	In Wichita, two trailer parks were devastated. Insulation and  
fragments of metal and lumber littered the ground. At one park, a 
yellow toddler's slide and a red Schwinn bicycle lay amid the 
debris. 
</P>
<P>
	Haysville resident Duane Moore and his wife, Vicky, hid with  
their three dogs in a neighbor's storm shelter, but the wind yanked 
the door off. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't seen anything yet; I just noticed I don't have a  
house,'' Ms. Moore said as she, her husband and the dogs walked out 
of their shattered neighborhood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
