<DOCNO> APW19990504.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 13:35:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Launches Asthma Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton kicked off a national  
asthma screening program Tuesday at an inner-city elementary 
school, hoping to draw attention to a dramatic rise in children 
with the disease. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 200 schools, shopping malls, community centers and  
health fairs offered free screenings as part of the program to 
increase detection of asthma. 
</P>
<P>
	Between 14 million and 15 million people have the disease but  
many don't realize that their wheezing, coughing and breathing 
problems are caused by it. And asthma is the leading cause of 
hospitalization for children and one of the leading reasons why 
children miss school. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to pay particular attention to poor families, because  
it is the children of the poor who suffer disproportionately from 
this disease,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the American College of Allergy, Asthma and  
Immunology, black children suffer the most from asthma. Although 
their risk of contracting it is only slightly higher than for other 
children, black children are more than four times more likely to 
die from it. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton called on Congress to enact a White House proposal  
to help fight asthma. The Department of Health and Human Services 
wants to spend $50 million for state grants that would identify and 
treat poor children served by Medicaid who have asthma. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of children with asthma has doubled to about six  
million in the last 15 years, said Dr. Talal Nsouli, Washington 
chairman of the ACAAI's screening program. The rate for children 
under age five increased 160 percent within the same period. 
</P>
<P>
	Asthma can be controlled with medication but early detection and  
constant, appropriate treatment are the best ways to prevent asthma 
statistics from increasing further, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton also unveiled a public service campaign to promote  
a study released by the Environmental Protection Agency that says 
exposure to second-hand smoke considerably worsens asthma for up to 
a million children. It also increases the chance among young 
children to contract pneumonia, ear infections, bronchitis and 
Sudden Infant Death Syndrome, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton encouraged parents who smoke to avoid doing so  
around their children or in their homes. She said she has 
implemented a non-smoking policy at the White House, which has led 
to some ``tickly'' situations involving visiting kings, prime 
ministers and other heads of state who tried to light up a 
cigarette inside but were shooed outdoors instead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that you'll think of your house, the White House, as an  
example perhaps for your own house,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
