<DOCNO> APW19990504.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 13:55:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Holdsclaw Is Top Pick in WNBA Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In Chamique Holdsclaw, the WNBA just might have  
its version of Michael Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw, a four-time All-American who led Tennessee to three  
consecutive national titles, was the No. 1 pick by the Washington 
Mystics in Tuesday's WNBA draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's the player of the present and the player of the future  
for our league,'' WNBA president Val Ackerman said. ``Her eventual 
appeal could rival what Michael Jordan was able to do over his long 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	``She'll have an appeal that players in our league haven't quite  
had yet in terms of reaching a new groups of fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw, a two-time national player of the year, was selected  
first even though pro players were from the defunct American 
Basketball League were also included in the draft. Holdsclaw was 
the only college player drafted in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	While the 6-foot-2 star goes to a team that won just three of 30  
games last season, she is expected to immediately turn around the 
Mystics. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw averaged 21.3 points and 8.1 rebounds last season for  
the Lady Vols, who were upset by Duke in the NCAA regional finals 
in March. She is Tennessee's career scoring leader, surpassing 
Allan Houston, with 3,025 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Former ABL player Yolanda Griffith was the No. 2 pick, going to  
the Sacramento Monarchs. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah then chose center Natalie Williams, the ABL's player of the  
year in '98 who averaged 21 points and 11.6 rebounds per game. Los 
Angeles picked forward Delisha Milton of Portland, a member of the 
1998 World Championship team. 
</P>
<P>
	Former San Jose Laser guard Jennifer Azzi went to Detroit with  
the fifth picks and forward Crystal Robinson was chosen by the New 
York Liberty. 
</P>
<P>
	The WNBA drafted 50 players in the four-round draft -- 35 from  
the ABL, 12 from college and three from international teams. 
</P>
<P>
	With the influx of the ABL players, many of them Olympians or  
All-Americans, Ackerman called it the ``deepest draft in modern-day 
sports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The draft was postponed a week because of a labor dispute  
between the players and league. 
</P>
<P>
	The league and players union agreed to allow three ABL players  
on each of the 10 established teams and five each on the expansion 
teams in Minnesota and Orlando. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12-team WNBA begins its third 10-week season on June 10.  
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw will join a Washington team that finished at the  
bottom of the league last season and be paired with former Lady Vol 
Nikki McCray. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the women's side, people most compare her to Cheryl Miller,  
who had an all-around game as Chamique does,'' Ackerman said. ``On 
the men's game, I hear her compared to Scottie Pippen. She's very 
agile, a good defensive player who can score, pass, has great court 
sense and is incredibly competitive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw will be coached by Nancy Darsch, a former Tennessee  
assistant in the mid-1980s. Darsch was fired after two seasons with 
the New York Liberty. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coach (Pat) Summitt really wanted me to play for Nancy,'' said  
Holdsclaw, a New Yorker. ``Washington is where my grandmother 
wanted me to play. I'm kind of glad I didn't go to New York because 
I don't know if I could handle all the pressure and friends and 
fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Griffith, the 1998 ABL defensive player of the year, averaged  
17.2 points and 12.3 rebounds for the Chicago Condors. She's 
looking forward to playing with Sacramento's Ruthie 
Bolton-Holifield. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ruthie is a great defender and a great player,'' Griffith  
said. ``Once we learn to play with each other, we'll be OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This year's expansion teams picked seventh and eighth: The  
Minnesota Lynx took guard Tonya Edwards of the two-time champion 
Columbus Quest, and the Orlando Miracle selected forward Tari 
Phillips of the Colorado Xplosion. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlotte followed with guard Dawn Staley, formerly of the  
Philadelphia Rage; Phoenix went for guard Edna Campbell of the 
Colorado Xplosion; Cleveland picked center Chasity Melvin of the 
Rage; and Houston selected the only international player in the 
first round, Natalia Zassoulskaia, a two-time MVP of the 
Euroleague, from Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:44:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Workers Get No Respect on TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- They are the Rodney Dangerfields of broadcast  
television: politicians, postal workers and government employees. 
They get no respect. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a new report, postal workers tend to be portrayed  
as lazy and inept -- like Cliff Clavin, the blowhard mail carrier 
perched on a barstool at ``Cheers.'' Politicians like Boss Hogg on 
``The Dukes of Hazzard'' are stereotyped as greedy and out for No. 
1. 
</P>
<P>
	Police officers and teachers, however, are depicted more  
positively. 
</P>
<P>
	The Center for Media and Public Affairs, a nonpartisan research  
organization here, came up with these findings after examining how 
prime-time entertainment shows on broadcast television over the 
last four decades have depicted elected officials, law enforcers, 
teachers and people who work for the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Elected officials had the worst image of any government-related  
occupation shown on television for the entire time period examined. 
</P>
<P>
	The report is based on 1,234 prime-time series episodes from  
1955 through 1998 on ABC, CBS and NBC, and the years during that 
period after Fox was launched. 
</P>
<P>
	In analyzing shows airing from 1955 through 1986, 51 percent of  
the politicians played negative roles compared with 40 percent who 
played positive ones, while 9 percent of the portrayals were 
neutral. 
</P>
<P>
	Politicians' roles have become more neutral in the past few  
years. For shows airing between 1992 and 1998, only 31 percent were 
depicted negatively, 22 percent positively and 47 percent 
neutrally. 
</P>
<P>
	Compared with other TV occupations, elected officials -- taken as  
a group -- contained a majority of bad guys, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some TV politicians were depicted as honorable, such as actor  
Fess Parker in the TV version of ``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington,'' 
a comedy show that ran from 1962 to 1963. 
</P>
<P>
	But after the mid-1970s, the report said, TV focused on either  
the dark side of political life -- evil politicians allied with 
business or criminal interests -- or as foolish bumblers in humorous 
roles, such as Boss Hogg, a corrupt and blustery county 
commissioner. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Spin City,'' fictional New York Mayor Randall Winston is  
portrayed as a scatterbrained bungler, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Civil servants, particularly postal workers like Clavin or the  
abrasive Newman on ``Seinfeld,'' are rarely portrayed in a positive 
light, the report said. Instead, they are depicted as ``robotic 
paper shufflers or abrasive malcontents'' too lazy to serve the 
public. 
</P>
<P>
	In one ``Seinfeld'' episode, Newman uses a government mail truck  
to haul recyclables from New York to Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Postal Service isn't insulted by the Clavin or Newman  
characters, said spokesman Mark Saunders. ``We take it in stride. 
It's meant to be humorous. We're not offended.'' A 1998 AP poll 
found that almost three-fourths of Americans believe the service is 
doing an excellent or good job. 
</P>
<P>
	But Alvin Poussaint, professor of clinical psychiatry at Harvard  
Medical School, said there is a serious side to these unflattering 
images. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a bad thing if you consider that most people,  
particularly children, get their impressions about the world and 
jobs and role models from television,'' he said. ``If they see 
mostly negative images of public officials or politicians that may 
turn them off from those kinds of jobs.'' Or, it could discourage 
them from voting, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	In an episode of ``The X-Files,'' FBI agent Fox Mulder -- often  
portrayed as a hero -- discovers a secret government conspiracy to 
implant a deadly biotoxin in stolen money to test its effects on 
the public. That, the report said, depicts government as a corrupt 
institution. 
</P>
<P>
	``Public officials and public employees are the Rodney  
Dangerfields of TV entertainment,'' said S. Robert Lichter, the 
center's president. ``They don't get no respect. Basically, 
bureaucrats are there to pester you and politicians are there to 
steal your money and generally corrupt the system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Partnership for Trust in Government, an advocacy group  
devoted to restoring the public's confidence in government, paid 
for the study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 13:55:06 </DATE_TIME>
