<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 07:35:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago's Treasurer Found Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Over and over, the jurors heard the tape: an  
angry Miriam Santos, Chicago's city treasurer, blurting to a 
securities firm that it was ``time to belly up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The outburst proved Santos' undoing in her extortion and fraud  
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was the most damaging,'' said Clayton Quinn, a member of  
the federal jury that convicted Santos on Monday of attempting to 
extort campaign funds and five counts of fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	Santos,43, faces up to 33 months in prison when sentenced in  
July. Her felony conviction mandates her removal from office, 
according to state law. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors accused Santos, a Democrat, of pressuring  
seven brokers who oversee the investment of $2.5 billion in city 
funds to donate thousands of dollars to her failed attorney general 
campaign last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The brokers said she threatened to stop doing business with them  
unless they paid up, and ordered them cut off when none donated. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors found her guilty of attempted extortion of only Fuji  
Securities, which had a tape recording of an angry conversation 
with Santos. The tape was played repeatedly over the course of the 
two-week trial, and Quinn said it took center stage in the jury's 
deliberations. 
</P>
<P>
	On the tape, Santos demands the company donate $10,000 to her  
campaign for attorney general, telling a broker it was ``time to 
belly up'' and that ``this is no choice.'' Fuji routinely taped its 
phone calls as a precaution in case questions arose concerning the 
way a securities trade was handled. 
</P>
<P>
	Santos and her attorneys said her words on the tape may have had  
a rough edge, but were not a threat. 
</P>
<P>
	Santos was also convicted of illegally directing employees to  
perform campaign work, but acquitted of four other attempted 
extortion counts for allegedly trying to shake down other 
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:31:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Kosovo Peace Breakthrough So Far </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russia's diplomatic offensive to bring peace  
to Kosovo is getting an unexpected boost from President Clinton, 
whose top foreign policy advisers met for a second day today with 
former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. 
</P>
<P>
	The president is offering both a pause in the deadly NATO  
bombing of Yugoslavia and negotiations on a peacekeeping force for 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton made the offer Monday with softer rhetoric than he has  
used since NATO began its air campaign March 24. The message is one 
that Chernomyrdin can take to Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, with 
a little more leverage than he had on his two previous rounds of 
talks with President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Although U.S. officials said no breakthrough is expected,  
Chernomyrdin met for an hour today with Vice President Al Gore, 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, national security adviser 
Sandy Berger and Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott following 
a 2 1/2-hour meeting Clinton held with Chernomyrdin on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian Ambassador Yury Ishakov telephoned Gore's office at 8:45  
a.m. to request the meeting, a spokesman for the vice president 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Chernomyrdin was due to meet U.N. Secretary-General Kofi  
Annan in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	David Leavy, a spokesman for the National Security Council, said  
after today''s meeting that ``we continue to have constructive 
discussions'' but no breakthrough appeared imminent. 
</P>
<P>
	On Capitol Hill, the Senate today set aside Sen. John McCain's  
effort to give President Clinton unsought authority to use ``all 
necessary force'' to win in Yugoslavia. McCain bitterly accused the 
president of being ``prepared to lose a war'' rather than consider 
ground forces. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote in the Republican-led chamber was 78-22, approving a  
leadership motion to table -- or set aside -- McCain's measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, meanwhile, was flying to NATO headquarters in Brussels,  
Belgium, tonight for an update on the air war from NATO 
Secretary-General Javier Solana and then to Germany to meet with 
U.S. troops involved in humanitarian efforts and with some Kosovo 
refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright is accompanying Clinton and may meet in Bonn with the  
foreign ministers of the G-8 nations, those from Britain, Canada, 
France, Germany, Italy, Japan and Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said it is ``fundamentally  
wrong'' to conclude that what Clinton is now saying is ``somehow 
new or a softening of the position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Dole, the former Senate Republican leader who ran against  
Clinton in 1996, urged Clinton in a letter not to end the conflict 
without a NATO victory. Dole said that meant ``a defeated and 
deposed Milosevic, the withdrawal or destruction of all Serbian 
force in Kosovo and a settlement providing for the safe return of 
all Kosovar Albanians to their former homes under the protection of 
a NATO force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Emerging from the 90-minute Oval Office meeting Monday night,  
Chernomyrdin said, ``We got closer to a diplomatic solution.'' He 
did not elaborate, except to say that he and the president 
discussed ``the circumstances and the conditions'' under which NATO 
would pause in its air assault on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not trying to drag this out,'' Clinton said before  
meeting first with Chernomyrdin and then with the Rev. Jesse 
Jackson, who secured the weekend release of three U.S. soldiers who 
had been held captive in Yugoslavia for 32 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton on Monday held fast to the four key U.S. requirements  
for ending the conflict in Yugoslavia: 
</P>
<P>
	--That Milosevic withdraw more than 40,000 Serb troops currently  
in Kosovo, a province of Serbia, the dominant republic in 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	--Safe return of the hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanian  
refugees uprooted from their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	--Acceptance by Belgrade of an international security force to  
protect the refugees and Serb and other minorities in the province. 
</P>
<P>
	--Restoration of the self-rule for the Albanians who, until a  
year ago, made up about 90 percent of Kosovo's 1.8 million 
population. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, though, gestures of compromise surfaced in the  
president's remarks at a joint news conference with Japanese Prime 
Minister Keizo Obuchi, who on a visit here pledged $200 million in 
assistance for refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	On the one hand, Clinton rejected Jackson's demand that NATO  
should end its bombing and that continuing the attacks after the 
soldiers were freed showed ``an arrogance of power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Release of the three Americans is not reason enough, Clinton  
argued. Milosevic must reverse what he has done to the ethnic 
Albanian refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	But the president did offer a pause in the bombing, provided  
Milosevic accepts his demands and begins to pull out the Serbs 
troops in a way that shows he means to withdraw virtually all of 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	That reinforces a similar offer made by the United States and  
the NATO allies at their summit meeting here last month to suspend 
the bombing if Milosevic presented a verifiable scheme to both 
withdraw Serb troops and paramilitary units and reversed what the 
administration and much of the world has denounced as ``ethnic 
cleansing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There has to be a clear commitment to let the Kosovars come  
home,'' Clinton said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort, meanwhile, to at least win Russia's support,  
Clinton said the peacekeeping force that would move into Kosovo 
should be endorsed by the United Nations and be broad enough to 
include Russians, Ukrainians and troops from other countries the 
Serbs were inclined to trust. 
</P>
<P>
	He said NATO ``has to be part of it,'' but otherwise ``there is  
room for discussion within limits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic so far has insisted he would accept a force from  
Russia and other friendly or neutral countries that also is very 
lightly armed. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration leaders said Clinton had not softened U.S.  
conditions for ending the airstrikes against Yugoslavia, which in 
41 days have failed to break Milosevic's will. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's exactly what we've said all along,'' Berger said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
