<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM's April U.S. Sales Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. was the only big automaker  
whose U.S. sales dropped in April, with purchases of its cars and 
light trucks off 4 percent compared with a robust performance in 
the same month of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's largest automaker reported Tuesday its car sales  
fell nearly 5 percent while sales of its pickups, sport utility 
vehicles, vans and minivans dropped 4 percent. GM's biggest foreign 
and domestic competitors reported sales increases Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	GM's performance was slightly worse than analysts expected. Yet  
despite the year-to-year decline, GM managed to edge its U.S. 
market share just over the 30 percent barrier for the first time in 
seven months -- to 30.4 percent from 29.5 percent in March. For the 
year through April, GM's share is at 29.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is fighting to get back above 30 percent for all of  
1999 because its North American production empire is geared to 
operate profitably at that level. 
</P>
<P>
	Roy Roberts, GM's North American sales chief, said the  
year-to-year sales comparison was skewed by GM's successful 
``loyalty coupon'' discount campaign that boosted sales in April 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``It meant that this past April we were playing catch-up,''  
Roberts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year GM played down the coupons' effect, saying they were  
used in only 2.5 percent of its April retail sales. Ford and the 
then-Chrysler Corp. quickly matched GM's discounts and generated 
sales gains a year ago and again last month. 
</P>
<P>
	GM's biggest problem is a product portfolio that remains far  
heavier in cars than trucks as the U.S. market continues its 
decade-long shift toward pickups, SUVs and minivans. Trucks also 
are far more profitable than cars, which are selling at the levels 
they are only because of deep discounts. 
</P>
<P>
	``From a margin standpoint it's obvious: GM continues to lag  
DaimlerChrysler and Ford in profitability,'' said analyst Richard 
Hilgert of Fahnestock &AMP; Co. ``It also hampers their ability to gain 
market share while DaimlerChrysler and Ford are able to manufacture 
more trucks as a percentage of their output.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the entire industry, sales were up 4 percent last month. For  
the first time in many months, car sales increased at a 
fractionally higher rate than truck sales -- both were up about 4 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was foreign automakers that made the biggest percentage  
gains last month -- at the expense of the domestics. European 
automakers improved 15 percent, while Asian automakers posted a 13 
percent gain. GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler's Chrysler unit together 
were up only 1 percent in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts told reporters he was optimistic about GM's progress. He  
noted that the redesigned version of GM's best-selling vehicle, its 
full-size Chevrolet and GMC pickup, remained in high demand and was 
putting the company on pace for a record-setting year in truck 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're building momentum,'' he said. ``We are putting more  
capacity into place. Our sales lead over our domestic competition 
is the biggest it's been since before the work stoppage last year, 
which had a crippling effect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GM's market share plummeted last summer when the United Auto  
Workers virtually shut down its North American production with two 
parts plant strikes. For months afterward, the automaker cited the 
strikes' effect on its inventories for its lagging market share. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to take a position from here forward of no  
excuses,'' Roberts said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
