<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Proposes Privacy Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Contending many privacy laws have been  
overtaken by the information age, President Clinton urged Congress 
on Tuesday to bolster the rights of consumers when banks and other 
financial companies seek to share or sell information about them. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said too many consumers ``have fallen victim to abusive  
practices'' and the rule changes would give them ``the tools and 
the confidence they need to fully participate in a thriving but 
highly complex 21st century economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president's proposal comes at a time when mergers and  
consolidations have melded financial institutions of all kinds and 
given banks unprecedented access to their customers' financial and 
medical records. 
</P>
<P>
	``You should not have to worry that the results of your latest  
physical will be used to deny your application for a mortgage or a 
credit card,'' Clinton said in a ceremony in the old Executive 
Office Building. 
</P>
<P>
	The basic principle of his proposal would give Americans the  
right to decide whether information about them held by banks, 
insurance firms or securities companies is shared or sold. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all know that technology and competition have  
revolutionized the financial services industry,'' the president 
said. ``But many people ... don't have the knowledge to properly 
evaluate what is truly a dizzying array of options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president also defended the Community Reinvestment Act  
against efforts of Senate Republicans to weaken it. 
</P>
<P>
	The act, which gives banks incentives to lend money in poor  
communities, has been in effect for 20 years. But Clinton said he 
is proud that more than 90 percent of the funds provided under the 
act have come in the last six years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has not done anything to hurt bank profits, and we ought to  
stay with it,'' the president said of the law. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, chairman of the Senate Banking  
Committee, maintained his opposition to the reinvestment law 
Tuesday as the Senate began debate on sweeping legislation to let 
banks, brokerage firms and insurance companies get deeper into each 
other's businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pretty serious about'' opposing the law, Gramm told  
reporters. ``I killed the bill (over) it last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House has threatened to veto the legislation in its  
current form because it would not require banks to have 
satisfactory community reinvestment ratings from the government in 
order to merge with other financial companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton plan, which follows the outlines of legislation  
introduced in January by Sen. Paul Sarbanes D-Md., has these main 
components: 
</P>
<P>
	--Require banks and other financial institutions to tell  
consumers when they plan to share or sell their personal financial 
information, and give consumers the power to stop such a transfer. 
</P>
<P>
	--Restrict any sharing of medical information within a financial  
conglomerate. ``As banks and insurance firms merge, for example, 
consumers should not fear that the results of a physical exam could 
be used to make a credit decision,'' a White House statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Require credit-card offers of low ``teaser rates'' to  
prominently disclose when those rates expire and how costly 
repayment can be if only minimum monthly payments are made. 
</P>
<P>
	--Increase the Securities and Exchange Commission budget by $16.5  
million in the coming fiscal year to boost the surveillance and 
prosecution of fraud in stock market and other financial 
transactions over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals were hailed by a number of consumer groups.  
</P>
<P>
	``The administration's proposals, if enacted, would go a long  
way to help inject honest and fair dealing into a marketplace that 
increasingly fails to meet the needs of modest and lower income 
consumers,'' said a joint statement by the Consumer Federation of 
America and the Consumers Union. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Banking Committee adopted a proposal in March that  
would restrict the sharing of certain information among affiliated 
banks, brokerage firms and insurance companies. Under the 
provision, customers' transaction data, such as checking account 
history, still would be allowed to be shared among affiliated 
financial companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
