<HEADLINE> Ump Danley Leaves Hospital for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Umpire Kerwin Danley was released from a  
hospital Tuesday evening and returned to his home in Phoenix to see 
his family doctor and get more tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Danley left the Cincinnati Reds' 4-3 victory over the Arizona  
Diamondbacks on Monday night after he became light-headed. He 
walked off the field after the second inning and was sent to Good 
Samaritan Hospital after a test found he had high blood pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	Crew chief Ed Montague said Danley hadn't felt well for about a  
week. He said the medical tests found nothing seriously wrong with 
Danley and that the problem could be an inner-ear infection. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said he felt better today,'' Montague said, shortly after  
Danley was released. 
</P>
<P>
	Montague took over behind home plate on Monday night, when the  
last seven innings were played with three umpires. C.B. Bucknor 
flew to Cincinnati to take Danley's place for the last two games of 
the series. 
</P>
<P>
	Danley, 37, worked his first National League game in 1992. He  
became a regular member of the NL umpire staff last season. He's 
listed as 6-foot-2 and 240 pounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
