<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GAO Says Y2K Costs Not Being Tracked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some federal agencies receiving emergency  
funding to help them fix Year 2000 computer problems are not 
keeping accurate track of how they spend the money, according to 
congressional auditors. 
</P>
<P>
	The General Accounting Office, in a report issued this week,  
said that of 24 major federal agencies surveyed, only seven 
reported separately tracking Y2K costs for the fiscal years 1996 
through 1998. Five tracked only some costs, while nine did not keep 
specific Y2K spending records and three did not respond to the GAO. 
</P>
<P>
	Linda Ricci, spokeswoman for the Office of Management and  
Budget, said Y2K spending was one of the most closely monitored 
processes in the federal government and ``we are absolutely 
confident that agencies are keeping track of their spending and 
their progress and reporting it appropriately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report said that in the 1996-98 period, the agencies  
apparently spent less than half the $7.5 billion that the 
administration has said will be needed to fix the millennium bug. 
But it said that because of the lack of separate tracking, these 
costs can only be regarded as estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, who requested the  
report, said he was startled by the accounting methods. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last fall the administration was adamant that federal agencies  
would not be ready for 2000 without an emergency cash infusion for 
Y2K readiness,'' he said. ``But their spending patterns don't match 
their rhetoric.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year Congress approved an emergency spending bill that  
provided $2.25 billion for civilian agencies and $1.1 billion for 
the Defense Department to ensure there will be no disruptions from 
the glitch that may prompt some computers to mistake the year 2000 
for 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	Last February, the 24 agencies reported that their estimated Y2K  
costs for fiscal 1999 would be $2.8 billion, and $1.1 billion in 
fiscal 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the spending will go toward renovating and testing  
equipment, while agencies said they also planned to use funds for 
outreach activities, contingency planning and replacing computer 
hardware and software. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO report said Treasury -- with Agriculture and State one of  
the three agencies not providing information -- told the OMB that 
$92 million of its $253 million in Y2K funding was for non-Y2K 
information technology investments. 
</P>
<P>
	But the OMB's Ricci said that was money for IRS modernization  
that Congress took out of a fiscal 1999 spending package with 
directions to Treasury to use money from emergency funding. 
``Treasury was doing exactly what Congress was telling it to do.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
