<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Seeking Senate Candidates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrats are still searching for a few good  
candidates for the Senate for 2000, and not above looking to the 
occasional Republican or independent as part of their assault 
against a 55-45 GOP majority. 
</P>
<P>
	Party officials are talking of the possibility that Minnesota's  
state auditor, Judy Dutcher, a Republican, might switch parties and 
challenge GOP Sen. Rod Grams. Dutcher has been elected twice to her 
statewide post, and Grams is viewed as the most vulnerable 
Republican on next year's ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Torricelli, D-N.J., chairman of the Democratic campaign  
committee, said he would be interested in ``progressive people 
despite their previous affiliation'' taking a look at challenging 
Grams. 
</P>
<P>
	Dutcher, in a telephone interview, said a ``number of  
(Democratic) senators have contacted me and given me 
encouragement'' about a possible challenge to Grams. She's also 
talked with officials from Emily's List, a Washington-based 
organization with strong Democratic ties. 
</P>
<P>
	She described herself as ``pro-choice, pro-gay rights,  
pro-public education'' and a fiscal conservative, and someone who 
has won union backing in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have not made a decision one way or another,'' and won't for  
a while, Dutcher said, adding that she is also being courted to run 
as a Reform Party candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Among more conventional Democratic contenders, Rep. David Minge  
has announced creation of an exploratory committee and has begun 
raising money for a possible race against Grams. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	The independent who's attracted attention from Democratic  
recruiters is Rep. Bernard Sanders of Vermont, being urged to run 
against veteran Republican Sen. James Jeffords. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats have offered to protect Sanders' seniority rights and  
committee assignments in the Senate, as they have done in the 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Sanders is in line for a House subcommittee chairmanship  
should Democrats regain control, and seems tugged by the prospect 
of other liberal-minded lawmakers gaining House chairmanships. 
</P>
<P>
	He has told Senate Democratic recruiters he'll make up his mind  
next month. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats are looking for candidates elsewhere.  
</P>
<P>
	In Ohio, where Sen. Mike DeWine is seeking a second term, three  
Democratic lawmakers have taken themselves out of the running -- 
Reps. Ted Strickland; Sherrod Brown and Marcy Kaptur. Among the 
names that have surfaced is Joel Hyatt, son-in-in-law of former 
Sen. Howard Metzenbaum. Hyatt lost to DeWine in 1994. Former Rep. 
Dennis Eckart, now with a law firm with offices in Ohio and 
Washington, is also exploring a candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats have a different problem in New Jersey, where former  
Democratic Gov. James Florio is running for a seat being vacated by 
retiring Democrat Sen. Frank Lautenberg. When last on the ballot, 
Florio lost his bid for a second term as governor in a voters' 
revolt over higher taxes. Democratic officials are notably 
unenthusiastic about his running for the Senate. Rep. Frank Pallone 
is considering a primary challenge, and party officials have 
courted Jon Corzine, a wealthy businessman. Republican Gov. 
Christie Whitman, who ousted Florio from the statehouse, is 
expected to run. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	In California, it's the Republicans who are scratching for a  
well-established candidate. Rep. James Rogan, who played a role in 
impeachment proceedings against President Clinton, announced 
recently he wouldn't challenge Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein. 
Bill Horn, a wealthy San Diego County supervisor, has filed papers 
for an exploratory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans must defend 19 of the 34 seats on the ballot next  
year. Democratic hopes for a takeover faded early this year when 
Lautenberg, New York's Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Nevada Sen. 
Richard Bryan decided to retire. In addition, House Democratic 
Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri has been urging House members to 
stay where they are, on the theory that the party has a strong 
chance to take control of the House, and little if any prospects in 
the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., is expected to meet  
Wednesday with about two dozen rank-and-file Republicans eager for 
a floor debate on legislation to overhaul campaign finance laws. 
The Republicans, led by Rep. Chris Shays, R-Conn., have thus far 
withheld support from a Democratic-led petition drive to force the 
measure to the floor. But they're expected to tell Hastert they 
want him to let the bill get to the floor, or risk their defection 
on the Democratic initiative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
