<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Serb Terror Campaign Is Cited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MORINI, Albania (AP) -- Terrified Kosovo refugees, some with  
gunshot wounds or bruises, on Tuesday accused masked Serb fighters 
of gunning down people who refused to hand over their money in the 
latest campaign to expel ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The killings took place Sunday night northwest of Pristina, the  
Kosovo capital, according to accounts from refugees who crossed 
Tuesday into northern Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	Some put the death toll at about 100 or higher, while others  
said they saw dozens of bodies on the roadside, in cars and in a 
stream. It was impossible to independently verify the accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Izet Krasniqi, his left shoulder heavily bandaged due to a  
bullet wound, said he saw 20 to 30 people shot to death in Studime, 
about 18 miles from Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	``The police shot me,'' he said from the front seat of a relief  
agency vehicle taking him for medical treatment. He described the 
encounter tersely -- masked Serb fighters demanded his money, and 
when he said he had none, the Serbs opened fire. 
</P>
<P>
	``When they shot me, I ran,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	In a wagon hauled by a tractor, Zylfie Gerxhali and her  
12-year-old daughter wept as they told how four men -- including 
Zylfie's husband -- were killed before their eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	Zylfie Gerxhali said the masked Serb fighters stopped the wagon  
Sunday night in Studime and demanded money from her husband, Avdyl. 
When he said he had none, the Serbs took him and three others, 
including his brother, and shot them to death on the roadside. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard him shout when they shot him,'' she said. When the  
soldiers returned to the wagon, she gave them money and a necklace 
because ``they said they would kill everyone if I didn't do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A woman in a different wagon, Selvie Goguri, said she saw bodies  
lying on the roadside, in cars and in a river in Studime. She and 
others said at least 100 people died along a half-mile stretch of 
road. 
</P>
<P>
	Kosovapress, the Kosovo Liberation Army's news agency, said  
about 100 civilians were killed by Serb soldiers in the offensive. 
The bodies were reportedly hauled away by soldiers driving tractors 
and dumped in a mass grave, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 6,000 refugees crossed into northern Albania by early  
evening, most of them crammed on wagons hauled by tractor, or on 
foot. They came from various regions of Kosovo, and many said they 
had been on the move for weeks, staying in the mountains or in 
different villages until forced to move on by Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	Some people said Serb forces also separated men from other  
refugees in Vranica, in southern Kosovo, and in the Djakovica area, 
in the southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike other recent arrivals from the nearby city of Prizren,  
the refugees crossing Tuesday looked exhausted from their travels. 
At least two men had gunshot wounds and several had bruised or cut 
faces from what they said were beatings by Serb police. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, the U.N. refugee agency and local officials worked  
to persuade Kosovo refugees to leave the border region of northern 
Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray Wilkinson, a spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for  
Refugees, said officials were becoming increasingly frustrated with 
the estimated 30,000 Kosovo Albanians refusing to leave several 
camps in and around Kukes, the regional center nearest to the 
Morini border crossing. 
</P>
<P>
	Many refugees worry they will be sent off to new, unknown camps  
without finding out about relatives still in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Kukes authorities could eventually force people out,  
perhaps by declaring the area a security zone and implementing a 
kind of martial law. 
</P>
<P>
	On at least one previous occasion, police forced a few thousand  
refugees to leave one Kukes camp at dawn -- a move the UNHCR 
protested as excessive for people already driven out of their homes 
by Serb forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
