<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goldman Sachs Shares Jump 43 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Newly minted shares of Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co.  
soared 33 percent in their first day of trading Tuesday as 
investors welcomed Wall Street's elite investment bank into the 
public arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldman's shares, which trade under the symbol GS, rose to  
$70.37 1/2, a gain of $17.37 1/2 from the $53 price set in Monday's 
initial public offering of stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The jump gave Goldman a market value of $38.6 billion, instantly  
making the company worth more than Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 22 million shares changed hands, making Goldman the  
second-most actively traded issue on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Goldman ended its 130-year run as a private  
partnership, selling 69 million shares in an IPO that raised $3.66 
billion. It was the second-largest IPO in U.S. history after last 
year's $4 billion stock sale by Conoco. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry M. Paulson Jr., Goldman's chairman and chief executive  
officer, said the company went public to gain ``the flexibility to 
use publicly traded securities to finance strategic acquisitions 
that we may elect to make in the future.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
