<DOCNO> APW19990504.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 13:25:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Akron Paper Was Silent About Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- The Akron Beacon Journal reported Tuesday  
that its publisher and a reporter knew of an allegation of 
wife-beating against the city's police chief, but the newspaper 
published nothing about it for almost two months. 
</P>
<P>
	Publisher John L. Dotson Jr. said Chief Edward Irvine phoned him  
Oct. 15 to say that his wife, Geneva, ``had been drinking, fell on 
the steps carrying a vacuum cleaner and that she was in the 
hospital.'' He quoted Irvine as saying his wife said he had pushed 
her. 
</P>
<P>
	Dotson said he told Irvine he was ``not the conduit to the  
newsroom'' but that he would watch out for the story and, if one 
were in preparation, make certain Irvine got the opportunity to 
respond. 
</P>
<P>
	When the incident did not appear on the newspaper's budget of  
planned stories for several days, Dotson said, ``I figured there 
wasn't a story and stopped checking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Oct. 16, Irvine summoned members of his department's Internal  
Affairs Unit, which investigates misconduct by police officers, to 
his office and ordered them to investigate his wife's complaint, 
the paper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	At about the same time, the newspaper reported, the chief also  
talked to Beacon Journal police reporter Robert Hoiles, telling 
him, ``I want to tell you something in confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hoiles recognized that he was torn between obligations to his  
employer and his promise to a news source but decided to remain 
silent and not betray a confidence, the Beacon Journal said. He has 
refused to say anything other than he was informed of the statement 
Mrs. Irvine made at the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoiles has since been moved from the police beat and given  
another reporting assignment. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, police investigators interviewed Mrs. Irvine,  
who denied that her husband had harmed her. She told officers the 
reason she had said originally that he had attacked her was that 
she was embarrassed that she lost track of her dosages of her 
medication. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't hit me,'' officers quoted her as saying.  
</P>
<P>
	The investigation quickly wound down, with police interviewing  
no neighbors, friends or relatives, the newspaper reported. The 
final police report concluded there was no substantiation of 
domestic violence. 
</P>
<P>
	However, on Dec. 10 someone phoned another Beacon Journal  
reporter, Bob Dyer, urging him to go the police department and ask 
to see incident report No. 98034694, which police later said had 
been inadvertently misfiled and was not discovered and filed 
properly until Dec. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	After obtaining the report, Dyer wrote a story about the  
investigation, which the paper published Dec. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's followup story about the investigation was accompanied  
by a column by Dotson. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, in hindsight, I was misled and may not have been as  
alert as I should have been to a significant possible news story 
involving a major department of our city government,'' the 
publisher wrote. ``I may have erred. If so, I can assure you, our 
readers, that I won't make the same mistake again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irvine denies asking either Dotson or Hoiles to withhold  
coverage of the incident, the Beacon Journal reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
