<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *Art Aylesworth    	
</P>
<P>
	RONAN, Mont. (AP) -- Art Aylesworth, ``the bluebird man'' of  
Montana, whose devotion to the colorful mountain bluebird led to 
the placing of more than 35,000 nest boxes in Montana, died 
Saturday of cancer. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Aylesworth was an early participant in state conservation  
organizations, pioneering efforts in goose nesting sites throughout 
the Mission Valley and other habitat restoration work. 
</P>
<P>
	He became widely known among conservationists as ``the bluebird  
man'' because of his quarter-century of passion for the spectacular 
mountain bird. 
</P>
<P>
	It began with a few nest boxes he built from scrap lumber at his  
ranch in 1974. He began giving away his boxes to anyone willing to 
put them out and to monitor their success in fledging baby 
bluebirds, a species whose natural habitat in the cavities of old 
trees had been dramatically reduced by logging. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mountain Bluebird Trails group that he founded 20 years ago,  
and headed until his death, estimated he and his volunteers had 
built and given away more than 35,000 bluebird nest boxes. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Daniel N. Cooke    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Retired police Lt. Daniel N. Cooke, a Police  
Department spokesman for 22 years and technical adviser to movies 
and television programs such as ``Dragnet'' and ``Adam 12,'' died 
April 30 of cancer. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooke was the department's most prominent spokesman for many  
years before his retirement in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	As the department's technical adviser to the entertainment  
industry he reviewed television and movie scripts. He became a 
friend of ``Dragnet'' star and producer Jack Webb, who created the 
``just the facts, ma'am'' image of Los Angeles police detectives. 
</P>
<P>
	In syndicated reruns, ``Dragnet'' was called ``Badge 714'' --  
Cooke's badge number. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooke joined the Los Angeles Police Department in 1953, walking  
a downtown beat before becoming press relations officer in 1964. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Edward Davis    	
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Edward Davis, a one-time mechanic who became the  
first black American to own a new car dealership, died Monday of 
congestive heart failure. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis worked at a Dodge plant before selling cars at a  
ChryslerPlymouth dealership. Although he wasn't allowed to sell on 
the showroom floor with the white salespeople, he successfully 
promoted himself in the black community. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1938, he opened Davis Motors Sales, a used car lot in  
downtown Detroit. In 1940, it became a Studebaker dealership. He 
kept the franchise until the manufacturer closed in 1956. In 
November 1963, he was awarded a Chrysler-Plymouth dealership. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis retired in 1971 and became the manager for Detroit's  
Department of Street Railway Systems. He continued to work as a 
consultant to minority auto dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, the National Association of Minority Automobile Dealers  
created the annual Edward Davis Pioneer Award. A scholarship fund 
has been established in his honor to help blacks pursue careers in 
the automobile industry. In January, Davis became the first black 
man to be inducted into the Automotive Hall of Fame Museum in 
Dearborn. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Ernest Gross    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ernest Gross, a former State Department legal  
adviser and delegate to the United Nations, died Sunday. He was 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Gross, an international lawyer, was legal counsel to U.N.  
Assistant Secretary General Ralph Bunche and to U.N. Secretary 
General Dag Hammarskjold. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1948, Gross helped introduce a convention against genocide to  
the United Nations. In the 1960s, while in private practice, he 
sued the South African government in the World Court because of its 
apartheid policies. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Billy Hendrix    	
</P>
<P>
	SIMMESPORT, La. (AP) -- Billy ``Red'' Hendrix, captain of  
Louisiana State University's 1958 national championship football 
team, died Tuesday at age 64. 
</P>
<P>
	He had Alzheimer's disease.  
</P>
<P>
	Hendrix played left defensive end for LSU. He was a senior in  
1958, when the Tigers went 10-0 to win the national championship, 
then defeated Clemson 7-0 in the Sugar Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	After graduating, Hendrix coached at high schools and at  
Northeast Louisiana University. He finished at Bunkie High, where 
he was first a coach and then a principal. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Harry L. Kavetas    	
</P>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Eastman Kodak Co. chief financial officer  
Harry L. Kavetas, who helped engineer nearly 20,000 job cuts at the 
photography company to counter Japanese gains in the U.S. market, 
died Tuesday of an apparent heart attack. He was 61. 
</P>
<P>
	A longtime executive at IBM, Kavetas was hired as Kodak's chief  
financial officer in 1994. He took over with much of a new strategy 
in place, to slash overhead and lay off 10,000 workers. It was 
aimed at defending Kodak's mainstay photographic businesses from 
assault by Japanese nemesis Fuji. 
</P>
<P>
	But in 1997, Kavetas and his boss, CEO George Fisher, resorted  
to even deeper cutbacks when Fuji slashed film prices in the United 
States and grabbed market share on Kodak's dominant home turf. 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of this year, Kodak expects to trim more than $1  
billion in costs by eliminating almost one-fifth of its worldwide 
payroll of 100,500. The company has seen a sharp rebound in sales 
and profits in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	At Kodak, Kavetas was appointed executive vice president in  
September 1994 and elected to the board of directors in May 1997. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Meredith Morgan    	
</P>
<P>
	BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- Meredith Morgan, who helped guide the  
University of California, Berkeley, optometry school through 67 of 
its 75 years, died Saturday of lung cancer. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	Known for his research into basic mechanisms of eye focus and  
alignment, Morgan was a professor for 33 years and dean of the 
School of Optometry from 1960 to 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	His research into the elements of binocular vision resulted in  
two dozen papers laying out a basic understanding of how the two 
eyes work together to focus and converge on objects at close range. 
He also contributed to textbooks on the vision of children and the 
elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan continued to be active with the university after his  
tenure and wrote the lead chapter in the recent book, ``Cal 
Optometry -- The First 75 Years.'' 

</P>
<P>
                         *Robert R. Scherer    	
</P>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Robert R. Scherer, the vice president and  
market manager for Clear Channel Broadcasting, died Tuesday of 
cancer. He was 57. 
</P>
<P>
	Scherer was hired by WHAS Inc. in 1963. He was an account  
executive, sales manager and general manager for WHAS/WAMZ until 
September 1996, when WHAS Inc. was sold to Clear Channel 
Broadcasting. 
</P>
<P>
	At Clear Channel, Scherer was named vice president and added  
market manager to his responsibilities in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	He was also a past president and director of the Kentucky  
Broadcasters Association and a chairman and executive committee 
member of the Kentucky Derby Festival. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Scherer received the Al Temple Award for outstanding  
contributions to the Kentucky Broadcasters Association and the 
National Association of Broadcasters. The following year, he was 
honored by the Society of Professional Journalists for a lifetime 
of distinguished service. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife and three children.  

</P>
<P>
                        *J. John Sepkoski Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- J. John Sepkoski Jr., a University of Chicago  
paleontologist known for his research of fossil records and the 
history of marine animal life, died Saturday of heart failure 
related to high blood pressure. He was 50. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Sepkoski's major accomplishments was analyzing data  
dating as far back as 600 million years and using it to study the 
history of oceanic life, said Douglas Erwin, a research 
paleontologist at the Smithsonian Institution and editor of the 
journal Paleobiology. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1980s, Sepkoski and a colleague developed a theory that  
catastrophic extinctions of marine animals may have occurred about 
every 26 million years during the past 250 million years. These 
periodic events included the extinction of dinosaurs -- events that 
had been previously considered random occurrences. 
</P>
<P>
	The controversial theory helped shape the view that mass  
extinctions of land and marine animals may have been caused by an 
external force, such as the impact of a comet or asteroid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
