<HEADLINE> Waste Management To Pay Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Waste Management Inc. has agreed to pay $756,680  
and extend job offers to 15 job applicants who alleged race and sex 
discrimination in the Chicago area. 
</P>
<P>
	An arm of the U.S. Labor Department brought the allegations  
after finding in routine reviews that the garbage hauler had denied 
female and minority applicants equal opportunity for hiring. The 
agency said their qualifications were equal to or greater than the 
white men who were hired. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said the company denied truck-driving jobs to five  
women and 10 black or Hispanic men in Cicero and Morris, Ill., and 
in Portage, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	``These were unfortunate and regrettable occurrences involving  
just a few of our operations,'' said company spokesman Bill 
Plunkett. ``Waste Management recognizes its obligations as a 
federal contractor to comply with both the letter and the spirit of 
the law, and we try to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plunkett said Waste Management chose to resolve the issue  
through the settlement but did not admit any violation in doing so. 
``We have taken steps to reinforce our policies in this area,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston-based Waste Services last year unveiled a plan to buy  
Waste Management and move its Oak Brook headquarters to Houston but 
retain the Waste Management name. The deal has since been 
completed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 14:05:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Broker Accountability Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government's top securities regulator,  
noting that ads for online trading often resemble lottery 
commercials, is urging Internet brokerages to better warn their 
customers about the risks that come with investing on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Explaining clearly to customers ... would go a long way toward  
reducing the complaints pouring into the SEC, Congress and firms,'' 
Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``To every online firm, I challenge you to meaningfully  
communicate with your customers,'' Levitt said in a speech at the 
National Press Club. ``Talk in realistic terms; let them know their 
options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said an SEC review of online brokerage account agreements  
found that ``almost none'' of them discuss trading risks or what 
customers should do if there is a computer system outage. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC chief also said online firms need to ensure they have  
adequate computer system capacity to handle the swarms of new 
customers, asserting that the brokers have a legal obligation to 
provide efficient execution of trading orders. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt said he's not convinced the market watchdog agency needs  
a new set of regulations for online investing, but he did not rule 
out that possibility in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	He also criticized advertisements by some Internet brokers which  
he said more closely resemble commercials for the playing the 
lottery by promising quick riches. 
</P>
<P>
	``In today's bull market there may be an increasing population  
of tow-truck drivers who now own their own islands as a result of 
online investing. ... (But) I'm worried these commercials step over 
the line and border on irresponsibility,'' he said, referring to 
one widely aired ad campaign on television, Levitt said, 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt's remarks come as the SEC and the National Association of  
Securities Dealers, a self-policing brokers' group, have been 
investigating online brokerages nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to looking for violations of securities laws, the  
investigators are examining how well firms execute orders and warn 
customers of trading risks. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt said SEC auditors already have inspected online firms  
representing 80 percent of the electronic-trading market. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters say that by year's end, 10 million amateur investors  
will be trading at least occasionally over the Internet, and online 
customers will account for about a quarter of all retail stock 
trades. The biggest online brokerages include Charles Schwab, 
E-Trade Group, Ameritrade, Datek Online, DLJdirect and Discover 
Brokerage. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt also expressed concern about that rising popularity of  
day trading, a practice in which investors scope out fast-moving 
stocks, buying and selling them quickly to profit from the sudden 
price swings. Many day-trading companies sell training courses and 
special software to ordinary investors who want to try the risky, 
lightning-speed strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Providing day-trading opportunities is not itself against the  
law, but these firms should be on notice that they ... must operate 
within the existing rules,'' Levitt said. He added that firms 
should ensure that their day-trading strategies are suitable for 
customers' financial circumstances and trading skills. 
</P>
<P>
	State securities regulators also have been scrutinizing  
day-trading firms and a handful of them, particularly in 
Massachusetts, have filed fraud charges. 
</P>
<P>
	William Galvin, Massachusetts' secretary of state, announced  
Monday a settlement with All-Tech Investment Group in which the big 
day-trading firm agreed to pay a $50,000 fine and reimburse 
customers $228,000. 
</P>
<P>
	All-Tech neither admitted to nor denied wrongdoing in the  
settlement, but agreed not to sign up any new customers in the 
state for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Operators of day-trading firms acknowledge that the strategy is  
not right for everyone, but contend state regulators are unfairly 
tarnishing the industry because of a few rogue firms that may have 
misled investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The NASD, which operates the Nasdaq Stock Market, has been  
considering since March a new rule that would require day-trading 
firms to screen investors and warn them in writing of the risks. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 06:15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Auto Sales Rise in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Consumers can't seem to get enough new cars and  
trucks, pushing the auto industry's sales boom into its second 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the major automakers that reported April sales results  
Monday, total sales were up 7.5 percent. Ford Motor Co., 
DaimlerChrysler AG and Japan's three biggest automakers each 
reported gains over the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Monthly year-to-year sales comparisons have been up through the  
past 13 months except in July and August, when total sales were 
artificially depressed as two strikes against General Motors Corp. 
restricted its supply. 
</P>
<P>
	GM remained the only major automaker to report its sales today.  
Analysts expected it to report flat to slightly lower sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``Barring any surprises from GM ... it looks like another  
gangbuster month,'' said analyst David Healy of Burnham Securities 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The reasons for April's improvement were familiar: a robust  
economy and consumers confident enough about the future to take on 
the increased debt of a new car or truck. 
</P>
<P>
	``The economy has the legs of a marathon runner,'' said Yale  
Gieszl, a vice president of Toyota Motor Sales USA Inc. ``Consumers 
look at interest rates, inflation, Wall Street and the job market 
and have every reason to be confident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said its April sales were up 7 percent last month, compared  
with April 1998. Sales of light trucks set an April record -- the 
company's 12th straight monthly record for pickups, vans, minivans 
and sport utility vehicles combined. Car sales were up 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures do not include Ford's Volvo AB or Jaguar Cars units,  
each of which reported its U.S. sales rose 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said demand is so strong that it is again increasing its  
second-quarter production schedule, this time by 20,000 additional 
vehicles. With last month's 30,000 increase, Ford now plans to 
build just over 1.26 million cars and trucks during the April-June 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a somewhat unusual month at DaimlerChrysler's Chrysler  
unit, in that its biggest improvement came in car sales. Total 
sales improved 2 percent; cars were up 6 percent while truck sales 
were flat. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chrysler unit sells more than twice as many light trucks as  
cars. But its minivan sales fell 19 percent just as the spring 
buying season was heating up, and pickup sales were flat. Healy 
said April's minivan performance was the ``hangover'' of 
incentive-driven sales in March that depleted inventories. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamie Jameson, vice president of sales and marketing, said truck  
sales also suffered from a tough comparison to April 1998 when 
sales were boosted by a coupon war launched by GM. 
</P>
<P>
	The German-American automaker posted an 18 percent gain in sales  
of highly profitable SUVs. In fact, SUV sales at the former 
Chrysler Corp. have set monthly records in 17 of the last 18 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota Motor Corp. posted its best April ever in the United  
States, with sales up nearly 10 percent. Its 7 percent rise in car 
sales was led once again by the Camry, the nation's bestseller, 
with sales up 21 percent for its best April ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest Japanese automaker also was boosted by a 13.5  
percent rise in truck sales: the hot-selling Lexus RX300 SUV was up 
78 percent, while; the Sienna minivan had its best month ever with 
a 25 percent increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda Motor Co. also benefited from improved truck sales, up 53  
percent. Overall sales improved 4 percent, dragged down by a 3 
percent decline in car sales. Honda's new Odyssey minivan posted a 
211 percent gain, while sales of the CR-V compact SUV improved 41 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of Honda's top-seller, the Accord sedan, were flat while  
sales of the Civic subcompact were off 7 percent. But buyers 
flocked to the Acura TL luxury sedan, whose sales nearly doubled. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan Motor Co. had its biggest improvement in months: total  
sales were up 21 percent, led by a 26 percent gain in trucks. Its 
redesigned Quest minivan, for example, nearly doubled sales over 
April 1998. Car sales were up nearly 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Volkswagen AG said it has its best April in the United States in  
19 years, with sales up 29.5 percent on the strength of a new 
product lineup. Its redesigned Jetta sedan led the sales drive, 
with its best single month since the original version was 
introduced in 1980. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
