<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Sidetracking Ground War Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. John McCain concedes most of his  
colleagues don't back his move to give President Clinton unsought 
authority to use ``all necessary force'' to win in Yugoslavia -- 
including ground troops if needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Top administration officials joined with Senate leaders in  
urging senators to brush aside the attempt by McCain and a few 
other senators in a showdown vote today. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, an Arizona Republican and GOP presidential hopeful,  
accused Clinton and his top national security advisers of working 
against their own interests in actively opposing the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	``But his irresponsibility does not excuse Congress,'' McCain  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Senate Minority  
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., asked the Senate to ``table,'' or set 
aside, McCain's proposal -- a move that would end all Kosovo floor 
debate for now. Senators on both side of the aisle said the 
leadership motion would prevail. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the measure would nominally strengthen Clinton's  
hand, the White House, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and 
Defense Secretary William Cohen worked hard throughout Monday for 
its defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration and its congressional allies feared that  
keeping the measure alive would open the way to a more contentious 
debate and more efforts to restrict presidential authority -- as the 
House had done last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The House voted to require Clinton to seek advance congressional  
approval before injecting ``ground elements.'' And, on a 213-213 
tie, it even failed to support the ongoing NATO air campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation by McCain, Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., and five  
others would authorize the president to use ``all necessary force 
and other means'' to win in Kosovo. Ground troops weren't spelled 
out, but sponsors said that's what was intended. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're making a horrible mistake here'' in not supporting a  
ground-troops option for Clinton, Biden told the Senate Monday 
night. ``We're not demanding that he use ground troops. We're 
saying to him, we want to make sure that you understand that you've 
got to win this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Robert Byrd of West Virginia, a senior and influential  
Democratic member, called the McCain-Biden legislation ``a bold and 
possibly risky stroke,'' particularly since Clinton did not ask for 
authority to expand the military campaign with ground forces. 
</P>
<P>
	In filing his legislation, McCain unwittingly triggered a  
provision of the 1973 War Powers Act that required the resolution 
to be brought to the floor on Monday -- and to be acted on by no 
later than today. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a new poll showed that most Americans believe  
Congress should have the final authority to decide whether the 
United States should continue the current airstrikes in Kosovo or 
send in ground troops. However, the CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll 
showed that 54 percent approve of the way Clinton has handled the 
situation in Kosovo, while only 41 percent say they approve of the 
way Congress has handled it. 
</P>
<P>
	Support for U.S. participation in the NATO airstrikes remains  
steady at 58 percent, with 41 percent saying they strongly favor 
the strikes and only 27 percent saying they strongly oppose them. 
Most Americans oppose sending U.S. ground troops into a combat 
situation in the region -- unchanged since April -- with 42 percent 
saying they strongly oppose that move. Two-thirds, however, favor 
sending U.S. ground troops to serve as peacekeepers in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey of 1,014 adult Americans was conducted April 30-May  
2. Questions have a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage 
points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 09:25:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines May Take Control of PAL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- The government is considering a  
temporary takeover of troubled Philippine Airlines to help it look 
for fresh capital and avoid being closed, President Joseph Estrada 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Estrada said the step would be a last resort if PAL chairman  
Lucio Tan is unable to raise the $200 million in new capital needed 
for its rehabilitation plan by an early June deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will take over PAL if that is necessary,'' Estrada told  
reporters. ``The bottom line is, I want to see to it that PAL will 
continue flying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said the government would  
take over PAL's management but would not infuse money into the 
troubled carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Estrada's administration has adopted a policy of not undertaking  
costly bailouts of beleaguered private and state-run companies. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL is mired in debts of more than $2.2 billion, of which more  
than two-thirds are owed to the U.S. and European credit agencies 
which helped finance the airline's ambitious but ill-timed fleet 
modernization program. 
</P>
<P>
	The capital infusion is a key element of a rehabilitation plan  
that also calls for cutting the airline's fleet to 22 planes from 
54 and slashing the labor force to about 3,000 from 8,000. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL submitted additional details of the plan on Tuesday, meeting  
a deadline set by Manila's Securities and Exchange Commission. The 
SEC had earlier rejected the plan for being too vague and failing 
to identify potential investors. 
</P>
<P>
	However, PAL's new document did not identify any interested  
investors other than Tan and did not divulge the basis for its 
future income projections as sought by the SEC. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC will review the filing and decide later whether it is  
sufficient. PAL's management must also meet a June 4 SEC deadline 
for it to come up with the $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	SEC chairman Perfecto Yasay has said he will order the  
liquidation of PAL if the capital is not raised by the deadline and 
other key requirements of the rehabilitation plan are not met. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline's major creditors, including the U.S. Export-Import  
bank and European export credit agencies, initially backed the plan 
but threatened to scuttle it after Tan reassumed direct management 
control of the airline last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The creditors have said they want PAL run by professional  
managers. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan, one of the country's richest men, owns 70 percent of the  
airline and has interests in banking, beer and tobacco. He was a 
major contributor to Estrada's campaign last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan has said he is willing to organize a group of investors to  
raise the $200 million and pledged to provide half of the total 
himself, but the government is uncertain whether he can do so by 
the deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan was set to fly to Germany to try to woo Deutsche Lufthansa  
AG to help recapitalize PAL, Trade and Industry Secretary Jose 
Pardo said. 
</P>
<P>
	As a fallback for Tan's efforts, the government has begun talks  
with two other potential investors, Pardo said, but declined to 
give details. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 20:41:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> At Least 43 Die in Plains Tornadoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Rescue crews looking for signs of life  
picked through shattered homes, twisted trees and mangled cars 
Tuesday after a swarm of astonishingly powerful tornadoes chewed up 
entire neighborhoods in Oklahoma and Kansas and killed at least 43 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	Even in an area accustomed to twisters and strong thunderstorms  
-- this is, after all, the region known as Tornado Alley, and spring 
is an especially dangerous time of year -- the twisters' wrath was 
extraordinary. 
</P>
<P>
	One monstrous funnel cloud skipped across the ground for four  
hours and was classified F-5, the most powerful tornado there is, 
with winds of more than 260 mph. It cut a path one mile wide, and 
along with the other twisters tore up 60 miles of the flat 
countryside. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is crazy,'' said Eric Peterson of Haysville, Kan., a  
suburb of Wichita, after a twister pushed a tree into his bedroom. 
``I have been in typhoons in the South Pacific and in hurricanes, 
but this tops it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tornadoes were spawned by a string of extreme thunderstorms  
that unleashed 76 twisters in 5 states on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The death toll was 38 in Oklahoma and five in Kansas, including  
a month-old baby in Haysville. 
</P>
<P>
	The same system produced a tornado in northeast Texas on  
Tuesday, leaving one person dead. In southern Arkansas, 
thunderstorms spawned tornadoes, large hail and heavy rain, leaving 
thousands of people without electricity. Several houses and a 
church were damaged. There were no immediate reports of any 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's tornado outbreak was the nation's deadliest since 42  
people were killed last year in Florida. It was also the deadliest 
such tragedy to hit Oklahoma since 1947, when a twister killed 113 
people in Woodward. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds were injured, including 500 in Oklahoma City and more  
than 100 in Wichita. At least 1,500 businesses and homes were 
destroyed or heavily damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	Cars were tossed across highways and crushed like soda cans.  
Houses were smashed into piles of splintered timbers and brick. The 
ground was scoured bare in places, stripped of trees. The air 
smelled like sawdust. Baby pictures floated down the streets in 
storm water. 
</P>
<P>
	Jon Hansen, an assistant fire chief in Oklahoma City, likened  
the scene to that of the Oklahoma bombing in 1995: ``It looks like 
the Murrah Building, but instead of nine stories tall, it's spread 
out over a large area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the death toll could have been worse if people  
had not heeded warnings to take cover underground. Local TV 
stations went live with coverage of the developing storm at least 
two hours before it hit the heavily populated Oklahoma City area. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating estimated that hundreds of millions  
of dollars of damage was done. He mobilized the National Guard to 
help with the rescue, and tanks joined police and fire vehicles in 
blocking streets where the heaviest destruction occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescuers conducted two preliminary searches for victims, then  
brought in bulldozers to clear away heavy debris in a third search 
during the afternoon. At least one woman was found alive in a 
trailer park. 
</P>
<P>
	``There may be someone, somewhere, still out there, under the  
clutter,'' said John Vears, one of the hundreds of volunteer 
searchers and emergency workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Most homes in Oklahoma are built on concrete slabs and don't  
have cellars where people can take shelter. When a tornado draws 
near, people are urged to take shelter in a structurally sound, 
centrally located space in the house, such as a bathroom, a closet 
or under a staircase. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Dennis McCarthy, chief meteorologist for the National  
Weather Service in Norman, said some deaths may have been 
unavoidable. ``With a storm of this intensity and this magnitude, 
sometimes even if you do the right things, sometime you just don't 
have enough shelter,'' McCarthy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wendy Knapp, a Red Cross volunteer at an evacuation shelter in  
Newcastle, said she was taking her son to T-ball practice but 
turned around when a funnel cloud came into view. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in several of them in my lifetime. But this was a  
big one,'' she said. ``This did more damage than I've ever seen in 
my life. There are dead cattle in people's yard, trees, debris. 
Grass was ripped up. At some homes, the foundations were ripped 
up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christy Smith was visiting her grandparents when a tornado tore  
through her neighborhood in Midwest City, just outside Oklahoma 
City. She spent Tuesday rummaging through the remains of what once 
was her home. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we got here, I could only tell it was our house because  
of the bushes,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lisa Poahty was still in shock as she looked at her neighbor's  
car, which had been hurled into her living room. Her son's mattress 
was in a tree and the family car was 100 yards away in a neighbor's 
yard. 
</P>
<P>
	She was able to salvage something, however: She found a small  
black bag on the floor, opened it and pulled out a glass bottle. 
``My perfume survived,'' she said. ``It was my favorite.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials estimated the tornadoes traveled as much as 80 miles  
after forming 45 miles south of Oklahoma City on Monday afternoon. 
Over the next 20 hours, as many as four dozen tornadoes developed. 
The same system spawned the Kansas tornado, which struck about 8:30 
p.m. Monday. It cut a path 12 miles long and three miles wide. 
</P>
<P>
	In southern Wichita, about 270 homes and businesses were  
damaged, including about 100 homes in two lakeside trailer parks. 
At least 150 houses and 27 businesses were damaged or destroyed in 
Haysville. 
</P>
<P>
	Darrell Zehr, 44, figured he would be safe inside the  
cinderblock warehouse where he was working when the tornado struck 
Haysville. Then he was lifted 4 feet in the air and dropped back 
down. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of a sudden I couldn't breathe,'' he said. ``The wind was  
knocked out of me. The roof fell on me. The wall fell on me.'' He 
marveled at how he survived with merely a bruised finger. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton declared disaster areas in 11 Oklahoma  
counties and one Kansas county and plans to tour the devastation 
this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the surreal images in the aftermath of the storm:  
</P>
<P>
	-- In a high school parking lot next to a row of flattened  
houses, a dead gray horse lay between cars after being been blown 
in from the surrounding countryside. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Officials reported that part of a wing apparently snapped off  
a small plane parked at a rural airport and drifted for 40 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Anna Knerr, 73, sat in the Midwest City Senior Center,  
mud-stained and slightly injured. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been through the war in Germany. I've had bombs fall all  
around me. Now I've been in a tornado,'' she said. ``It's a feeling 
I can't describe. Everything was falling on me, two-by-fours and 
insulation.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
