<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oklahoma, Kansas in Tornado Alley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The death and devastation inflicted on  
Oklahoma and Kansas illustrates once again why the region is called 
Tornado Alley. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not unusual to have tornadoes in Oklahoma and Kansas at  
this time of year. It is unusual to have 76 (reports of) tornadoes 
over multiple states in a seven-hour period,'' said John Jones, 
deputy director of the National Weather Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The vicious twisting winds that can destroy anything in their  
path occur more often in this region than anywhere else, the result 
of a unique combination of geography and climate. 
</P>
<P>
	Here, dry air from America's West meets warm, moist air flowing  
north from the Gulf of Mexico. As happened Monday, this encounter 
can turn violent. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know what conditions were there to bring about the  
thunderstorms and tornadoes, but to say why there was such a large 
outbreak, no we don't know. ... There was no way for us, or anyone, 
to know there would be'' so many tornadoes, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tornadoes aren't exclusive to Tornado Alley. They have struck in  
every state and can occur at any time of the year, though they 
prefer the spring and summer. 
</P>
<P>
	In concentration of tornadoes, Oklahoma tops the nation. Between  
1880 and 1989, it had 19.7 tornadoes per 10,000 square miles, the 
most in the nation, according to calculations done by researcher 
Thomas P. Grazulis in his massive study, ``Significant Tornadoes 
1880-1989.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But when it comes to the most violent storms -- F5 on the Fujita  
scale -- Kansas has recorded the most with 12 over that period, 
Grazulis reported. The Fujita scale ranks the damage done by 
twisters on a scale of F0-F5, with F5 the strongest. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Jones explained, there was a dry line on the ground,  
a north-south line with dry air to the west, moist air to the east. 
Overhead there were strong winds blowing from the south and 
southwest between 5,000 feet and 10,000 feet, while above that, up 
to 20,000 feet, the winds were from the west. Warm, moist air 
originating in the Gulf of Mexico was pulled upward by the strong 
overhead winds. 
</P>
<P>
	As moist air rises, the water condenses into clouds. When they  
encounter the area of shear -- where winds are moving in different 
directions -- the clouds can begin to spin into a storm. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not rare to have one or two of these ingredients, it's  
not rare to have all three of them at the same time, to have them 
produce thunderstorms and a few tornadoes,'' Jones said, ``But to 
get this type of outbreak is rare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By most definitions, Tornado Alley extends from north-central  
Texas through central Oklahoma, Kansas and Nebraska into the 
Dakotas, the north-south line where moist and dry air collide time 
after time. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida is another focus for heavy tornado activity, both early  
in the spring as warming conditions bring battling air masses 
there, and later in the year when hurricanes can spawn twisters. 
</P>
<P>
	A third tornado focus is the so-called Dixie Alley, which runs  
from northeast Texas to northern Alabama, then skips over the 
southern Appalachians and reforms in North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	While Oklahoma has the greatest concentration of tornadoes and  
Kansas is struck by the most violent ones, Texas is far and away 
the most twister-prone state. 
</P>
<P>
	Between 1950 and 1994, federal records show 5,490 tornadoes  
reported in the Lone Star State. Oklahoma came second at 2,300, 
followed by Kansas with 2,110 and Florida with 2,009. 
</P>
<P>
	Others with 1,000 tornadoes or more during that period were  
Nebraska, 1,673; Iowa, 1,374; Missouri, 1,166; South Dakota, 1,139; 
Illinois, 1,137; Colorado, 1,113; Louisiana, 1,086, and 
Mississippi, 1,039. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
