<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 13:55:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Held In Colo. Shooting Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- The man who sold a semiautomatic handgun  
to the two Columbine High killers went shooting with them in the 
woods three times in the month before the bloodbath, the man's 
lawyer said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Manes, 22, admitted selling the semiautomatic TEC DC-9 to  
one of the teen-agers but did not know it would be used in the 
April 20 attack that left 15 dead, including the gunmen, said 
attorney Robert Ransome. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're up shooting in the woods with a bunch of kids who  
love to shoot at things, the obvious assumption is, `Hey, they like 
guns and they like to shoot,''' Ransome said. ``He never got to 
that point, thinking what they might do with it. It just never 
crossed his mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manes, a computer programmer and former Columbine student, was  
booked on suspicion of providing a handgun to a minor, punishable 
by up to six years in prison. His lawyer is trying to work out a 
deal with prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	Ransome would not say whether Manes sold the two teen-agers  
ammunition, how much he charged for the gun, where they went 
shooting, who else accompanied them or what Manes may have known 
about the law involving gun sales to minors. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, stormed Columbine on  
April 20, hurling explosives and blasting away with four guns. They 
killed 13 people and wounding 23 students before committing 
suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	They used the TEC DC-9 purchased from Manes in late February and  
three guns -- two shotguns and a rifle -- that had been legally 
purchased by Klebold's girlfriend, Robyn Anderson, investigators 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Colorado law, an 18-year-old without a felony record can  
furnish minors with rifles and shotguns. Investigators have 
characterized Miss Anderson as a witness, not a suspect. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators believe Harris and Klebold were the only two  
gunmen but are looking at the possibility that others may have been 
involved in the conspiracy. They are also performing ballistics 
tests to determine which weapons fired the fatal shots; Manes could 
face more serious charges if the TEC DC-9 was used to kill someone. 
</P>
<P>
	Manes is the first person arrested and connected to the school  
attack. He bought the pistol at a gun show last fall, Ransome said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A third party knew Mark had this certain weapon and also knew  
Eric and Dylan were looking for weapons. He put them together,'' 
the lawyer said. ``Mark was not friends with Eric and Dylan. He did 
not hang out with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said the middleman was a pizza shop employee who  
worked with Harris and Klebold. 
</P>
<P>
	Three times in the month prior to April 20, the three, joined by  
an unspecified number of other people, went into the woods, 
``shooting automatic weapons,'' Ransome said. He would not if the 
weapons were fully automatic. 
</P>
<P>
	Automatic weapons, which fire continuously as long the trigger  
is down, are illegal. Semiautomatic weapons fire once with every 
pull of the trigger. But semiautomatic pistols are sometimes 
loosely referred to as ``automatic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A homemade video obtained by investigators shows Harris and  
Klebold practicing with weapons in a mountain setting, supposedly 
with two men and a woman, the Denver Post reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Ransome said Manes has cooperated with authorities but does not  
know of any other person who may have been involved in the 
massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	Manes attended Columbine for 1 1/2 years before transferring to an  
alternative high school. He later attended Arapahoe Community 
College. 
</P>
<P>
	His parents, Michael and Diane, are longtime gun opponents who  
have never kept a weapon in the home, Ransome said. Mrs. Manes 
belongs to a coalition that lobbies for gun control laws. 
</P>
<P>
	As Columbine students attended classes a second day at Chatfield  
Senior High School, workers began dismantling a huge makeshift 
memorial of flowers, stuffed animals, balloons, cards and letters 
honoring the shooting victims. 
</P>
<P>
	About half of the flowers left at small memorials throughout the  
240-acre park next to the school will be donated to the Littleton 
Fire Department, where they will be turned into potpourri for 
Columbine students. 
</P>
<P>
	Teddy bears, notes, posters, silk flowers and other mementos  
will be stored in boxes and catalogued for a permanent memorial 
someday. 
</P>
<P>
	Amy Pomering, a neighborhood resident, said it's time for the  
temporary memorial to come down: ``The longer it stays, the harder 
it is for the families.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
