<DOCNO> APW19990504.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 16:15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Steel Efforts Working </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's efforts to combat unfair  
steel shipments from Japan and other countries are showing dramatic 
results and will take the steam out of a congressional drive to 
limit steel imports, the administration's top trade official 
predicted Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said steel was a  
key discussion item when Clinton met Monday with Japanese Prime 
Minister Keizo Obuchi. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton repeated earlier warnings that if Japan's steel  
shipments, which surged over the past two years, do not return to 
levels in effect before 1997, the administration will pursue its 
own trade sanction cases against Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to jawboning Japan, the administration negotiated an  
agreement with Russia to restrict steel shipments voluntarily and 
is expediting a number of cases filed by the domestic industry that 
will impose high tariffs on steel determined to be sold in the 
United States at unfairly low prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think we have undertaken actions that have brought steel  
import volumes way down, back to pre-crisis levels in many 
instances,'' Barshefsky told the Society of American Business 
Writers and Editors. 
</P>
<P>
	Steel imports into the United States rose by 25 percent in  
March, but that increase followed four consecutive months of steep 
declines. Even with the March increase, steel imports remained 30 
percent below what they were in November. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, the House voted 289-141 for legislation that would  
impose global quotas on steel shipments into the United States. The 
proposal is pending in the Senate. The U.S. industry is lobbying 
for the passage of the measure to combat a flood of imports it 
blames for the loss of thousands of American jobs in the past year. 
</P>
<P>
	Barshefsky on Tuesday repeated the administration's view that  
the quota bill is clearly in violation of global trade rules 
administered by the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she would continue to urge a presidential veto on the  
grounds that the United States as the world's largest exporter ran 
a great risk of retaliation from other countries if it sought to 
erect protectionist barriers in violation of WTO rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there will be a quota bill ultimately presented  
to the president,'' Barshefsky told the business writers' group. 
``I think the president's program has been working.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But that assessment was disputed by Sen. Jay Rockefeller,  
D-W.Va., who said at a separate appearance Tuesday that he believed 
the Senate was ``very close to being able to do what the House 
did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rockefeller, a key supporter of restricting foreign steel, said  
he believed the Senate could vote in ``another week or so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other countries have become worried about growing protectionist  
pressure in Congress because of the soaring U.S. trade deficit. The 
deficit hit a record $169 billion last year and is headed higher in 
1999 as American manufacturers and farmers continue to suffer from 
a global financial crisis that has pushed one-third of the globe 
into recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Obuchi wrapped up his visit to Washington on Tuesday with  
meetings on Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., told reporters the  
discussions covered trade and other economic issues as well as 
Japan's support for U.S. efforts in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting with House members, Rep. Benjamin Gilman, chairman  
of the House International Relations Committee, gave Obuchi a 
report recommending that the United States, Japan and South Korea 
jointly establish an early warning system to guard against 
ballistic missile attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``All three nations face a common threat from North Korea, which  
has developed dangerous medium- and long-range missile systems 
despite international sanctions,'' Gilman said in a statement. 
``The time has come for us to coordinate the defense of all three 
countries against this threat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the Clinton-Obuchi summit meetings Monday, the two  
countries announced a package of agreements aimed at boosting sales 
prospects in Japan for American telecommunications, drug, financial 
service and energy companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But one of those agreements, which would boost cooperation on  
antitrust issues, was attacked at a Senate Judiciary Committee 
hearing Tuesday by senators who warned that Japan has not lived up 
to previous agreements. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although the Japanese say all the right things and sign all  
the right agreements, their keiretsu (linkage of businesses) of 
manufacturers and distributors has made it impossible for hard 
working companies to bring competitive products to Japan,'' said 
Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, said that as an alternative, the U.S.  
Justice Department should consider bringing enforcement cases 
against Japanese firms judged to be violating American antitrust 
laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
