<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Falling; Dow Down 110.25 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were tumbling lower in late afternoon, as  
a runup in interest rates prompted investors to reverse a buying 
spree on Monday that sent the Dow industrials above 11,000 for the 
first time. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 110.25, just more than 1 percent, at 10,904.44. That was still 
less than half of Monday's 225-point gain to 11,014.69. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were still catching their breath after the leap from  
10,000 past 11,000. Taking just 24 trading days, it represented the 
fastest rise ever between 1,000-point milestones. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is part of the two steps forward, one step back that the  
market has been engaged in lately,'' said Charles White, portfolio 
manager at Avatar Associates. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were lower after a mixed morning. The  
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was down 19.38 at 1,335.25, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was off 30.06 at 2,505.52. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Hogan, market analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. in Boston,  
agreed that today's losses were ``not a scary hit; I'll take that 
any day of the week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One reason was that, despite the drop in the Dow, advancing  
issues narrowly led decliners on the New York Stock Exchange, where 
volume came to 754.89 million shares, up from Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, blue-chip shares fell with bond prices, after two more  
reports today reinforcing a strong economic outlook. The 30-year 
Treasury bond was down sharply, pushing its yield up to 5.72 
percent from 5.65 percent late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board reported that a key gauge of future  
economic activity rose for the sixth straight month in March. The 
research group's index of leading economic indicators rose 0.1 
percent in March, in line with economists' predictions. 
</P>
<P>
	And in a confirmation that the housing market remains robust,  
the Commerce Department reported that completion of privately owned 
housing units rose 12.6 percent in March, the fasted pace since 
April 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Both figures fed fears that the Federal Reserve might be  
inclined to raise interest rates in a bid to cool the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Industrial shares were big losers among blue-chip Dow  
components. General Motors skidded 3 5/8 to 90 1/8. And financial stocks 
fell with bond prices. American Express was down 4 13/16 at 128 
9/16. 
</P>
<P>
	But Goldman Sachs shares soared to 72 1/4 in leading volume on the  
Big Board, after the investment firm sold 69 million shares at $53 
apiece in an initial public offering on Monday. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
