<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Griffey Gets Dad's Help With Swing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Ken Griffey Jr. knew his swing needed help and  
he knew exactly where to get it. 
</P>
<P>
	He went home and saw his dad.  
</P>
<P>
	Junior spent a half-hour of his day off at Cinergy Field on  
Tuesday, letting his father, Ken, toss him balls and give him 
advice. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knows my swing better than anybody,'' Junior said. ``I just  
wanted him to tell me what I was doing wrong. I've been fighting 
myself for the last two weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Junior has nine homers, 24 RBIs and a .287 average, but has  
struggled in his few opportunities against left-handed pitchers. 
He's only 5-for-28 (.179) with one homer against left-handers. 
</P>
<P>
	With Seattle off Tuesday before a two-game series in Cleveland,  
Junior had planned to get together with his family in his hometown 
before heading north. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey, a coach with the Reds, got a hint that it would be more  
than just a social visit when Junior called and asked about his 
plans -- other than seeing his two grandchildren, of course. 
</P>
<P>
	``His excuse was he's bringing the kids in,'' Griffey said,  
smiling. ``But I knew what it was when he wanted to come in early. 
I knew he probably wanted me to throw to him, to try to correct 
something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey got his son started on baseball at the age of 5 and  
often gets a call when Junior's swing is out of whack. He asked for 
his dad's help Tuesday because he's been slow getting the bat 
around against left-handers. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey, who throws left-handed, tossed him balls for about a  
half-hour in a batting cage under the stands before the Reds' game 
against Arizona. Griffey asked some questions and gave a few tips. 
</P>
<P>
	Mainly, they talked.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's not so much the swing, it's how he thinks,'' Griffey  
said. ``When I played, my thinking was how quick can I get out of 
it when I'm having problems at the plate so instead of going 
0-for-25, I may go 0-for-10 and then get a hit and start hitting 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds are off Thursday, so Griffey plans to join his son in  
Cleveland and throw him another round of batting practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey, 49, was part of the Big Red Machine that won  
consecutive World Series in 1975-76. He hit .296 during his major 
league career, which ended after he teamed up with his son in 
Seattle in 1990-91. They became the first father-son tandem to hit 
consecutive homers in a game on Sept. 14, 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	While his father was an All-Star outfielder for the Reds, Junior  
became a prep star in Cincinnati and was the Mariners' top draft 
pick. Junior kept in close touch with his family, and his father 
knew whenever his son was in a slump because the phone would ring. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been doing it ever since he's been in the game,'' Griffey  
said. ``We'll talk about something he's doing wrong and I'll kind 
of give him a question that he already knows the answer to. It's 
just a mental thing where it clicks and he says, ``Dad says this, 
so I'm doing this, so I'm OK.''' 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a dad first before anything,'' Junior said. ``If I'm  
swinging bad, he'll call me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
