<DOCNO> APW19990504.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 12:35:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smith-De Bruin Drug Ban Hearing Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- An international arbitration panel  
ended its appeal hearing Tuesday of a four-year drug ban imposed on 
triple Olympic gold medalist Michelle Smith-De Bruin, with a plea 
from her lawyer to overturn the punishment and award the swimmer 
damages. 
</P>
<P>
	``Her entire life has been turned upside down,'' said lawyer  
Peter Lennon. ``Before these charges she was an athlete held in 
high repute.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lennon renewed accusations that there were major flaws in the  
testing procedures which led to Smith-De Bruin being expelled from 
the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think she is entitled to the benefit of the doubt in this  
particular case,'' he told the three-man International Court of 
Arbitration for Sport, as his client listened nervously. 
</P>
<P>
	Tribunal chairman Yves Fortier refused to say when the verdict  
of the two-day hearing would be made public. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think in the fullness of time, the parties will be informed  
of our award. The ball is now in our court,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The swimming world governing body, FINA, imposed the ban last  
August after accusing Smith-De Bruin of tampering with an 
out-of-competition urine test taken at her Irish home, 
contaminating it with large amounts of alcohol. 
</P>
<P>
	The Irish swimmer denied the charge and appealed the ban which  
would disqualify her from the 2000 Olympics and 2001 World 
Championships and effectively end her career. 
</P>
<P>
	FINA lawyer Jean-Pierre Morand dismissed claims by Smith-de  
Bruin that someone else had manipulated the sample. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not a single element of concrete evidence,'' he said  
in his closing argument. He maintained that the culprit ``could 
only be the appellant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the evidence at Tuesday's hearing focused on whether it  
was possible to tamper with the urine sample container without 
leaving signs. 
</P>
<P>
	Monica Bonfanti, who works for the Lausanne Forensic Institute  
which conducted the tests, said her experiments to open three 
sample containers all left marks. But the proof wasn't conclusive, 
she told the court. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's possible there is another method which enables the  
canister to be opened without leaving a trace','' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, a test conducted in Britain showed it was  
possible to open and close containers used to transport urine 
samples without leaving any marks simply by immersing them in 
boiling water. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith had a mediocre record before capturing three gold medals  
and a bronze at the Atlanta Games, three years after Erik de Bruin 
became her coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Her marriage to de Bruin, the Dutch discus and shot put champion  
banned for four years after testing positive to excessive 
testosterone, stirred speculation that her rise had been aided by 
drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	But she said she had been tested more often than her rivals and  
each time the result was negative. 
</P>
<P>
	In his closing summary, Lennon said Smith-De Bruin had no need  
to take performance-enhancing drugs because at the time of the 
fateful test she was recovering from a road traffic injury. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the drug testers weren't qualified and the procedures  
were wrong. In addition to overturning the ban, FINA should pay 
court costs and award undisclosed damages, Lennon said. 
</P>
<P>
	``FINA has been looking to get Michelle de Bruin for a very  
considerable period of time,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
