<DOCNO> APW19990504.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Hamilton Seems Headed for NBA Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STORRS, Conn. (AP) -- All American guard Richard Hamilton  
apparently is leaving national champion Connecticut for the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton called a news conference for today and was expected to  
announce he is passing up his final year of eligibility and would 
make himself available for next month's draft. 
</P>
<P>
	UConn's other star guard, Khalid El-Amin, announced in April  
that he would return to Storrs for his junior season. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Tolokan, UConn's sports information director, would not  
confirm media reports that Hamilton was leaving. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-6 swingman was the heart of the Huskies' championship  
season. He averaged 19.7 points a game and become the 
second-highest scorer in school history with 2,036 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton was an All-American and co-Player of the Year in the  
Big East Conference, joining Patrick Ewing and Chris Mullin as the 
only two-time winners of that award. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton flirted with the idea of turning pro before his junior  
season, but was lured back to campus by the prospect of making a 
run at the national title. 
</P>
<P>
	The Huskies upset Duke 77-74 to win their first national  
championship in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
