<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Caldera Answers Microsoft Motions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Caldera Inc., a small Utah company suing  
Microsoft for alleged antitrust violations, says the software 
giant's internal documents show it used misleading statements to 
discourage customers from buying Caldera's product. 
</P>
<P>
	In filings with U.S. District Court here on Monday, Caldera said  
the documents demonstrate that Microsoft used misleading product 
announcements, known in the industry as ``vaporware,'' to dampen 
sales and reduce interest in DR-DOS. 
</P>
<P>
	DR-DOS is a program that enables computers to perform basic  
functions, and Caldera contends Microsoft deliberately destroyed 
public demand for the program. One of Caldera's expert witnesses 
has calculated the company's damages at $1.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's filings were in response to Microsoft's request in  
January for the judge to make a summary judgment to throw out nine 
separate issues in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Court Judge Dee Benson has scheduled five hearings  
on the motions starting May 25. The case began nearly three years 
ago and is scheduled for a jury trial in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldera, which is based in Orem, Utah, also claims Microsoft  
used misleading statements about DR-DOS to create fear, uncertainty 
and doubt; used licensing terms to block out DR-DOS; intentionally 
created incompatibilities and the perception of incompatibilities 
to hurt DR-DOS in the marketplace, and ``black listed'' Novell, 
which previously owned DR-DOS, from access to a Windows test to 
hinder compatibility. 
</P>
<P>
	It also claims that Windows 95 is just MS-DOS and Windows  
packaged together to eliminate the possibility of the customer 
buying a competing DOS to run the new Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft claims that internal memos show DR-DOS's developers  
knew they had a flawed product and poor technical support for 
frustrated consumers. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
