<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Auto Sales Rise in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Consumers can't seem to get enough new cars and  
trucks, pushing the auto industry's sales boom into its second 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the major automakers that reported April sales results  
Monday, total sales were up 7.5 percent. Ford Motor Co., 
DaimlerChrysler AG and Japan's three biggest automakers each 
reported gains over the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Monthly year-to-year sales comparisons have been up through the  
past 13 months except in July and August, when total sales were 
artificially depressed as two strikes against General Motors Corp. 
restricted its supply. 
</P>
<P>
	GM remained the only major automaker to report its sales today.  
Analysts expected it to report flat to slightly lower sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``Barring any surprises from GM ... it looks like another  
gangbuster month,'' said analyst David Healy of Burnham Securities 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The reasons for April's improvement were familiar: a robust  
economy and consumers confident enough about the future to take on 
the increased debt of a new car or truck. 
</P>
<P>
	``The economy has the legs of a marathon runner,'' said Yale  
Gieszl, a vice president of Toyota Motor Sales USA Inc. ``Consumers 
look at interest rates, inflation, Wall Street and the job market 
and have every reason to be confident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said its April sales were up 7 percent last month, compared  
with April 1998. Sales of light trucks set an April record -- the 
company's 12th straight monthly record for pickups, vans, minivans 
and sport utility vehicles combined. Car sales were up 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures do not include Ford's Volvo AB or Jaguar Cars units,  
each of which reported its U.S. sales rose 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said demand is so strong that it is again increasing its  
second-quarter production schedule, this time by 20,000 additional 
vehicles. With last month's 30,000 increase, Ford now plans to 
build just over 1.26 million cars and trucks during the April-June 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a somewhat unusual month at DaimlerChrysler's Chrysler  
unit, in that its biggest improvement came in car sales. Total 
sales improved 2 percent; cars were up 6 percent while truck sales 
were flat. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chrysler unit sells more than twice as many light trucks as  
cars. But its minivan sales fell 19 percent just as the spring 
buying season was heating up, and pickup sales were flat. Healy 
said April's minivan performance was the ``hangover'' of 
incentive-driven sales in March that depleted inventories. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamie Jameson, vice president of sales and marketing, said truck  
sales also suffered from a tough comparison to April 1998 when 
sales were boosted by a coupon war launched by GM. 
</P>
<P>
	The German-American automaker posted an 18 percent gain in sales  
of highly profitable SUVs. In fact, SUV sales at the former 
Chrysler Corp. have set monthly records in 17 of the last 18 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota Motor Corp. posted its best April ever in the United  
States, with sales up nearly 10 percent. Its 7 percent rise in car 
sales was led once again by the Camry, the nation's bestseller, 
with sales up 21 percent for its best April ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest Japanese automaker also was boosted by a 13.5  
percent rise in truck sales: the hot-selling Lexus RX300 SUV was up 
78 percent, while; the Sienna minivan had its best month ever with 
a 25 percent increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda Motor Co. also benefited from improved truck sales, up 53  
percent. Overall sales improved 4 percent, dragged down by a 3 
percent decline in car sales. Honda's new Odyssey minivan posted a 
211 percent gain, while sales of the CR-V compact SUV improved 41 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of Honda's top-seller, the Accord sedan, were flat while  
sales of the Civic subcompact were off 7 percent. But buyers 
flocked to the Acura TL luxury sedan, whose sales nearly doubled. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan Motor Co. had its biggest improvement in months: total  
sales were up 21 percent, led by a 26 percent gain in trucks. Its 
redesigned Quest minivan, for example, nearly doubled sales over 
April 1998. Car sales were up nearly 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Volkswagen AG said it has its best April in the United States in  
19 years, with sales up 29.5 percent on the strength of a new 
product lineup. Its redesigned Jetta sedan led the sales drive, 
with its best single month since the original version was 
introduced in 1980. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
