<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belle Says It'll Take a Team To Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Don't blame Albert Belle for the Baltimore  
Orioles' woes. 
</P>
<P>
	His bat may not be living up to the $65 million contract he  
signed in the offseason, but it's early. And he's only one guy. 
</P>
<P>
	``One guy is not able to turn an organization around. It takes  
all 25 players, the coaching staff, the management and the 
organization,'' said Belle, who is hitting .253. ``You can't just 
depend on one guy to do it. That's what I learned from '97. ... 
</P>
<P>
	``In that situation, I tried to do it all myself,'' he said.  
``It's just not going to work that way. ... April wasn't very good 
for a lot of us here. We've kind of dug ourselves a hole, and now 
we're trying to get out of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belle still isn't talking to Baltimore reporters because they  
wrote about a clubhouse temper tantrum in spring training. He spoke 
with the Chicago Sun-Times and the Chicago Tribune before 
Baltimore's first series with the Chicago White Sox, his old team. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle's contract with the White Sox allowed him to ask for a  
raise or become a free agent if his average salary didn't remain 
among the top three in baseball. When the White Sox refused to give 
him a raise, Belle signed with the Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	But unlike when he left Cleveland in 1996, there's no animosity  
toward his former team. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're entirely different situations,'' Belle said. ``I left  
Cleveland on bad terms, real bad. A lot of things happened and a 
lot of things were said that told me I could never go back. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was different with the White Sox. When you only draw 1.3  
million fans and finish below .500, you know things have to change. 
That's just business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Belle would like to see his old team win the AL  
Central. Of course, that's partly because it would mean Cleveland 
wouldn't win it. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle's biggest concern right now, however, is his own team.  
With the highest payroll in baseball ($84 million), the Orioles had 
high expectations at the beginning of the season. Instead, their 
7-17 record through Monday was the worst in the AL. They're already 
nine games behind New York in the AL East and have won just once on 
the road. 
</P>
<P>
	And Belle isn't doing much to help. Traditionally a slow  
starter, he was in an 8-for-46 slump through Monday with five 
homers. He's batting .200 with runners in scoring position. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Belle usually heats up late -- he hit .387 with 31  
homers in the second half last year -- it might not be in time for 
the Orioles. Owner Peter Angelos is not likely to put up with the 
losing for long, and manager Ray Miller is already on shaky ground. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ray's OK,'' Belle said. ``He's under tremendous pressure to  
win, especially with the high payroll, but we should be all right 
once we get over injuries and start to play like a team. There are 
a lot of new players here, like myself, but we're mostly veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, we played a lot of Eastern Division teams  
first. It's the toughest division, but I think we can catch up to 
them.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
