<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Questions To Ask About Mutual Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Some time when you want to challenge friends or  
a financial adviser to see how savvy they are about mutual-fund 
investing, try asking them these three simple questions: 
</P>
<P>
	Which types of long-term funds, investing in stocks or bonds or  
both, work best in ordinary taxable accounts? Which are better in 
tax-deferred retirement accounts? And why? 
</P>
<P>
	If the person you are questioning is truly knowledgeable, don't  
expect a fast, facile reply. These are very tough questions to 
answer correctly -- much tougher than anybody who follows the 
standard rules of thumb may realize. 
</P>
<P>
	``When planning for retirement, investors often face the dilemma  
of deciding which funds to hold in their taxable and tax-deferred 
accounts,'' notes Samuel Beardsley, a tax specialist at the fund 
management firm of T. Rowe Price Associates in Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	``The conventional wisdom of putting stock funds in taxable  
accounts and bond funds in tax-deferred accounts may not be the 
best strategy for all investors,'' Beardsley says in a report just 
published at Price's site on the World Wide Web 
(www.troweprice.com). 
</P>
<P>
	The whole issue matters because the two basic types of  
investment accounts operate under entirely different tax systems. 
As Beardsley observes, ``Making the best choice can significantly 
affect long-term returns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a standard taxable account, distributions based on dividends  
and interest, and short-term capital gains on investments held a 
year or less, are taxed by Uncle Sam at ordinary income rates which 
range as high as 39.6 percent, depending on your total income. But 
long-term capital gains, including the gains distributions many 
funds make each year, have a top rate of 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, investors in tax-deferred plans such as individual  
retirement accounts and employer-sponsored 401(k) plans pay no tax 
until they take money from the account, when all withdrawals are 
taxed as ordinary income. 
</P>
<P>
	Since a greater percentage of the return from bond funds than  
from stock funds typically comes from dividends, it is often 
suggested that bond funds make more sense in tax-deferred accounts, 
and stock funds in taxable accounts. That is what Beardsley calls 
``the conventional method.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``However,'' Beardsley says, ``in many cases, the taxes paid on  
the average stock fund's annual distributions exceed the taxes paid 
on the bond fund's distributions ... . Basically, because the stock 
fund earns so much more each year, and because that excess 
compounds, its tax bite is greater than the bond fund's and it pays 
to shelter the stock fund from tax.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Be advised, that general principle may not hold in every case.  
For instance, if we're talking about an index fund that makes few 
capital gains distributions, you are likely to be better off using 
the conventional method. 
</P>
<P>
	In many instances, the way things work out will depend on  
variables that can't be known in advance -- including the returns 
that will be earned over any future period by stock and bond funds. 
``Tax rates could change,'' Beardsley says. ``Another consideration 
is state taxes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the length of time you hold your investments can make a  
big difference. This is something you can plan for, although future 
events may cause you to change those plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid all this uncertainty, Beardsley offers a series of  
guidelines, summarized here only in part because of space 
constraints: 
</P>
<P>
	1. If you switch in and out of stock fund investments  
frequently, use the unconventional method. 
</P>
<P>
	2. If your stock fund is an index fund, use the conventional  
method. 
</P>
<P>
	3. If the tax-deferred account is a Roth IRA, use the  
unconventional method. 
</P>
<P>
	4. If you will liquidate your tax-deferred account in less than  
15 years, use the conventional method. 
</P>
<P>
	In practice, many individual fund investors don't bother with  
calculations like this. There are just too many unknowns involved. 
Besides, they may be dealing with limited choices anyway in a 
401(k) or similar retirement account. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it's worth noting that a haphazard selection system may  
hurt the returns you realize over the years, by some amount that 
may never get measured. 
</P>
<P>
	 *End adv for use anytime    	



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
