<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Factory Owner's Assets Unfrozen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Faced with a lawsuit, the Clinton  
administration is unfreezing the assets of Saudi businessman Saleh 
Idris even though it still believes he may be involved in 
international terrorism, the Justice and Treasury departments say. 
</P>
<P>
	The government agreed to release more than $24 million in Bank  
of America deposits on Monday, the day it was scheduled to answer a 
civil suit Idris filed Feb. 26 over the U.S. bombing of a 
pharmaceutical plant he owned in Khartoum, Sudan. The suit claimed 
the government was blocking his use of the money even though it had 
no evidence the factory was producing chemical weapons agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen cruise missiles struck the El Shifa plant in Khartoum  
on Aug. 20, 1998. It was one of several properties destroyed after 
bombings earlier that month at U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania 
killed a total of 301 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department officials said the government lifted the  
freeze after deciding it was unwise to reveal the sources of their 
evidence during a trial in open court. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made a judgment that we had concerns regarding Mr. Idris  
based on sensitive information, but we're not prepared to 
compromise those sources for the sake of this case,'' said an 
administration official who spoke on condition of not being 
identified by name. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have concerns about Mr. Idris and his business dealings,''  
the senior official said. ``There are things that Mr. Idris has 
associated himself with that I think that every American would find 
reprehensible. ... And we will continue to monitor his network for 
any potential threat to U.S. interests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of Idris' attorneys said he believed the government backed  
down because it had no evidence the plant was involved in chemical 
weapons production. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fortunately, we live in a country where we have a system of  
justice that requires that people produce evidence when someone is 
accused of being a terrorist,'' attorney George Salem said. 
</P>
<P>
	Salem also said that studies, including examinations of the soil  
at the plant, performed by independent consultants at Idris' 
request found no trace of substances used in chemical weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Salem said Idris planned to drop the suit -- as well as another  
one filed against the Bank of America -- with the full and 
unconditional release of his bank accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of the bombing, U.S. officials said the  
pharmaceutical plant was a cover for chemical weapons production. 
They also said it had links to suspected terrorist mastermind Osama 
bin Laden, who allegedly bankrolled the bombings of the American 
embassies. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly afterward, the Sudanese government called the bombing a  
blunder and insisted the facility produced medicines and other 
goods needed by the country's citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
