<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2:15 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Storms Deadliest in 15 Years  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The pack of tornadoes that tore through the  
Midwest left at least 45 people dead, making them the deadliest 
storms in nearly 15 years. The death toll is the highest for a 
weather-related disaster since 1985, when storms killed 90 people 
in Ohio, Pennsylvania and Ontario. And Oklahoma authorities say the 
death toll is expected to rise because destruction is just ``so 
massive.'' The National Weather Service says the biggest twister 
formed about 45 miles southwest of Oklahoma City. Entire 
neighborhoods were wiped out, officials said. Mobile homes were 
tossed around like tin cans. President Clinton has declared 11 
counties in Oklahoma disaster areas, a move that will provide 
federal funding. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Claims Heavy Hits in Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO claimed today its most  
successful round of attacks yet against Serb forces and shot down a 
Yugoslav plane in the first air-to-air battle since early in the 
six-week-old campaign. An alliance jet downed a Yugoslav MiG-29 
fighter jet in a dogfight over Serbia. The Serbs have avoided air 
confrontations since early in the conflict, which began March 24. 
British defense officials said more than 50 targets were struck 
over the previous 24 hours in relentless attacks focusing on 
Yugoslav forces in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovars Tell of Serb Attacks  
</P>
<P>
	MORINI, Albania (AP) -- Refugees streamed into Albania today with  
fresh reports of Serb forces using extortion and murder to push 
ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. More than 2,000 refugees had crossed 
the border by midafternoon, many repeating similar stories of 
forces demanding money from ethnic Albanian refugees, and gunning 
down those who didn't comply. Officials say more than 250,000 
refugees have headed south from Kukes, but more than 100,000 remain 
in the Kukes area and do not want to leave. 

</P>
<P>
	NRA Re-Elects Charlton Heston  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Actor Charlton Heston, who blamed the Colorado  
school shooting partially on the government's failure to enforce 
gun laws, has been re-elected to another term as president of the 
National Rifle Association. Demonstrators gathered to protest the 
NRA's meeting so soon after the massacre at Columbine High, where 
two teen-aged gunmen killed 12 classmates and a teacher. ``The 
problem is not the availability of arms,'' Heston said shortly 
after the shootings, ``but the government's poor record in 
prosecuting both juveniles and adults for gun violations.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Wrestling Fragrance in the Works  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- If you've always wanted to smell like a wrestler,  
now you can, thanks to Perfumania and World Championship Wrestling, 
which said yesterday they would join forces to manufacture a new, 
upscale line of fragrances. The aromas are described as fresh and 
spicy. The fragrances should be available for sale via Perfumania's 
Internet store in November, and in Perfumania's 288 stores 
nationwide. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 87  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 87.63 to 10,927.06. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,496-1,407. The Nasdaq was down 10.56 to 
2,525.02. 

</P>
<P>
	Cuban Misses Flight Home  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- At least one Cuban missed the flight that  
returned baseball players home to Havana after their victory over 
the Baltimore Orioles, a law enforcement source said. The source 
indicated someone was seeking asylum but police said some 
delegation members overslept. More than 300 Cubans were part of the 
delegation that attended Monday night's game, which the Cubans won 
12-6. Besides players, the delegation included journalists, retired 
baseball players, ordinary citizens, members of youth groups and 
outstanding students. The Immigration and Naturalization Service 
would not comment on possible defections. 

</P>
<P>
	Hamilton Reportedly Heading to NBA  
</P>
<P>
	STORRS, Conn. (AP) -- All-America forward Richard Hamilton, who  
led Connecticut to its first national championship in March, 
reportedly will enter the NBA draft. ESPN says Hamilton will make 
the announcement at a news conference at 3 p.m. EDT today. The 
6-foot-6 guard-forward averaged 19.7 points a game. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
