<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Meeting Fails To Appoint Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The World Trade Organization broke off attempts  
Tuesday to find a new director-general after virtually ruling out 
Thailand's candidate and failing to agree on his New Zealand rival. 
</P>
<P>
	A meeting of the 134-nation WTO General Council adjourned after  
its chairman, Ali Mchumo, was unable to rally Asian and developing 
countries around former New Zealand Premier Mike Moore, the 
American and European choice. 
</P>
<P>
	The deadlock increased the likelihood that a third candidate may  
need to be found. 
</P>
<P>
	It also raised the prospect of a lengthy leadership vacuum which  
may damage efforts to mediate high-profile trade disputes and 
prepare for a November summit in Seattle to lower barriers to 
exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy's Renato Ruggiero officially left Friday after four years  
in the post, but stayed at work until Tuesday afternoon. In a final 
statement, he expressed disappointment that no successor had been 
found. 
</P>
<P>
	Mchumo, a Tanzanian diplomat told the council that there was no  
prospect of consensus to appoint Supachai Panitchpakdi, the Thai 
deputy prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	In a poll last week, 62 countries supported Moore, a former  
trade unionist who was prime minister briefly in 1990. Supachai, 
the front-runner for months and the perceived developing country 
candidate, was backed by 59 nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may be the case that Dr. Supachai and his supporters may  
still believe he is a candidate,'' Mchumo said. ``But in terms of 
the rules of this process he is no longer a candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Asian nations stood by their choice.  
</P>
<P>
	``Any attempt to impose a decision on the WTO membership could  
divide us and as a consequence gravely impair ... the entire 
organization,'' said a statement by Malaysia on behalf of the ASEAN 
group of countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ask for reflection and responsibility by all as the means  
to restore unity,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and its allies in Latin America and parts of  
Europe insist that the title of director-general now belongs to 
Moore. 
</P>
<P>
	``It takes a while to form a consensus,'' U.S. delegate Rita  
Hayes said. 
</P>
<P>
	The organization has named David Hartridge, head of its services  
division, as acting director, but only to handle routine matters. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartridge lacks the international clout needed at a time when  
free trade ideals are under pressure from the global economic 
upheavals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
