<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Company Conference Calls Go Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Investor conference calls, once reserved for  
financial analysts and investment bankers, are moving to the 
Internet, where they'll be available to online investors. 
</P>
<P>
	A pair of technology companies will carry the conference calls  
of publicly traded companies live and offer the ability to send 
questions by e-mail during the call. 
</P>
<P>
	CCBN.com, a Boston-based provider of investor relations Web site  
services, and INTERVU Inc., a San Diego-based company that delivers 
audio and video over the Internet, today established an alliance 
that will put the calls online. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, INTERVU's streaming media services will be  
used in CCBN.com's WebCast service, the companies said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	CCBN.com's WebCast will also provide clients with the ability to  
post a Microsoft PowerPoint presentation for review during the 
call. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips Petroleum Co. used WebCast to broadcast its quarterly  
conference call on April 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Edd Grigsby, vice president of Investor and Public Relations at  
Phillips Petroleum, said Internet carriage helps ``level the 
playing field'' for individual and institutional investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Conference calls have been used as a tool for public companies  
to deliver comprehensive insight and timely information to 
analysts, investment bankers and major institutional investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Securities and Exchange Commission, however, has continued  
to scrutinize conference calls as a potential area for selective 
disclosure by public companies. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
