<HEADLINE> Dollar, Gold Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar gained against the Japanese yen but was  
lower against other major currencies in European trading today. 
Gold fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose to 121.02 Japanese yen from 119.89 yen late  
Monday, but was lower against the British pound and the euro, the 
currency of 11 European nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6162, up from $1.6106, while  
the euro rose to $1.0585 from $1.0569 late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Monday included 1.5201  
Swiss francs, down from 1.5236, and 1.4500 Canadian dollars, down 
from 1.4565. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York at midday, the dollar was worth 120.92 yen, 1.5148  
Swiss francs and 1.4528 Canadian dollars. The British pound was 
worth $1.6253 and the euro was worth $1.0607. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth: 1.8477 German marks, down from 1.8505; 
6.1970 French francs, down from 6.2064; and 1,829.26 Italian lire, 
down from 1,832.03. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold traded in Zurich at a bid price of $284.95 per troy ounce  
late Tuesday, down from $286.05 late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $284.85, down from 286.50 on Friday.  
Currency and metal markets in London were closed for a holiday on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell 75 cents in Hong Kong to $285.70.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.31 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$5.34 on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
