<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 05:05:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MediaOne Calls Off Comcast Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T. Microsoft. America Online. And now  
apparently MCI WorldCom. 
</P>
<P>
	All have been linked to the bidding war for MediaOne Group Inc.  
in what is shaping to be the highest-profile battle on Wall Street 
since the fight for control of RJR Nabisco and could lead to a 
showdown between two of the nation's top telecommunications 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The war started when AT&AMP;T Corp. issued a surprise bid for  
MediaOne on April 22, ultimately derailing Comcast Inc.'s $48 
billion agreement to acquire the fourth-largest U.S. cable company. 
MediaOne said Monday it was choosing AT&AMP;T's cash and stock deal, 
now worth nearly $56 billion, but also said Comcast had until 
Thursday to make another offer. 
</P>
<P>
	That sent Comcast, the nation's No. 3 cable company, scrambling  
to find help. Enter Microsoft Corp. and America Online Inc., who 
both signed confidentiality agreements to examine MediaOne's secret 
internal financial data last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Numerous sources reported Monday that America Online had bowed  
out of the bidding war, though AOL declined to comment. Microsoft, 
meanwhile, hasn't said anything publicly about its intentions, and 
Comcast also refused to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a new suitor has reportedly jumped into the game. The  
New York Times reported today that MCI WorldCom Inc. is seriously 
considering jumping into the fray to aid Comcast. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom was talking to MediaOne Monday night about signing  
the same kind of agreement to examine the cable company's, the 
Times said, citing executives close to the negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	If MCI WorldCom does join the bidding war, America Online may be  
interested in being a third-party partner to the bid, the 
executives said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for both MCI WorldCom and MediaOne declined comment  
Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite fears that AT&AMP;T will dominate the potential online and  
telephone riches to be mined from cable TV wires, analysts have not 
been optimistic that a competing offer would emerge. For one thing, 
Microsoft and AOL simply may not want to become cable companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think (Comcast's) partners want to be as deeply into  
cable as some people are assuming they do,'' said Tom Vanderslice, 
managing director for media corporate finance at CIBC Oppenheimer. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, however, has already committed itself to the cable  
business though its purchase of Tele-Communications Inc., the 
nation's second biggest system, and an alliance with Time Warner, 
the biggest. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft and AOL don't have the same incentive. If the goal of  
buying MediaOne is to use cable TV wires for high-speed Internet 
access and phone calls, what good does it do to own the nation's 
fourth largest cable company if it means alienating AT&AMP;T, which 
already has access to the two biggest? 
</P>
<P>
	``AT&AMP;T needs MediaOne more than Comcast does and more than  
Microsoft does,'' Thomas Eagan, a cable industry analyst for 
PaineWebber Group. 
</P>
<P>
	If AT&AMP;T wins, the No. 1 long-distance company will also be the  
No. 1 cable company, having access to 60 percent of the U.S. homes 
wired for cable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
