<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Arrested In Colo. Shooting Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- A 22-year-old man who has admitted  
selling a semiautomatic handgun to the two Columbine student gunmen 
had gone shooting in the woods with the two before the school 
massacre, his attorney said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Manes, a computer programmer, fired weapons with Eric  
Harris and Dylan Klebold three times within the month prior to the 
rampage that left 15 dead, said attorney Robert Ransome. 
</P>
<P>
	The semiautomatic TEC DC-9 was one of four guns used by Harris,  
18, and Klebold, 17, in the April 20 attack. Twelve students and a 
teacher were killed and 23 others were wounded before the attackers 
committed suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Manes thought he was just spending time with fellows who just  
enjoyed shooting, and ``did not know this was going to happen,'' 
Ransome said. ``Mark's family is extremely devastated about what 
happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police have said they do not know if Manes was aware of what the  
gun would be used for. 
</P>
<P>
	Manes was arrested Monday on suspicion of providing a handgun to  
a minor. The charge carries a maximum six years in prison. Ransome 
said his client was talking to prosecutors and hoped to avoid a 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Ransome said his client bought the pistol at a gun show last  
fall. He later met Harris and Klebold through a mutual 
acquaintance. 
</P>
<P>
	``A third party knew Mark had this certain weapon and also knew  
Eric and Dylan were looking for weapons. He put them together,'' 
the attorney said. ``Mark was not friends with Eric and Dylan. He 
did not hang out with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He would not give specifics on where they went out shooting,  
whether Manes sold ammunition to the pair, the sale price of the 
gun, what his client may have known about the law involving sales 
to minor, or who else might have been involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, detectives kept up their search for those who may  
have known what the pair had planned for Columbine High. 
</P>
<P>
	Manes' arrest came as Columbine's 1,900-plus students made an  
eager but uneasy return to class Monday at nearby Chatfield High 
School. Chatfield students had class in the morning, Columbine 
students in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every loud noise, you freak out,'' said Samantha Roman, a  
16-year-old Columbine sophomore. ``But it makes us feel more secure 
once you see all the police and stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Administrators asked friends of Harris and Klebold not to attend  
Chatfield, opting instead to have them home-schooled for the rest 
of the year. The parents agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	Manes, a Littleton resident who once attended Columbine, was  
released from jail after posting bond. 
</P>
<P>
	Manes, who is scheduled to make his first court appearance next  
Monday, was the first person since the shootings to be arrested on 
charges of helping Harris and Klebold arm themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities have said that Robyn Anderson, Klebold's 18-year-old  
girlfriend, purchased the other three weapons used -- two rifles and 
a shotgun -- and has been interviewed as a witness. Under Colorado 
law, an 18-year-old without a felony record can furnish minors with 
rifles and shotguns. 
</P>
<P>
	Police are still trying to find others who may have known the  
killers' plans, though detectives appeared to all but rule out a 
third gunmen inside the school during the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've always, from day one, had a feeling that there had to  
be some people who had some knowledge or helped them plan or build 
some of these bombs,'' Jefferson County sheriff's spokesman Steve 
Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	But, ``our people are definitely leaning toward the good  
possibility that Harris and Klebold were the only people in the 
school that day,'' Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said an employee at the pizza parlor where Harris  
and Klebold worked put the two teen-agers in touch with Manes and 
the TEC DC-9 pistol. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Monday, the coroner's office said Harris had the  
anti-depressant Luvox in his system at the time of the attack. 
Before the attack, the Marine Corps rejected Harris' application 
for enlistment after learning he used the drug. Luvox is commonly 
used to treat obsessive-compulsive disorder and is also used to 
treat depression. 
</P>
</TEXT>
