<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson &AMP; Johnson Wants Centocor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Johnson &AMP; Johnson is in talks to buy  
Centocor Inc. for more than $3 billion in stock in a deal that 
would give J&AMP;J access to a new, hot-selling heart drug, according 
to people familiar with the discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	While the negotiations are in an early stage and could still  
fall apart, J&AMP;J and Centocor could reach an agreement within a 
week, said one of the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
Both companies declined to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Centocor makes ReoPro, a popular drug used to prevent blood  
clotting that had sales of $365 million last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say that Johnson &AMP; Johnson may want to acquire the drug  
maker to help revive weakening sales of its cardiovascular stents, 
the tiny devices that hold arteries open. In addition to drugs, 
Johnson &AMP; Johnson also makes many consumer products such as 
Band-Aids, Tylenol and baby shampoo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Johnson &AMP; Johnson could bundle their stents with ReoPro for  
the cardiovascular community and differentiate their product line 
up,'' said Ann Pluemer Barber, an analyst at Credit Suisse First 
Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal would be the latest big consolidation in an industry  
driven by the quest for new products. In January, Warner-Lambert 
Co. announced a $2.1 billion acquisition of Agouron 
Pharmaceuticals, which makes the AIDS drug Viracept. 
</P>
<P>
	``Big drug companies need more products in their pipelines to  
drive growth,'' Barber said. ``If you get a couple new products out 
you can really drive profitability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Centocor's stock, which has been climbing on takeover rumors,  
rose another $2.25 or 4.8 percent to $49.12 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock 
Market Tuesday, giving the Malvern, Pa. company a market value of 
$3.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	J&AMP;J's stock fell $2.75 to $95 on the New York Stock Exchange.  
Investors may be worried about the dilution to J&AMP;J's earnings if it 
issues stock to pay for Centocor. They also may be concerned that 
Centocor's agreement with Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. to co-market ReoPro makes 
Centocor a less attractive target. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, J&AMP;J could do a lot to help expand Centocor's  
business. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you look at the financial and organizational resources  
Johnson &AMP; Johnson can bring to bear on the ongoing development of 
Centocor, it would be an exciting opportunity,'' said Richard 
Stover, an analyst with Arnold &AMP; S. Bleichroeder. 
</P>
<P>
	J&AMP;J's marketing muscle could also boost sales of Centocor's drug  
Remicade, which treats Crohn's disease, which is currently under 
governmental review for treating rheumatoid arthritis. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
