<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Auto Insurance Rates Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Auto insurance rates fell 2.8 percent last year  
nationwide -- the first decline in 25 years -- and could fall further 
this year, an industry group said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Insurance Information Institute said the drop reflected  
greater competition among insurers, more skilled drivers on the 
road, safer vehicles and less tolerance for drunken drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based institute said it expected an additional drop  
of about 4.5 percent this year, adding that ``motorists with good 
driving records may see even bigger savings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the decline in rates, auto insurance spending rose  
slightly in 1998, the institute said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert P. Hartwig, chief economist of the New York-based  
institute, said the average amount spent on auto insurance 
increased 0.5 percent last year largely because of record new car 
sales, which drove up the price of vehicles being insured. 
</P>
<P>
	``New cars are more expensive than old ones, and so is the  
insurance,'' he said. Hartwig added that a larger proportion of new 
vehicles being sold are expensive sports utility vehicles and 
trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, he predicts expenditures to fall by about 1 percent  
because ``the rate decline should be larger (this year) than in 
1998, and new car prices are falling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The institute predicted consumers would spend, on average, about  
$702 in auto insurance this year, down from $709 in 1998. The 
average expenditure was $706 in 1997, it said. It based its 
averages on figures from the National Association of Insurance 
Commissioners and the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartwig noted that the last time insurance rates declined was in  
1973, when the economy was in recession. To see a decline now, amid 
economic growth, indicates ``that the insurance industry is among 
those that are almost deflationary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said that about half of the 2.8 percent drop in rates this  
year was attributable to increased competition in the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
