<HEADLINE> Arkansas Boat Accident Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- The driver of a Lake Hamilton tour boat  
that went to the bottom in seconds, killing 13 people, said the 
vessel's pump failed to kick in when water poured through the hull, 
a federal investigator said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The pump has become a focus of the investigation as a Navy  
salvage crew began preparations to raise the amphibious craft from 
the lake bed where it settled Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	In talking with investigators on Sunday, the day after the  
accident, driver Elizabeth Helmbrecht said she did not hear the 
main pump activate, National Transportation Safety Board spokesman 
John A. Hammerschmidt said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she did not hear the larger pump begin pumping the water,  
then she had no real warning'' that the amphibious craft was taking 
on water, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hammerschmidt said Helmbrecht may not have heard the pump.  
Ms. Helmbrecht told investigators she scuttled a trip several days 
before the fatal outing when she heard the bilge pump turn on. 
</P>
<P>
	The pump is supposed to turn on if water about four inches deep  
reaches the center of the hull, Hammerschmidt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hammerschmidt said it was not immediately clear whether  
mechanics had worked on the pump when it was taken in for repairs 
prior to the sinking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
