<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Khmer Rouge Torturer Disappears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAMLOT, Cambodia (AP) -- Until the past few days, the family of  
Kaing Khek Iev had no idea he was a notorious torturer in the Khmer 
Rouge during the late 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time they'd digested the news, he had disappeared.  
</P>
<P>
	Kaing Khek Iev -- known as Duch in the Tuol Sleng prison he once  
commanded -- seemed Tuesday to have slipped back into the shadows 
that shielded him for 20 years until news reports recently exposed 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Duch, 56, told his sister, Hong Kim Hong, on Saturday that he  
planned to travel to nearby Battambang. She said Tuesday she hadn't 
seen him since, although the 45-mile trip normally wouldn't take 
more than a day or two. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm worried because my brother hasn't come home,'' said Hong  
Kim Hong, 41, in the one-room shack they share near Samlot, a 
former stronghold of the now-defunct Khmer Rouge guerrillas. 
</P>
<P>
	Brother and sister were separated during the Khmer Rouge regime  
and were not reunited until 1988. Hong Kim Hong learned of the part 
her brother played in the nightmarish revolution only when 
reporters seeking him started showing up recently. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was always kind to his family,'' Hong Kim Hong said. ``He  
always warned them to do what their leaders told them to do, to 
never contradict their superiors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That advice wouldn't have gone far in Tuol Sleng, the former  
high school the Khmer Rouge turned into a brutal interrogation 
center after seizing power in 1975. Even when a prisoner 
``confessed'' -- to being a traitor or a spy, for example -- Duch 
would accuse them of holding back and would order more torture by 
electricity, water and beatings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hong Kong-based Far Eastern Economic Review published an  
interview last week in which Duch admitted he signed the orders for 
the torture of at least 14,000 men, women and children at Tuol 
Sleng. 
</P>
<P>
	They were later taken to killing fields on the outskirts of  
Phnom Penh and executed. Only seven inmates survived. 
</P>
<P>
	The Khmer Rouge were toppled in 1979 by a Vietnamese invasion,  
after an estimated 1.7 million Cambodians -- of a population of 7.9 
million -- had died from executions, overwork and disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Duch told the Review he had converted to Christianity in recent  
years and made a living working for foreign aid agencies that 
didn't know his identity. 
</P>
<P>
	Duch also said he would be prepared to testify against his  
former leaders, most of whom live freely under controversial deals 
granted by the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Human rights groups and genocide researchers have expressed  
concerns for Duch's safety. They fear he may be killed to keep him 
from implicating the Khmer Rouge leadership in mass murder, which 
would pressure the government to rescind the de facto amnesties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
