<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ariz. Eateries Pay $2M in INS Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix owners and managers of a chain of  
Mexican restaurants agreed to a fine of nearly $2 million for 
hiring illegal immigrants, a federal official says. 
</P>
<P>
	Hank Woodrum, an assistant director of the U.S. Immigration and  
Naturalization Service, said the Filiberto's chain accepted the 
settlement on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodrum said it was ``the biggest fine for a work site  
enforcement case in U.S. history'' and that it involved the largest 
number of illegal hirings. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, nearly 200 illegal immigrants were arrested when INS  
raided 15 Filiberto's restaurants. The award-winning cafes are 
franchised by brothers Filiberto, Aurelio, Francisco and Reynaldo 
Tenorio-Quintero, all of Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	All four pleaded guilty to one count of conspiracy to hire  
illegal immigrants and one count of federal tax fraud. An employee 
for the restaurants, Martha Idalia Rios, also pleaded guilty to 
conspiracy to employ illegal immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the brothers nor their attorney would comment Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	As part of the plea agreement, the brothers and 17 Filiberto's  
managers have agreed to pay a $1.9 million fine and pay all back 
taxes to the Internal Revenue Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The managers will pay $400,000 of the fine and the brothers will  
pay the balance. The managers did not face criminal charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
