<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Did Salt Lake Get Special Info? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANBERRA, Australia (AP) -- Highly sensitive Australian  
diplomatic assessments for Sydney's 2000 Olympics bid were passed 
on to Salt Lake City's 2002 Winter Games bid team, it was reported 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian Broadcasting Corp. radio said confidential briefings  
from Australia's department of foreign affairs and notes by IOC 
member Phil Coles had been obtained by Salt Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC said it was clear that Australian diplomats were working for  
the Sydney bid, adding that Salt Lake City's Olympic committee 
received nearly 400 pages of the confidential files of Sydney's bid 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	The revelations came as the IOC's executive board decided to  
continue its investigation of Coles in the Salt Lake City bribery 
scandal, with a final report due June 13. 
</P>
<P>
	The board also decided to drop its inquiry of Kim Un-yong, a  
member of the ruling panel and the highest-ranking official 
implicated in the scandal. Both Kim and Coles already have received 
severe warnings from the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents quoted by the Australian network included letters  
and cables from senior diplomats at 23 foreign missions, with one 
offering to get around rules on gifts to International Olympic 
Committee by having the embassy pay, ABC said. 
</P>
<P>
	It quoted a cable from Australia's ambassador to Poland, Tony  
Kevin, in March 1993 about a meeting with Poland's IOC member, 
Wlodzimierz Reczek. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not think we misunderstood his message -- there were  
certain conditions,'' the cable said. ``Poland was not a big or 
rich country and would need help from abroad in supporting its team 
for the 2000 Olympics (and) perhaps the Australian Olympic 
Committee could do something to help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government had since entered an agreement with  
Poland to bring athletes to train in Australia, paying for the bulk 
of the cost, ABC radio said. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian diplomats in China had suggested in 1993 the  
Mongolian IOC member ``might be seduced by the attraction of 
Australian mutton.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And a senior diplomat in Paris had offered to send Prince Albert  
of Monaco three Australian Rules football videos, while suggesting 
they be sent as diplomatic gifts rather than Olympic presents. 
</P>
<P>
	The ABC said it was not known if any gifts were actually paid  
for or passed on by diplomatic missions. 
</P>
<P>
	Also falling into Salt Lake's hands were individual dossiers on  
each IOC member by Coles, who played a key role in Sydney's 
successful bid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 00:32:47 </DATE_TIME>
