<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Tornado Death Toll Expected To Rise  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Oklahoma authorities say the death toll  
from last night's devastating tornadoes is expected to rise because 
destruction is just ``so massive.'' At least 45 people are 
confirmed dead in Oklahoma and Kansas. Officials are sifting 
through row after row of leveled houses and stores, looking for 
more victims. ``We have whole communities that simply aren't there 
anymore,'' Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating told NBC's ``Today'' show. 
President Clinton promised today to declare several Oklahoma and 
Kansas counties disaster areas, which would provide federal aid to 
those areas. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovars Tell of Serb Attacks  
</P>
<P>
	MORINI, Albania (AP) -- Refugees streamed into Albania today with  
fresh reports of Serb forces using extortion and murder to push 
ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. More than 2,000 refugees had crossed 
the border by midafternoon, many repeating similar stories of 
forces demanding money from ethnic Albanian refugees, and gunning 
down those who didn't comply. Officials say more than 250,000 
refugees have headed south from Kukes, but more than 100,000 remain 
in the Kukes area and do not want to leave. 

</P>
<P>
	American Jet Downs Yugoslav Fighter  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO downed a Yugoslav MiG-29  
fighter jet in a dogfight over Serbia and struck a hydraulics 
factory, fuel storage depots and armored vehicles today. It was the 
first air-to-air confrontation since the early days of the NATO 
bombing campaign. Meanwhile, cities and towns across Yugoslavia 
were slowly restoring electricity and water after NATO jets blasted 
power plants in strikes aimed at disrupting the Yugoslav military. 
Serbia lost 70 percent of its electricity. 

</P>
<P>
	Gov't Workers Get No Respect on TV  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new study shows that television tends to  
depict government officials as evil or bumbling. The Center for 
Media and Public Affairs, a nonpartisan research organization, 
studied prime-time television over the last four decades to see how 
the shows presented elected officials, civil servants, law 
enforcers, teachers and other government workers. It found teachers 
and police fared the best, and office-seekers the worst. Elected 
officials had more bad guys than other TV occupations. Postal 
workers are often shown as lazy, inept malcontents. 

</P>
<P>
	Newspaper Circulation Declines  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Despite some gains by larger newspapers, overall  
daily newspaper circulation declined by 0.5 percent in the six 
months ending in March, an industry association reported. The top 
ten papers with circulations over half a million, including the New 
York Times and Washington Post, reported a gain of 0.02 percent 
over the same six-month period a year ago, according to data 
released by the Audit Bureau of Circulations. The Newspaper 
Association has launched an effort to boost readership at a time 
when consumers face more choices for getting news, including the 
Internet and television and radio sources. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 52  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 52.40 to 10,962.29. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,509-1,351. The Nasdaq was up 0.93 to 
2,536.51. 

</P>
<P>
	Cuban May Have Defected  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- At least one person who was part of the Cuban  
baseball team's delegation to the United States is seeking asylum 
here, the Associated Press has learned. Officials at the 
Immigration and Naturalization Service did not say if baseball 
players were involved. The Cuban players were greeted by Fidel 
Castro upon their return to Havana, and given heroes' welcomes for 
their victory over Baltimore. 

</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw to D.C. in WNBA Draft  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw was the No. 1 pick in the  
WNBA draft today, selected by the Washington Mystics following a 
college career in which she led Tennessee to three straight NCAA 
titles. Following Holdsclaw, former ABL players were the next three 
selections: Yolanda Griffith to the Sacramento Monarchs, Natalie 
Williams to the Utah Starzz and DeLisha Milton to the Los Angeles 
Sparks. The ABL, a rival of the WNBA, folded midway through its 
season last year. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
