<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Twister Raked Ground for Miles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORMAN, Okla. (AP) -- The biggest twister to tear through  
Oklahoma was a monster unlike most any other tornado, cutting a 
path one mile wide and tearing up miles of the flat countryside. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's at the outer edge,'' said Dr. Fred Carr, director of  
the University of Oklahoma School of Meteorology. ``Just a few 
percent will do that in a given year. This is at the extreme.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said most tornadoes only measure 500 to 600 feet wide and  
reach the ground briefly, skipping across the landscape. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest of Monday's tornadoes was classified F-5 -- the  
highest on the Fujita scale, which measures storm severity -- 
meaning it had winds in excess of 260 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	That was a whopper even for the heart of a region used to  
twisters. Tornado Alley, a swath running from west Texas through 
Oklahoma and Kansas to Iowa, is ripe for stormy conditions because 
of colliding air masses that occur each spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's storms left at least 43 dead in Oklahoma and Kansas and  
were the deadliest to hit Oklahoma since April 9, 1947, when a 
twister killed 113. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that makes this unique is putting a violent tornado  
through a heavily populated area,'' said Harold Brooks, a 
researcher with the National Severe Storms Laboratory in Norman. 
``That's the primary reason for the high death toll.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exceptional tornadoes such as Monday's are the product of  
supercells, considered the kings of thunderstorms. They soar 60,000 
feet into the atmosphere -- nearly twice as high as the zone where 
jet aircraft fly. 
</P>
<P>
	Most thunderstorms die in an hour or so, but an anvil-shaped  
supercell persists for hours and travels hundreds of miles, hurling 
the most destructive weather in its path. 
</P>
<P>
	The big tornado in Oklahoma formed the classic dark funnel as it  
sucked debris along its path. Tornadoes often are masked by rain 
and can't be seen, but not this one. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sucked our hair straight up,'' said a witness, Kathy  
Martin. ``I'm here to tell you, whoever did that movie `Twister' 
has got it down.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
