<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	URENA, Venezuela (AP) -- The presidents of Venezuela and Colombia  
on Tuesday hugged, joked, and pledged to improve bilateral ties -- 
two months after an initial meeting was canceled over what Colombia 
called imprudent remarks by Venezuela's Hugo Chavez. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombian President Andres Pastrana refused to meet the  
Venezuelan leader in this hot border city on March 10 after Chavez 
declared himself ``neutral'' in Colombia's rebel war and suggested 
guerrillas were a legitimate fighting force. 
</P>
<P>
	Both presidents indicated Tuesday that the incident was  
forgotten. 
</P>
<P>
	``That phase has been overcome,'' Chavez said during a joint  
news conference with Pastrana. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez, the leader of a failed 1992 coup attempt, steered clear  
of provoking more controversy on the rebel issue, stressing that he 
would follow the lead of Pastrana and would be available to help in 
any way including as a mediator. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombian rebel leaders and government officials met twice in  
February in Venezuela to try to advance stalled peace talks. The 
three-decade conflict has left tens of thousands of people dead. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- A judge ordered the arrest of a  
former army chief and an ex-defense minister on corruption charges 
Tuesday, a sign of growing civilian control over the 
once-untouchable military. 
</P>
<P>
	The order comes amid allegation that Mario Hung Pacheco, the  
former army leader, and Cristobal Corrales took money in 1997 in 
exchange for licensing a private security company. Prosecutors 
claimed neither had the power to issue the license. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges once would have been unthinkable in Honduras, where  
military held great political influence in the years after 
restoring the country to civilian rule in 1982. But lately civilian 
officials have gradually reasserted authority over the armed 
forces. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- Three children died  
when a mudslide triggered by heavy rains buried a house in a poor 
neighborhood of the Dominican capital, Civil Defense officials said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The children were sleeping with their mother, who was also  
injured, when a wall of mud struck their house in the Cristo Rey 
neighborhood Monday morning, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The children ranged in age from 4 to 11.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- A judge ordered a California  
man on Tuesday to stand trial in the kidnapping a 75-year-old 
woman. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Gorims, 47, is accused of kidnapping Martha Nohemi Lara  
de Valladares, a relative of Marta Valladares, a prominent member 
of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, which is the 
country's second-largest political party. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said the kidnappers at first demanded $1 million in  
ransom but eventually settled for $20,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorims was arrested in August as he tried to leave the country.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- About 8,000 government  
doctors are warning patients they will strike for 48 hours 
Wednesday to demand raises. 
</P>
<P>
	The strike could affect clinics and more than 54 government  
hospitals that serve about 40,000 patients daily, the government 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors are demanding raises from their base pay of $680 a month  
to $1,720. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The head of Mexico's state oil company said  
Tuesday the recovery in world oil prices following a new round of 
output cuts came quicker than had been expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``We could not be happier about the increase in the price of our  
export crude,'' Adrian Lajous told a press conference to announce 
the first quarter results of Petroleos Mexicanos or Pemex. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexico's export crude basket averaged around $14.55 a barrel in  
the last week of April, compared with $9.27 a barrel in the first 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude prices have recovered significantly since producers of the  
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and non-OPEC members 
agreed to cut a further 2.1 million barrels a day from world oil 
supply as of April 1. 
</P>
