<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S. treasury bonds fell Tuesday amid renewed  
fears that the Fed might hike interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 25/32  
points, or by $7.81 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which 
moves in the opposite direction, rose to 5.71 percent from Monday's 
5.65 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices dropped after two more strong economic reports fed fears  
that the Federal Reserve Board might hike interest rates to cool 
down the economy before it overheats. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board reported that a key gauge of future  
economic activity rose for the sixth straight month in March. The 
research group's index of leading economic indicators rose 0.1 
percent in March, pushed higher in part by rising stock prices. 
</P>
<P>
	In a second confirmation that the housing market remains robust,  
the Commerce Department reported that completion of privately owned 
housing units rose 12.6 percent in March, the fastest pace since 
April 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were down 1/16 point, while intermediate maturities ranged between 
down 7/32 and down 11/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a 
financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on three-month Treasury bills was 4.61 percent as the  
discount rose 0.01 percentage point from Monday's auction price to 
4.49 percent. Six-month yields rose to 4.68 percent, while the 
discount increased 0.01 percentage point from Monday's auction 
price to 4.51 percent. One-year yields held steady at 4.77 percent 
as the discount remained unchanged from Monday at 4.54 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.69 percent from Monday's 5.13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell to 123 from 123 5/16 late Monday. The 
average yield to maturity rose to 5.32 percent from 5.30 percent 
late Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
