<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Speedway Gets Tape of Flying Wheel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Investigators examined a fan's videotape  
that shows a wheel flying into the grandstand where three people 
were killed and eight others injured during last weekend's race. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't show it from start to finish, but it's still better  
than anything we've gotten up to this point,'' track spokesman 
Jerry Gappens said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gappens said the camcorder videotape was shot by a spectator who  
was sitting in the terrace boxes atop the grandstands in the fourth 
turn during Saturday night's Pep Boys Indy Racing League event. 
</P>
<P>
	The spectator turned the tape over to Lowe's Motor Speedway on  
the condition his identity not be revealed. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators hope to find a videotape that will show them how  
the wheel snapped off one of the cars in the three-car wreck. 
</P>
<P>
	They also want to determine how much clearance there was between  
the wheel and the top of a safety fence that reaches 15 feet above 
the track surface. 
</P>
<P>
	The information would help them determine if any safety changes  
could be made to the cars and how much the height of the fence 
should be increased. 
</P>
<P>
	The spectator's videotape that was turned over to speedway  
officials Monday night shows neither the wreck itself nor the wheel 
going over the fence. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see it after it clears the fence and before it hit. It was  
already on its way down and it was coming in high,'' Gappens said. 
``But at least we see the object coming into the stands. It's the 
first time we've seen that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The race was carried by Speedvision, a small cable network that  
was broadcasting an IRL race for the first time. Speedvision's 
cameras did not capture the start of the wreck or any debris flying 
into the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Television video usually helps quite a bit,'' Gappens said,  
``but that's not the case this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even without conclusive evidence of how much clearance there was  
between the wheel and the top of the catch fence, speedway 
officials are still considering raising the height. The track's 
engineers and architects have been studying the matter since the 
accident, and a decision is likely soon, Gappens said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully in the next day or two we'll have something more to  
share in that regard,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, a funeral was held for the first of the victims. A  
service for Jeffrey Patton, 32, was held in his hometown of 
Hickory. 
</P>
<P>
	A funeral was scheduled Wednesday for Randy Pyatte, 21, of  
Connelly Springs. The parents of the third victim, Barry Mobley, 
41, of Statesville, planned to take his body back to their home in 
Georgia for burial. 
</P>
<P>
	The only one of the eight injured people still hospitalized,  
Haley McGee, 9, of Conover, remained in Carolinas Medical Center in 
Charlotte. She was in critical condition with brain and lung 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Speedway officials held the first of several counseling sessions  
for any of the nearly 50,000 spectators who want to discuss the 
accident. Three 90-minute sessions were offered Tuesday in 
Charlotte and two more were scheduled for Wednesday and Thursday 
nights in Hildebran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 15:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cos. Hear Disgruntled Voices on Web </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When disgruntled customer Phil Van der Vossen  
launched a Web page in February to bash Internet retailer Buy.com, 
he was trying to be a thorn in their side. 
</P>
<P>
	Little did he expect that two months later, he would be on an  
all-expense paid trip to California to meet with the consumer 
electronics merchant's top executives. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never imagined that they would ever care enough to even look  
at the site, no less fly me out there to talk about how to improve 
their business,'' the 20-year-old University of Maryland student 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of people like Van der Vossen are taking their rage to  
the Internet these days, venting their displeasure over everything 
from Dunkin Donuts to Bally Total Fitness health clubs to an 
audience of millions. 
</P>
<P>
	And because of the widespread reach of the Internet, a growing  
number of companies are starting to pay attention, realizing that 
bad publicity online can be a threat to the bottom line. 
</P>
<P>
	Some businesses are assigning staffers or hiring cyber-snooping  
specialists to scour for vengeful Web pages and eavesdrop in chat 
rooms. Others are buying up the domain names most likely to be used 
for negative campaigning. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the Internet universe, nothing replaces word of mouth and  
word of mouth can spread fast,'' said Darryl Peck, chairman and 
chief executive of Cyberian Outpost, an online computer seller. 
``You can't ignore what is being said out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet is the fastest growing means of communication and  
information in society today. Last year, about 37 percent of all 
U.S. households were online, compared with about 27 percent in 
1997, according to the New York-based Internet research firm 
Jupiter Communications. 
</P>
<P>
	As cyberspace grows, so do the number of anti-company Web sites  
and discussion groups. Consumers are quickly realizing that the 
Internet is an unregulated space where they can reach people 
worldwide instantly for very little cost. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Internet is a very effective new weapon for the  
consumer,'' said Patricia Sturdevant, general counsel to the 
Washington-based National Association of Consumer Advocates. 
``Before the Internet, unless you had a lot of time or money, there 
wasn't any way to get the public's attention to a problem. Now, you 
can broadcast it to the entire world in an instant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's what inspired Van der Vossen to launch his site against  
Buy.com, www.buycrap.cjb.net. He was outraged by the company's 
pricing foul-up for a computer monitor and wanted to warn others to 
not shop at the online store. 
</P>
<P>
	Buy.com had mistakenly priced a Hitachi monitor on its Web site  
at $164.50, which was about $400 below cost. The company took 1,600 
orders before realizing the error. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, shoppers were given mixed messages over whether they would  
get the monitor at the bargain price and some were even charged for 
it on their credit cards without ever receiving it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted people to know that there had been many problems with  
Buy.com and that they couldn't be trusted,'' said Van der Vossen, 
whose site includes links to other anti-Buy.com sites, news 
coverage on the company and direct e-mail to the CEO. 
</P>
<P>
	``More than 5,000 people logged on to my site in the first week,  
so I know that people were interested,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of those people happened to be Buy.com's executives, who  
were trying to keep up with the bad publicity scattered about them 
online. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew many of the things that I was seeing on the Internet  
were true and we needed to start changing them,'' said Greg 
Hawkins, who took over as chief executive about two months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	While the company has yet to remedy the monitor debacle, the  
experience inspired it to revamp its business. Many of its planned 
changes come directly from comments they read online, including the 
addition of more customer service representatives and telling 
shoppers if an item is in stock or on back-order. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are cognizant of the things we want to change because they  
were communicated to us over the Internet, on Web sites and in the 
chat rooms,'' Hawkins said. 
</P>
<P>
	The giant pension system TIAA-CREF also learned that watching  
the Web pays off. In the midst of the Asian economic crisis in 
October, someone posted in a CompuServe discussion room that the 
company's Global Equities pension fund had 25 percent of its assets 
in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	But the fund only had a 5 percent stake in Asia. Since the error  
was caught within days, the company was able to contact the chat 
room mediator and stop a rumor that had the potential to spur an 
exodus of investors from the fund. 
</P>
<P>
	``Watching the Web is like competitive intelligence,'' said Alan  
Shea, who runs the new Internet monitoring company EclipZe. ``You 
need to keep track of who is saying what and who is doing what to 
stay ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While keeping an eye on the Internet keeps companies abreast of  
consumers' opinions, many are still struggling with how to respond 
to complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough to know whether or not something is a legitimate  
gripe or problem, or whether a company should respond to every Web 
site and posting,'' said Jason Alexander, founder of Ewatch, a 
company that scours the Internet on the behalf of its corporate 
clients and helps them determine when to intervene. ``It's hard to 
decide when to reach out and when to just sit back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some companies are attempting to protect themselves from an  
organized attack by registering negative domain name themselves. 
Chase Manhattan Bank, for instance, owns ihatechase.com, 
chasesucks.com and chasestinks.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer electronics retailer Best Buy has a media analyst on  
staff who tracks references to the company on the Internet, but its 
policy it to act only when it sees something that infringes on its 
logo or brand identity or defames the company, said spokeswoman Joy 
Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyberian Outpost will join an online discussion only if it feels  
that it will help remedy a problematic situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are there monitoring, but unless it is something that we  
really feel that we need to jump into, we let the customers just 
talk about it themselves,'' said Outpost's CEO Peck. ``Watching the 
Web is an information tool that helps us improve our business.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
