<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Force Remains Key Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Pledging to keep up shuttle diplomacy  
until the Kosovo conflict is settled, Russian envoy Viktor 
Chernomyrdin said Tuesday the key issue remains the type of 
peacekeeping force that would be deployed in the Yugoslav province. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether it would be paramilitary, military or civil forces --  
of course it's subject to negotiations,'' the former Russian prime 
minister told reporters after meeting U.N. Secretary-General Kofi 
Annan. 
</P>
<P>
	``There must be political will, both in Belgrade and NATO,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Chernomyrdin's second meeting with Annan in less than a  
week, and the Russian envoy said the U.N. secretary-general ``is 
determined to participate in a settlement to the crisis ... because 
there is no other organization which has as much experience as the 
United Nations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in  
Belgrade late last week, Chernomyrdin flew to Washington and spent 
2 1/2 hours with President Clinton on Monday discussing the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian envoy met Vice President Al Gore and top U.S.  
foreign policy advisers Tuesday morning before flying to New York 
to see Annan. He also held talks with Norway's Foreign Minister 
Knut Vollebaek, chairman of the Organization of Security and 
Cooperation in Europe, whose monitoring mission left Kosovo just 
before the NATO bombing began March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Praising Russia's diplomatic efforts, Vollebaek said there was  
still no ``major breakthrough. But there are positive signs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Norwegian minister, whose country is a NATO member, said  
Milosevic must accept an armed force for Kosovo ``because there is 
no way that any of us would be willing to compromise on that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can compromise on some of the other elements. But  
the necessity to have an armed, military force in Kosovo -- that is 
a prerequisite (without) which we cannot implement any peace 
agreement,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He suggested that NATO might be willing to compromise, for  
example, on whether all Yugoslav forces have to withdraw from 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	When he met Milosevic some time ago, Vollebaek recalled that the  
Yugoslav leader ``discarded any kind of international presence'' in 
Kosovo. Now, he said, ``there seems to be more of a willingness 
from Milosevic's side to have an international component, an 
international force, in Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO is demanding that its armed troops ensure the safety of  
refugees, but Milosevic has indicated that he would only allow a 
non-NATO force, armed with no more than personal weapons and under 
U.N. supervision. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked what needs to be done to stop the bombing, Vollebaek  
replied: ``I think we need a sign from Milosevic that there is a 
willingness from his side to ... accommodate some of the demands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If we see that sign, of course there should be a possibility  
for stopping the bombing,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Vollebaek said he believes the involvement of both Russia and  
the United Nations is key to the search for a peace agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin gave few details of his talks in his brief exchange  
with the media, saying he planned to return to Moscow and might 
then go to Belgrade again and elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
