<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Reported Dead in Wichita Tornado </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WICHITA, Kan. (AP) -- The unwelcome guest tore the roof off the  
Karr home and barged inside as the family huddled in terror and 
disbelief. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was freaked out at that point. I was scared for my life,''  
said 13-year-old Courtney Karr, who cowered with her 15-year-old 
sister, Jessie, and their parents as a killer tornado ripped their 
house apart. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten people were killed and up to 100 people were injured by  
Monday night's twister in Wichita and its southern suburb of 
Haysville. A tornado spawned by the same storm killed at least 29 
people in the Oklahoma City area 150 miles due south. 
</P>
<P>
	Courtney watched in horror as her house's bay windows collapsed  
and the twister's winds swirled inside. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen it on TV, but seeing it with my own eyes, tearing up  
my own home ... it is hard to explain,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The family was trapped in the basement for about half an hour  
until the storm subsided. 
</P>
<P>
	The twister cut a path 3 1/4 miles wide and 10 miles long through  
Haysville and southern Wichita. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the destruction was in Haysville, where parts of the  
older business district were demolished, including a bank, real 
estate company, chiropractor's office, a 10-unit apartment complex 
and several homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Railroad tracks were uprooted and metal, lifted and flung about  
like paper, was wrapped around trees near the ruins of the 
two-block long Norland Plastics plant. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Bill Graves declared Sedgwick County a disaster area early  
today and called on the National Guard, which set up a temporary 
morgue and an aid station. Emergency officials used military 
vehicles to evacuate some homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescue workers were going door-to-door to look for people who  
might be trapped or injured. Bob Thompson, a battalion chief for 
the Sedgwick County Fire Department, said the death toll was 
expected to rise. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we've seen the end of it,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	In Wichita, two trailer parks were devastated. Insulation, metal  
and board fragments littered the ground. A yellow toddler's slide 
and a red Schwinn bicycle floated in the muck at one park. 
</P>
<P>
	Haysville resident Duane Moore and his wife, Vicky, hid with  
their three dogs in a neighbor's storm shelter, but high winds 
yanked the door off. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't seen anything yet; I just noticed I don't have a  
house,'' Vicky Moore said as she, her husband and the dogs walked 
out of their shattered neighborhood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
