<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Leader Dissolves Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUWAIT (AP) -- Kuwait's leader dissolved Parliament on Tuesday,  
hours after lawmakers threatened to oust his Islamic Affairs 
minister for mistakes printed in 120,000 copies of the Koran. 
</P>
<P>
	Jabar al-Ahmed al-Sabah called for July 3 elections for a new  
Parliament, nearly a year and a half ahead of schedule. The emir 
said lawmakers misused their constitutional rights by demanding the 
no-confidence vote against Ahmed al-Kulaib. 
</P>
<P>
	In an emotional five-hour session earlier Tuesday, Kuwaiti  
lawmakers lambasted al-Kulaib for his ``political responsibility'' 
in allowing the Islamic holy book to be printed and released with 
verses missing, repeated or misplaced. 
</P>
<P>
	Abbas al-Khodari, the legislator who had requested the grilling,  
accused him of attempting to ``disfigure the faith of Muslims'' in 
Kuwait and abroad, where the free copies of the Koran were 
distributed. The mistake was noticed late last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a horrendous mistake that cannot be forgiven,''  
al-Khodari said, denying the impeachment calls were political. 
``Trying to correct it later does not make it go away. ... This has 
to do with the great book of God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Kulaib acknowledged the errors, saying they were made in the  
collating and binding stages. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody is denying that an unintentional mistake has been  
made,'' he said. ``The mistakes do not include any intended change 
in the meaning'' of verses. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, 20 lawmakers in the 50-seat house submitted two  
motions for a vote of no-confidence in al-Kulaib. A simple majority 
would have been needed to impeach him, and his removal in a vote 
scheduled for next Tuesday appeared likely had the emir not 
dissolved Parliament or chosen to reshuffle his Cabinet. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuwait's deputy prime minister, Sheik Sabah al-Ahmed al-Sabah,  
had urged lawmakers not to follow through with impeachment. 
Parliament and the Cabinet, he said, ``can fight over the economy 
or politics, but we should not fight over religion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheik Sabah, who was visibly upset during the session, said he  
believes in democracy, but is ``sorry we have reached the stage of 
burning down our country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only two lawmakers spoke in support of the Islamic Affairs  
minister, accusing their colleagues of early campaigning for 2000 
elections and of salting wounds instead of trying to heal them. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1976 and in 1986, the house was dissolved following  
lawmakers' severe criticism of Cabinet members. Each time, it 
remained dissolved for years. This is the first time a Kuwaiti emir 
has followed the constitution and called for elections within two 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislature was elected in 1996 and the next elections had  
been expected in October 2000. Lawmakers have been criticized for 
an inability to address the country's problems, including carrying 
out economic reforms. Kuwait has the only elected parliament among 
the Arab Gulf countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
