<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Format for News Story Coding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- News industry organizations have agreed to a new  
format for coding news stories to improve their usefulness on the 
Internet, in text archives and on devices such as pagers and 
personal digital assistants. 
</P>
<P>
	The coding language, called News Industry Text Format, will  
benefit news organizations by lowering editing and transmission 
costs while making it easy to repackage news for multiple media. 
</P>
<P>
	NITF coding can be used to mark parts of articles -- names of  
newsmakers, for example -- to make it easier for search engines to 
identify them. It can also be used to automatically identify the 
story's headline, editor's note and writer's byline, for example. 
</P>
<P>
	Wire services, including The Associated Press, plan to use the  
coding for new media products. NITF uses XML coding, or Extensible 
Markup Language, which is a new format for identifying specific 
portions of documents. 
</P>
<P>
	NITF was endorsed at an April 23 meeting in Dallas of wire  
services, newspaper front-end system vendors and industry groups, 
including the Newspaper Association of America, International Press 
Telecommunications Council and the Media Center at the American 
Press Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	The Radio-Television News Directors Association previously  
announced its support for NITF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 15:05:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palladium Falls for Third Day  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Palladium futures tumbled Tuesday for a third consecutive  
session on the New York Mercantile Exchange as another large sale 
of the industrial metal reinforced views Russia has begun heavy 
shipments. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, wheat and soybeans retreated, corn gained and  
coffee retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium fell after investors in London said as much as 120,000  
ounces of the metal had been sold. That comes after Russia on 
Friday sold 160,000 ounces, a move that caused prices to tumble 
nearly 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is the largest single producer of palladium, which is  
used in jewelry, electronics and the automobile industry. 
Large-scale shipments had been halted since December, however, amid 
bureaucratic delays that have taken place for three consecutive 
years at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
	The delays have forced auto manufacturers in particular to  
scramble for available supplies since many use the metal in the 
manufacture of emission-control devices required under clean-air 
laws in a number of countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium for June delivery fell $6.30 to $290 an ounce.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures and soybean futures retreated on the Chicago Board  
of Trade, while corn futures advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures fell amid continued expectations of an improved  
winter wheat crop and as farmers rushed to get spring wheat into 
the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures gained on the U.S. Agriculture Department's report  
that plantings remain behind the five-year pace despite drier 
weekend weather. Prices also were supported by the National Weather 
Service's latest 10-day forecast, which predicted more rain for a 
soggy Midwest. That could further delay plantings as the window of 
opportunity begins to close for corn. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans were pressured by the knowledge that the planting  
window for soybeans is larger. That could mean any acreage not 
planted to corn is switched to soybeans. Prices also were pressured 
by the continuation of harvesting in South America, although that, 
too, has been slowed by inclement weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 1 3/4 cents to $2.62 1/4 a bushel; July  
corn rose 2 1/4 cents to $2.22 3/4 a bushel; July oats rose 1 cent to 
$1.18 3/4 a bushel; July soybeans fell 1 1/4 cents to $4.88 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures fell on the Board of Trade of the City of New  
York amid expectations a respected crop forecaster this week will 
boost his estimate of total Brazilian production. 
</P>
<P>
	Former U.S. Agriculture Department attache Leon Yallouz, who is  
now in private business, was expected to issue a report to his 
clients that revises upward his previous estimate of a 
23.7-million-bag to 25.9-million-bag crop a month before heavy 
harvesting begins, analysts said. Each bag weighs 132 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee prices have been in the doldrums for weeks on the belief  
that Brazil, the world's largest producer, will harvest a bumper 
crop for the second consecutive year. The supplies are coming in 
after a relatively weak peak coffee consumption period came to an 
end. 
</P>
<P>
	July arabica coffee fell .70 cent to $1.02 a pound, while  
September coffee fell 1.5 cents to $1.028 a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
