<HEADLINE> Wolves Sign 1998 First-Round Pick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Radoslav Nesterovic, a 7-foot center who was the  
Minnesota Timberwolves' first round pick in 1998, signed a 
multi-year contract with the club prior to Tuesday night's game 
against the Houston Rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	He was in uniform for the game.  
</P>
<P>
	Nesterovic, a native of Slovenia, recently finished his second  
season with Kinder Bologna, where he averaged 13.5 points and 6.2 
rebounds during the Italian League regular season. The team also 
played in the EuroLeague finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're happy that he can participate for us for the remainder  
of this season,'' team vice president of basketball operations 
Kevin McHale said. ``We want him to get his feet wet and get 
acclimated to the NBA and the Twin Cities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Wolves picked Nesterovic 17th overall last June, even though  
he had a year left on his Italian contract. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Timberwolves hadn't signed Nesterovic by Wednesday, they  
wouldn't have been able to negotiate with him until Aug. 1. That 
would have given other European teams time to make offers, and they 
could pay him more than the three-year, $2.6 million deal he gets 
from the Wolves. 
</P>
<P>
	To make room on the roster, the Timberwolves placed forward Bill  
Curley on the injured list with a sprained right wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	Curley played in 35 games this season and averaged 2.2 points  
and 1.5 rebounds. The Timberwolves also waived rookie center Trevor 
Winter, who appeared in one game this season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
