<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 500 Days Until Sydney Olympic Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The shadow of the Olympic corruption  
scandal fell across the festivities Tuesday as organizers started a 
500-day countdown to the start of the 2000 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	While officials brought out a giant fake kangaroo on a bicycle  
and a glittering sculpture for auction, one of the key players in 
bringing the games to Sydney was placed under renewed 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive board of the International Olympic Committee  
appointed a three-member panel to look at the latest allegations 
against Phil Coles, a former Olympic athlete now accused of abusing 
his IOC position. The panel will report to the full IOC June 13. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles was censured after the IOC's votes-for-bribes case in Salt  
Lake City, and is being further investigated for allegedly 
receiving excessive gifts from someone associated with Athens' 
failed 1996 bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles also was at the center of fresh allegations Tuesday that  
confidential briefing notes from the Sydney bid were given to 
organizers of the successful Salt Lake City team. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has stepped aside from the board of the Sydney Organizing  
Committee for the Olympic Games pending an IOC decision, but 
president Michael Knight believes he should already have resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	``My position has always been that I think it would be in both  
Phil Coles' interests and Sydney's interests for him to remove 
himself permanently from the SOCOG board,'' Knight said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	At a function in a shopping mall in central Sydney, Knight  
helped auction the first of 500 numbered sculptures, one of which 
will be sold each day between now and Sept. 15, 2000, when the 
games begin. 
</P>
<P>
	Made of the same steel as the cauldron that will hold the  
Olympic flame during the games and the same silver as the medals, 
the sculpture sold for $17,000. 
</P>
<P>
	With SOCOG still $110 million short of its budget, Knight  
greeted the money as ``26,000 (Australian dollars) we didn't have 
yesterday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG has had to cut its $1.65 billion budget by $48.7 million  
because of sponsor wariness blamed on the IOC scandal, and to pay 
for other contingencies. 
</P>
<P>
	A special committee has been appointed to find the savings.  
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, games preparations are well advanced.  
</P>
<P>
	The $2.1 billion construction program is 85 percent complete and  
the six more venues expected to be finished by the end of 1999 will 
supply all the promised permanent sporting venues, Knight said. 
</P>
<P>
	A dispute with local residents about closing part of Bondi beach  
for the beach volleyball is yet to be resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're down to the business end of running the games,'' he  
said. ``We're in good shape but we've got a lot of things to do and 
a fairly short time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The complete event-by-event schedule was released this week,  
giving organizers an opportunity to gear up campaigns to refocus 
attention on sport rather than scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Tickets go on sale in Australia on May 30 and SOCOG concedes  
raising the budgeted $390 million in sales is a challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC coordination commission inspected Sydney's preparations  
last week and came away generally satisfied in the areas of venues, 
athletes and media villages, medical, accommodation, security and 
ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	Commission head Jacques Rogge said he was satisfied problems  
with technology and the budget were being dealt with. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
