<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Launches Asthma Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton encouraged parents who  
smoke to light up outside the home as she helped launch several 
initiatives to help children fight asthma, a disease that has 
reached epidemic proportions. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 14 million to 15 million Americans have asthma but  
many don't realize that their wheezing, coughing and breathing 
problems are caused by it. The disease is the leading cause of 
hospitalization for children and one of the main reasons children 
miss school. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to pay particular attention to poor families because  
it is the children of the poor who suffer disproportionately from 
this disease,'' Mrs. Clinton said Tuesday as she kicked off a 
national asthma screening program at an inner-city elementary 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	Black children suffer the most from asthma, according to the  
American College of Allergy, Asthma and Immunology. Although their 
risk of contracting it is only slightly higher than for other 
children, black children are more than four times more likely to 
die from it. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of children with asthma has doubled to 6 million in  
the last 15 years, said Dr. Talal Nsouli, Washington chairman of 
the ACAAI's screening program. The rate for children under age 5 is 
1.6 times higher than it was 15 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 200 schools, shopping malls, community centers and  
health fairs offered free screenings Tuesday as part of the program 
to increase detection of asthma. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton called on Congress to enact a White House proposal  
to help fight asthma. The Department of Health and Human Services 
wants to spend $50 million for state grants that would identify and 
treat poor children served by Medicaid who have asthma. 
</P>
<P>
	Asthma can be controlled with medication but early detection and  
constant, appropriate treatment are the best ways to prevent asthma 
statistics from increasing further, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton also introduced a public service campaign to  
promote a study released by the Environmental Protection Agency 
that says exposure to secondhand smoke considerably worsens asthma 
for up to a million children. It also increases the chances among 
young children that they will contract pneumonia, ear infections, 
bronchitis and sudden infant death syndrome, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton encouraged parents who smoke to avoid doing so  
around their children or in their homes. She said she has 
implemented a nonsmoking policy at the White House, which has led 
to some ``tickly'' situations involving visiting kings, prime 
ministers and other heads of state who tried to light up a 
cigarette inside and were shooed outdoors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that you'll think of your house, the White House, as an  
example perhaps for your own house,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
