<DOCNO> APW19990504.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 15:35:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Celebration for Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- What Palestinians once hoped would  
be their Independence Day began like any other for laborer Abdel 
Kareem Abu Najim: Waiting in the pre-dawn darkness at a dusty 
border crossing for permission to go to his $25-a-day construction 
job in Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday, the end of a five-year autonomy agreement with Israel,  
was once touted by Yasser Arafat as the day a Palestinian state 
could finally be declared. It became instead a melancholy milestone 
for Palestinians, the latest in a long line of hopes deferred. 
</P>
<P>
	A few Palestinians reacted with shows of defiance -- some clearly  
meant to underscore the threat of violence if the deadlock with 
Israel continues. In the West Bank town of Hebron, masked men fired 
rifles into the air while hundreds of marchers chanted, ``Statehood 
is our right!'' 
</P>
<P>
	A group of marchers broke away and hurled stones at Israeli  
troops who fired rubber-coated steel pellets in response. Three 
Palestinians and an Israeli TV cameramen were injured. A clash in 
the town of Beitunia left one demonstrator injured. 
</P>
<P>
	But such demonstrations were small and scattered. Throughout the  
Palestinian lands, the overriding sentiment was one of quiet 
disappointment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just like any day -- all I can think about is getting  
work,'' said Abu Najim, a 36-year-old father of six who lives in 
Gaza's Nusseirat refugee camp, stepping momentarily out of the long 
line of Palestinian workers passing through the Erez checkpoint 
between the Gaza Strip and Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Trained as an accountant, he works instead as a day laborer and  
was headed Tuesday for a construction site outside Tel Aviv. The 
$20 to $30 he makes there each day is more than he would be paid in 
Gaza -- even if he could find a job, which he cannot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I leave my house at 3 a.m. ... I'm so exhausted, and I never  
see my children,'' said Abu Najim, rubbing red-rimmed eyes. 
``That's what statehood would mean to me, having a job in my field, 
being able to have time with my family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Few here argue with Arafat's decision to delay a declaration of  
statehood, despite the long-held Palestinian view that they had the 
right to become independent upon Tuesday's expiration of the Oslo 
interim peace accords. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a declaration now, in the absence of a negotiated statehood  
agreement with Israel, would likely have brought a sweeping Israeli 
crackdown -- and ignited Israelis' fears over national security, 
thus boosting re-election prospects for hard-line Israeli Prime 
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in voting only 13 days away. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with an almost universal sense among Palestinians that  
holding off on statehood was the smart tactical move, seeing the 
day come and go brought a palpable sense of letdown. 
</P>
<P>
	A cartoon in the leading daily newspaper Al-Quds had three  
panels, the first showing a calendar page marked May 3 and the last 
showing May 5. In the middle, where the May 4 Tuesday date would 
normally be, was a page with the notation: ``Forget it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat, perhaps wishing to disassociate himself from the day's  
unhappy associations -- and from any potential unrest -- spent the 
day outside the country, visiting Ireland and Algeria. 
</P>
<P>
	In Jerusalem, Netanyahu claimed it was his unyielding stance  
toward the Palestinians that had staved off a declaration of 
independence. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the fourth of May and there is no declaration of  
Palestinian statehood,'' the prime minister told reporters. ``It's 
an important achievement for the state of Israel and the government 
of Israel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Netanyahu government has frozen compliance with the  
U.S.-brokered land-for-peace accords negotiated last September, 
saying the Palestinians have not lived up to their commitments. 
</P>
<P>
	The prime minister said if he were re-elected, his government  
would work toward a new accord that would ``give the Palestinians 
the freedom to manage their own affairs,'' while safeguarding 
Israel's interests. Netanyahu opposes Palestinian independence. 
</P>
<P>
	But the notion that Israel could indefinitely prevent a  
statehood declaration drew derisive laughter from Palestinians in 
the Khan Younis refugee camp, living in some of the worst 
conditions in Gaza. The smell of sewage hangs in the warm air, and 
debris litters the sandy streets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is there anyone who doesn't want to control their destiny? Who  
could possibly doubt that this will happen?'' said Abdul Hamid, 54, 
who lives with a family of 15 in a small cement-block house with a 
corrugated tin roof. ``We will have our state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Mercy Mosque in Gaza City's old town, the imam, or prayer  
leader, said he kept the day's meaning in mind during Tuesday's 
morning prayers. Only about a dozen worshippers made their way 
through the dawn chill to join in. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pray that we will have peace and stability in our land,''  
said Mohammed Ali Yussef, white-bearded and dressed in the 
traditional long white robe. ``I think the coming of a Palestinian 
state will bring that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Gaza's Mediterranean shore, a teen-age fisherman said that  
for him, statehood might mean freedom to cast his nets without 
being kept close to the shore by Israeli patrol boats. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's only a normal day -- no state for us now,'' said Rashid  
Abu Mahdi, his trousers soaked to the knee and held up with twine 
from a fishing net. ''But things will change.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
