<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Oil Co. Mulls Repsol Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- The board of Argentina's YPF SA  
energy company will ask an investment bank to review a $13.4 
billion acquisition offer by Spain's Repsol SA. 
</P>
<P>
	The Argentine oil giant did not specify which bank would be  
tapped for the review, but said Tuesday that YPF board members will 
meet again by May 13 to comment on Repsol's offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The bid announced last Thursday could lead to the latest merger  
in the rapidly consolidating oil industry. A deal would create one 
of the world's 10 biggest oil companies with revenue of more than 
$27 billion a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Repsol offered to pay YPF shareholders $44.78 a share for the 85  
percent of the local energy giant it doesn't already own. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting Monday, YPF's board received formal notification of  
the Repsol tender, saying details would be relayed to shareholders. 
Repsol chairman Alfonso Cortina, who was elected last month to 
YPF's 12-member board, did not attend. 
</P>
<P>
	Repsol's all-cash offer runs from May 24 through June 23 and is  
conditioned on Repsol obtaining a majority ownership of YPF. If the 
deal between the two former state-owned oil companies goes through, 
Repsol said it hopes to achieve double-digit earnings growth 
through 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company would be a powerful Latin American rival to  
the state oil companies of Venezuela and Brazil. While the bid was 
uninvited, Repsol officials declined to describe it as hostile, 
expressing hope the YPF board would recommend the offer to 
shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Repsol acquired 14.99 percent of YPF from the  
Argentine government for $2.01 billion. The Spanish company has 
strengths in crude oil refining and marketing of final products. 
</P>
<P>
	YPF owns and operates three refineries, and owns 2,253 service  
stations in Argentina. It specializes in oil production and 
exploration. It earned $1.1 billion on revenue of $5.5 billion in 
1998. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
