<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T To Acquire MediaOne for $54B  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. and Comcast Corp. reached a deal  
tonight, paving the way for AT&AMP;T's $54 billion acquisition of 
MediaOne Group Inc. Under the agreement, the two companies will 
exchange various cable systems, resulting in the net addition of 
750,000 subscribers for Comcast, the nation's No. 3 cable company. 
Because Comcast is obtaining more subscribers, it will pay AT&AMP;T up 
to $3.5 billion. The majority of the exchanges are subject to the 
completion of the AT&AMP;T-MediaOne merger. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton May Release Serb POWs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is considering ordering the  
return of two captured Serb soldiers to Yugoslavia after the 
release of three U.S. POWs, a White House aide said tonight. Senior 
administration officials were reviewing the idea as Clinton heads 
to Europe to get an update from NATO commanders on the airstrikes 
and meet with American troops. One of the Serb soldiers was turned 
over to U.S. military officials in Albania in mid-April after his 
capture by members of the Kosovo Liberation Army. The second came 
into U.S. custody last week, according to Pentagon officials. The 
Rev. Jesse Jackson, who secured the release of the U.S. soldiers, 
met with Clinton yesterday and asked him to consider releasing the 
Yugoslav soldiers. 

</P>
<P>
	Poll: Bush Holds Big Lead Over Gore  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush has taken a strong lead over  
Elizabeth Dole in New Hampshire in the race for the Republican 
presidential nomination, and retains a big advantage nationally, 
according to two polls released today. On the Democratic side, Vice 
President Al Gore has expanded his lead over Bill Bradley, 
according to a national poll of Democrats by CNN-USA Today-Gallup. 
Gore had 66 percent in the poll, while Bradley had 23 percent. In 
mid-April, Bradley trailed Gore 54 percent to 34 percent. Bush 
leads Gore in a theoretical match by 56 percent to 40 percent, in 
the CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll, about the same lead Bush has held 
over Gore since February. 

</P>
<P>
	Twister Raked Ground for Miles  
</P>
<P>
	NORMAN, Okla. (AP) -- The biggest twister to tear through  
Oklahoma was a monster unlike most any other tornado, cutting a 
path one mile wide and tearing up miles of countryside. Multiple 
tornadoes slammed Oklahoma and Kansas yesterday, killing at least 
43 people. Dr. Fred Carr, director of the University of Oklahoma 
School of Meteorology, said most tornadoes measure 500 to 600 feet 
wide and reach the ground briefly, skipping across the landscape. 
The biggest of yesterday's tornadoes was classified F-5 -- the 
highest on the Fujita scale, which measures storm severity -- 
meaning it had winds in excess of 260 mph. That was a whopper even 
for the heart of a region used to twisters. 

</P>
<P>
	New Boeing Rocket Malfunctions  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Boeing's new Delta III rocket  
blasted into space tonight, eight months after the inaugural flight 
ended in a midair explosion. But it quickly ran into trouble. The 
second stage used to boost the Orion communication satellite into a 
higher orbit ignited properly the first time, but apparently did 
not fire as long as it should have the second time around. If the 
information is correct, the satellite could be in too low of an 
orbit. The satellite was supposed to serve Asia and the Pacific for 
Loral Space and Communications from a 22,300-mile-high perch. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Announces Internet Safety Plan  
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- The nation's major Internet companies  
have agreed to offer parents faster access to technology allowing 
them to control and monitor children's online habits, Vice 
President Al Gore said today. Gore called the agreement ``a 
positive step forward'' that could keep youngsters away from 
``inappropriate content'' like violent game sites or hate group 
sites. Under the agreement, officials have developed an Internet 
site containing a series of resources, including a ``guide to good 
content,'' and safety tips for youngsters and parents. 

</P>
