<HEADLINE> Newspaper Circulation Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Daily newspaper circulation declined 0.5 percent  
in the six-month period ending in March, continuing a long-term 
trend that the newspaper industry is hoping to reverse. Sunday 
circulation fell by 1.0 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Larger newspapers reported slight gains in circulation, but  
smaller ones continued to struggle with declines, according to data 
released by the Audit Bureau of Circulations. 
</P>
<P>
	The top 10 papers with circulations over half a million reported  
a gain of 0.02 percent over the same six-month period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Large papers reporting circulation increases included USA Today,  
The New York Times, The Washington Post, the Los Angeles Times, 
Newsday and the Daily News of New York. The Chicago Tribune 
reported gains in its Wednesday, Thursday and Friday editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Smaller papers generally reported declines. According to an  
analysis of the Audit Bureau's data by the Newspaper Association of 
America, the 30 papers with circulations between 250,000 and 
500,000 posted a decline of 0.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The 67 papers between 100,000 and 250,000 daily circulation  
declined 0.1 percent, and the 111 papers between 50,000 and 100,000 
declined by 0.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to the long-term decline in newspaper readership,  
which has nagged the industry for years, the Newspaper Association 
has launched an effort to boost readership at a time when consumers 
face more and more choices for getting news from cable TV and the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The first phase of the NAA's campaign was officially launched  
last week at the group's annual convention under the guidance of 
Sergio Zyman, a former marketing executive for Coca-Cola Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Commenting on the figures, NAA president and CEO John F. Sturm  
said: ``The newspaper industry is strong financially. Now, we 
recognize both the need and the opportunity to invest our resources 
in growing readership.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
