<DOCNO> APW19990504.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 03:25:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles, Baltimore Cops Get Lessons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles learned a thing or two  
about baseball from a Cuban team that brought the proper attitude 
into a game of historic proportions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Baltimore police, meanwhile, got a lesson in crowd control  
from the second-base umpire. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles were humiliated by a feisty team of Cuban all-stars  
Monday night, falling 12-6 in the first game held in the United 
States between a Cuban team and a major league club. 
</P>
<P>
	``This victory has great meaning, not just for me but for all  
the players and all the Cuban people,'' third baseman Omar Linares 
said. ``We just tied the series between the Orioles and Cuba.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans treated the game with reverence. Baltimore wanted the  
day off. 
</P>
<P>
	By the third inning, the Orioles trailed 6-3 and were pretty  
much done for the evening. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, they wanted it much more than we did. They showed a  
lot of energy, and my hat's off to them,'' Baltimore manager Ray 
Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans ran around the bases at a dizzying pace, but arguably  
the biggest burst of energy was displayed by second-base umpire 
Cesar Valdez. 
</P>
<P>
	Three protesters ran onto the field in the middle of the fourth  
inning and were eventually run down by Baltimore police and charged 
with trespassing. A fourth ran onto the field in the top of the 
fifth carrying a sign that read ``Freedom -- Strike out against 
Castro.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valdez body-slammed the man to the ground and began punching him  
until Baltimore outfielder B.J. Surhoff separated the two. At that 
point, police finally stepped in and ushered the man off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``Above all, I am Cuban,'' Valdez said. ``I just thought it was  
the right way to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Apparently, it was. No one else ran onto the field after that,  
but the incidents were almost as embarrassing to the hosts as the 
lopsided final score. 
</P>
<P>
	``It didn't affect us at all, this lack of respect by the  
spectators,'' Linares said. ``The ones who should worry about this 
are the organizers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The arrests marred a night in which the Orioles made a  
concentrated effort to be exemplary hosts to the Cubans. The team 
served Cuban-style food and drink at the concession stands, played 
Latin music over the public address system before the game and gave 
the Cuban contingent excellent seats behind the visitor's dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	But the hosts couldn't control a few unruly fans -- or the  
weather, which was damp and chilly. 
</P>
<P>
	It was drizzling when Baltimore's Scott Kamieniecki threw the  
first pitch, and the game was delayed by rain for 56 minutes in the 
bottom of the first. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles thrilled the sellout crowd of 47,940 with two runs  
in the first inning, but the Cubans quickly took over and gained a 
split in the historic two-game series that began in Havana on March 
28. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were excited about their win. That's how they play,''  
Surhoff said. ``I've played against them in international events 
and they're usually older teams playing against younger kids. It's 
not the way we play, but that's what they do. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a no-win situation for us. If we won, we were supposed  
to win,'' Surhoff said. ``If we lost, we didn't play so well. We 
just didn't play well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By the third inning, the home fans were booing their  
high-priced, last-place team. The Cuban fans, however, were having 
a grand old time. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Orioles' mascot spelled out O-R-I-O-L-E-S for the fans  
in center field, several fans rooting for the visitors retaliated 
by spelling out C-U-B-A over and over. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the game, the winners walked to the center of the  
field carrying two Cuban flags. They exchanged handshakes between 
themselves and then cheerfully shook hands with the Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was the day we have been waiting for,'' Linares said.  
``We hope to have many like it in coming years as well.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
