<DOCNO> APW19990504.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 16:33:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sharks' Postseason Goes In the Tank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Left wing Jeff Friesen knows why his San  
Jose Sharks failed to get past the opening round of the Stanley Cup 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're too slow and not strong enough to make any progress. To  
move ahead, we have to be ready,'' Friesen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sharks got off to a dismal start this season, winless in  
their first eight games. Still, they rebounded to make the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	But that was of little comfort as the Sharks once again failed  
to have a .500 season. San Jose has never reached the milestone as 
a franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want our team to finish over .500 next year. We're so close  
to getting there. All it will take is a little more work,'' Friesen 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sharks started the season 0-6-2, but went 26-19-11 in their  
last 56 games to claim a seventh-place finish in the Western 
Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	In the midst of their recovery, they had to go on the longest  
uninterrupted road trip in NHL history, a grueling 10 games that 
sent them to Phoenix, Los Angeles, Chicago, St. Louis, Tampa Bay, 
Florida, Detroit, Buffalo and Washington in February. They emerged 
4-5-1. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sharks were 31-33-18 at the end of the regular season. The  
team set franchise records for fewest goals allowed at 191, with a 
team goals-against average of 2.28. 
</P>
<P>
	Vincent Damphousse, who came to the Sharks at the trading  
deadline from Montreal, speculated that the start cost the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a better team now than at the start of the season,''  
he said. ``We had a slow start and I think that hurt us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some on the team blamed the start on a tiring season-opening  
road trip to Tokyo, where they went 0-1-1 against Calgary. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sharks did their best to make up for it. Friesen led the  
team with 22 goals and 35 assists in the regular season. Right wing 
Alex Korolyuk, who was called up from the Kentucky Thoroughblades 
on Dec. 11, had 12 goals and 18 assists with the Sharks and was 
named the team's rookie of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Veteran goalie Mike Vernon and backup Steve Shields also proved  
competent. Together, they combined for a franchise-record eight 
shutouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Shields was especially effective down the stretch, going 9-0-2  
with three shutouts from March 9 to April 12. 
</P>
<P>
	One oddity of the Sharks' season was the saga of defenseman  
Andrei Zyuzin, who abruptly fired his agent on March 19 and went 
AWOL from the team for 12 games. During his absence, he was 
represented by Vitaly Shevchenko, who was not recognized as an 
agent by the NHL player's union. Zyuzin eventually rehired his 
previous agent and returned to the Sharks without explanation. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end -- just like last year -- a stronger playoff opponent  
sent the Sharks on their summer vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colorado Avalanche beat them 3-2 in overtime Monday to wrap  
up the first-round series at 4-2. Last season, the Sharks fell to 
the Dallas Stars 4-2 in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado coach Bob Hartley was gracious in complimenting the  
Sharks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fans in San Jose can be real proud of their hockey club,''  
Hartley said. ``It looks good for the future and they are very 
exciting to play against.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sharks defenseman Jeff Norton agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``This team is going places,'' he said. ``We're taking shape. We  
can go places, we're just turning things our way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it will be up to the Sharks to make sure of that, Friesen  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This offseason we need to work on getting stronger and faster.  
We have to work on that,'' he said. ``Our team has to get bigger 
and faster.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
