<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Chief Not Worried About Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- The president of the European Central Bank  
said Tuesday he wasn't worried about the weakness of the new euro 
currency against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Wim Duisenberg refused to comment, however, on whether the bank  
would consider intervening if the euro's decline continued. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no concerns,'' he told reporters before a conference  
on the 75th anniversary of the National Bank of Poland. 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal's central bank president Antonio de Sousa said the bank  
was not happy with the weakened euro, the currency of 11 European 
nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should clearly stress that we don't want a weakened euro,''  
de Sousa said. But he added that intervention in the foreign 
exchange market can't solve structural problems that could be 
weakening the currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro this week was trading in London about 9.6 percent below  
its level when launched Jan. 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
