<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ridding Sprouts of Harmful Bacteria / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) -- Crunchy, nutritious sprouts seem like the  
ultimate health food -- often piled on salads or layered in veggie 
sandwiches. 
</P>
<P>
	But the sprout industry has been devastated in the past few  
years by concerns over the unhealthy pathogens that sprouts can 
carry. A recent medical study estimated more than 20,000 people 
were sickened in three salmonella outbreaks linked to alfalfa 
sprouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Now a task force of researchers, including some from the  
University of Georgia, is trying to find ways to rid sprouts of 
pathogens and reinstate consumer confidence in the food. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like we've just thrown up our hands and said, 'Take  
your chances.' We don't feel that way. We feel the health of our 
consumer is the most important priority,'' said Nancy Snider, 
president of the International Sprout Growers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Snider said about 475 sprout growers are located across the  
United States. Sprout growing was a $250 million industry in 1998, 
but Snider estimates it will be down to $200 million this year 
because of decreased consumer sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The Massachusetts-based sprout growers association is a member  
of the task force, along with researchers from the U.S. Department 
of Agriculture, the Food and Drug Administration, the Environmental 
Protection Agency, Illinois Institute of Technology, the University 
of Georgia and the University of Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	The task force wants to reduce the amount of pathogens like  
salmonella and E. coli that sprout seeds can carry by more than 
99.99 percent, said Dr. Charles Sizer, director of the National 
Center for Food Safety and Technology at IIT. 
</P>
<P>
	Task force members are working on four different ways to  
accomplish that goal -- by heating the seeds in water in a process 
similar to pasteurization, by using a disinfecting chemical like 
hydrogen peroxide and with two different methods of irradiation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is the seeds are fairly delicate. We're in a  
balancing act, trying to get as much kill as we can and still 
retain the germination of the seeds,'' Sizer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Peter Slade, an assistant professor at IIT and the task  
force coordinator, said irradiation looks promising. The process 
involves using low-level doses of gamma rays or electron beam 
irradiation to kill bacteria. 
</P>
<P>
	And researchers are optimistic about a test on growing water  
before the sprouts would be harvested. If the water tested positive 
for a bacterium like salmonella, the sprouts would be discarded, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The task force hopes to have some solutions in another six  
months, but in the meantime, growers can used a chlorination 
process approved by the FDA to decontaminate seeds, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Contamination comes from several sources. About half the alfalfa  
seeds used by growers come from foreign suppliers, whose growing 
safeguards might not be as strict as in the United States, said 
Slade. 
</P>
<P>
	The seeds can become contaminated in the field by feces from a  
salmonella-infected animal or waste water. The way sprouts are 
produced -- with lots of water -- also encourages the spread of 
pathogens, as does the fact that bacteria love the same nutrients 
that make sprouts nutritious for humans, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 05:45:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> California Executes Manuel Babbitt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN QUENTIN, Calif. (AP) -- A Vietnam veteran who received a  
Purple Heart on death row was executed by injection early Tuesday 
for beating a 78-year-old woman to death. 
</P>
<P>
	Manuel Babbitt died at 12:37 a.m. PDT, a day after his 50th  
birthday, after all his court appeals were denied. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt was sentenced to death for killing Leah Schendel in  
1980. He was convicted of breaking into her Sacramento apartment 
and hammering her with punches that broke her dentures and split 
the skin on her forehead to the bone. Her frail heart gave out 
under the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt said he didn't remember what happened that night, or the  
following evening when he attacked another woman, breaking off when 
a friend rushed to her aid. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Marine was turned in to police by his brother, Bill,  
whose suspicions were aroused after he found items stolen in the 
Schendel slaying in Manuel Babbitt's belongings. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Babbitt and other family members deplore what Babbitt did  
but they don't believe he was in his right mind when he did it. 
They say he was flashing back to Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	Defenders said Babbitt, troubled by mental disease since his  
youth, cracked under the pressure of 77 days of shelling, misery 
and death in the siege of Khe Sanh. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt received a Purple Heart in prison for wounds suffered  
during that siege. The rare death row ceremony infuriated Mrs. 
Schendel's family, which demanded -- and got -- legislation banning 
another such presentation. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt was the seventh man executed since California resumed  
executions in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 13:05:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3:40 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Cops Say Cuban Asks for Asylum  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A member of the Cuban delegation that came to  
Baltimore for a baseball game has requested asylum, Baltimore 
police said Tuesday. Police said Rigoberto Herrera walked into a 
Baltimore Police Department office at 10 a.m. EDT today to make the 
request. Baltimore police contacted the Immigration Naturalization 
Service. INS representatives took custody of Herrera at 11:30 a.m., 
police spokesman Robert Weinhold said in a statement. What role 
Herrera played in the delegation and whether he was a player was 
not immediately known. 

</P>
<P>
	Crews Search for More Storm Victims  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Rescue crews picked their way past  
snapped-off trees and smashed cars today in a search for more 
victims of powerful tornadoes that killed at least 36 people in 
Oklahoma and Kansas. Oklahoma's medical examiner's office said an 
earlier higher death toll was an estimate, but one official said he 
was ``fairly certain that number will go up.'' Hundreds of law 
enforcement personnel were dispatched to the damaged areas. It was 
the nation's deadliest outbreak of tornadoes since 1985, when 
storms killed 90 people in Ohio, Pennsylvania and Ontario. 
President Clinton has declared 11 counties in Oklahoma disaster 
areas. 

</P>
<P>
	Federal Aid for Tornado Victims  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal emergency and Red Cross workers are on  
the scene, with more on the way, to assist the victims of the 
tornadoes in Kansas and Oklahoma. The Federal Emergency Management 
Agency will coordinate the work of 27 federal agencies and the Red 
Cross. The Red Cross has set up 10 emergency shelters in Oklahoma 
and three in Kansas. It has also sent a dozen emergency response 
vehicles to provide food for tornado victims in the two states. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Claims Heavy Hits in Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO claimed today its most  
successful round of attacks yet against Serb forces and shot down a 
Yugoslav plane in the first air-to-air battle since early in the 
six-week-old campaign. An alliance jet downed a Yugoslav MiG-29 
fighter jet in a dogfight over Serbia. The Serbs have avoided air 
confrontations since early in the conflict, which began March 24. 
British defense officials said more than 50 targets were struck 
over the previous 24 hours in relentless attacks focusing on 
Yugoslav forces in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady To Greet Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton is to travel  
to New Jersey tomorrow to welcome the first group of ethnic 
Albanian refugees to arrive in the United States from the Balkans. 
About 400 refugees from Kosovo, who have been staying at a camp in 
Macedonia, are being flown to McGuire Air Force Base in Burlington 
County, N.J., which is next to the U.S. Army base at Fort Dix where 
they will be temporarily housed. Relief workers will gather 
biographical information needed to place them with host families 
around the nation. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Address Consumer Privacy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is proposing legislation to  
protect consumers against the increasing trend toward 
information-sharing among banks, insurance companies and securities 
firms. The proposals include requiring financial institutions to 
inform consumers of plans to share or sell their personal financial 
information, and giving consumers the power to stop such a 
transfer; restricting any sharing of medical information within a 
financial conglomerate, and requiring credit-card offers of low 
rates to disclose prominently when those rates expire. 

</P>
<P>
	Sara Lee Makes Bid for Coffee Co.  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sara Lee launched a hostile takeover bid for  
Chock full o'Nuts today as it seeks to compete against giant 
Starbucks. The offer is essentially the same as Sara Lee's $223 
million cash offer that was rejected by the Chock full o'Nuts 
board. Sara Lee would roll Chock full o'Nuts into its Superior 
Coffee division if the takeover is successful. Chock full o'Nuts 
also owns and franchises a chain of 40 drive-through coffee outlets 
called Quikava. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 102  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 102.23 to 10,912.46. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,473-1,467. The Nasdaq was down 7.28 to 
2,528.30. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  

</P>
