<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 15:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Broker Accountability Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government's top securities regulator,  
noting that ads for online trading often resemble lottery 
commercials, is urging Internet brokerages to better warn their 
customers about the risks that come with investing on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Explaining clearly to customers ... would go a long way toward  
reducing the complaints pouring into the SEC, Congress and firms,'' 
Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``To every online firm, I challenge you to meaningfully  
communicate with your customers,'' Levitt said in a speech at the 
National Press Club. ``Talk in realistic terms; let them know their 
options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said an SEC review of online brokerage account agreements  
found that ``almost none'' of them discuss trading risks or what 
customers should do if there is a computer system outage. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC chief also said online firms need to ensure they have  
adequate computer system capacity to handle the swarms of new 
customers, asserting that the brokers have a legal obligation to 
provide efficient execution of trading orders. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt said he's not convinced the market watchdog agency needs  
a new set of regulations for online investing, but he did not rule 
out that possibility in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	He also criticized advertisements by some Internet brokers which  
he said more closely resemble commercials for the playing the 
lottery by promising quick riches. 
</P>
<P>
	``In today's bull market there may be an increasing population  
of tow-truck drivers who now own their own islands as a result of 
online investing. ... (But) I'm worried these commercials step over 
the line and border on irresponsibility,'' he said, referring to 
one widely aired ad campaign on television, Levitt said, 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt's remarks come as the SEC and the National Association of  
Securities Dealers, a self-policing brokers' group, have been 
investigating online brokerages nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to looking for violations of securities laws, the  
investigators are examining how well firms execute orders and warn 
customers of trading risks. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt said SEC auditors already have inspected online firms  
representing 80 percent of the electronic-trading market. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters say that by year's end, 10 million amateur investors  
will be trading at least occasionally over the Internet, and online 
customers will account for about a quarter of all retail stock 
trades. The biggest online brokerages include Charles Schwab, 
E-Trade Group, Ameritrade, Datek Online, DLJdirect and Discover 
Brokerage. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt also expressed concern about that rising popularity of  
day trading, a practice in which investors scope out fast-moving 
stocks, buying and selling them quickly to profit from the sudden 
price swings. Many day-trading companies sell training courses and 
special software to ordinary investors who want to try the risky, 
lightning-speed strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Providing day-trading opportunities is not itself against the  
law, but these firms should be on notice that they ... must operate 
within the existing rules,'' Levitt said. He added that firms 
should ensure that their day-trading strategies are suitable for 
customers' financial circumstances and trading skills. 
</P>
<P>
	State securities regulators also have been scrutinizing  
day-trading firms and a handful of them, particularly in 
Massachusetts, have filed fraud charges. 
</P>
<P>
	William Galvin, Massachusetts' secretary of state, announced  
Monday a settlement with All-Tech Investment Group in which the big 
day-trading firm agreed to pay a $50,000 fine and reimburse 
customers $228,000. 
</P>
<P>
	All-Tech neither admitted to nor denied wrongdoing in the  
settlement, but agreed not to sign up any new customers in the 
state for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Operators of day-trading firms acknowledge that the strategy is  
not right for everyone, but contend state regulators are unfairly 
tarnishing the industry because of a few rogue firms that may have 
misled investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The NASD, which operates the Nasdaq Stock Market, has been  
considering since March a new rule that would require day-trading 
firms to screen investors and warn them in writing of the risks. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 22:51:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Broker Accountability Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- You may have seen the TV ad: A guy's car has  
broken down and he's riding in the front seat with the tow-truck 
driver. They talk and it turns out the driver not only trades 
online with a big brokerage firm, he's made enough money to buy his 
own island. He just drives the truck for fun. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the government's top securities regulator, saying such  
advertisements for online trading often resemble lottery 
commercials, is urging online brokerages to provide better warnings 
to their customers about the risks that come with investing on the 
Internet. 
</P>
