<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Boeing Rocket Malfunctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Boeing's new Delta III rocket  
blasted into space Tuesday night, eight months after the inaugural 
flight ended in a midair explosion. But it quickly ran into 
trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	The second stage used to boost the Orion communication satellite  
into a higher orbit ignited properly the first time, but apparently 
did not fire as long as it should have the second time around. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's all the information we have for right now,'' the launch  
commentator said before going off the air an hour into the flight. 
``It's preliminary at this time, and we believe we will have 
further details for you later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the information is correct, the satellite could be in too low  
of an orbit. The satellite was supposed to serve Asia and the 
Pacific for Loral Space and Communications from a 22,300-mile-high 
perch. 
</P>
<P>
	It would be the third time in less than a month that a satellite  
has ended up in the wrong orbit. The two other satellites were 
launched aboard the Air Force's Titan IV rocket. 
</P>
<P>
	The Delta III is key to Boeing's plan to grab more of the launch  
market. The rocket is designed to carry twice as much payload as 
the smaller Delta II. 
</P>
<P>
	The mood was tenser than usual going into Tuesday night's  
launch. Not only did it mark the Delta III's return to flight, it 
was the fifth launch attempt in a month. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, the countdown went all the way down to zero, but  
the rocket never ignited. Boeing fixed the error and aimed for a 
Sunday liftoff, then delayed the mission two days to make sure 
there were no similarities between the Delta III and the Titan IV, 
which launched a military communication satellite into an orbit 
thousands of miles too low last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm more nervous than I normally am,'' Boeing mission director  
Rich Murphy said Tuesday afternoon. ``The whole industry is having 
its problems at the moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last August, a Delta III carrying a Galaxy broadcasting  
satellite blew up 71 seconds after liftoff. The rocket used up all 
of its hydraulic fluid for steering and broke apart when it 
encountered wind shear. 
</P>
<P>
	The Delta III's debut ended up being a $225 million disaster and  
cost Boeing millions more for the investigation that followed. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 19:12:15 </DATE_TIME>
