<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alexander Looks To Raise More Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander,  
saying his ability to garner money will make him a more viable 
candidate for the presidency, picked up $1 million in his first 
fund-raiser Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we continue to raise money at the rate we're starting with,  
I have no doubt that I'll be one of two or three candidates able to 
raise enough money to compete for first place in all of the early 
primaries,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The former governor, university president and education  
secretary made the remarks to reporters before the fund-raising 
dinner at the Opryland hotel here -- the first of 26 such events on 
his schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander said his strong support for and identification with  
education is what sets him apart from his Republican competitors 
for the party's presidential nomination next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want our party to be strong on taxes, I want us to be strong  
on defense, but at the top of my list is having the best schools 
and helping parents be at their best,'' he said. ``I believe I 
carry that message more effectively to the country and in debates 
with (Vice President) Albert Gore than any of the other 
Republicans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander remains undaunted by his failed effort three years ago  
to win the GOP nomination then. 
</P>
<P>
	``Like Presidents Bush, Nixon and Reagan, I've run before and no  
one on the Republican side, since Eisenhower, has made it all the 
way to the top the first time they've run,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He dismissed a recent CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll showing him  
ranked seventh in popularity among possible GOP presidential 
contenders, characterizing them as pre-season results. 
</P>
<P>
	The most important thing for voters is putting the right person  
in office, he said, especially considering the U.S. military 
strikes against Yugoslavia and the Littleton, Colo., school 
shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what's happened in the Balkans and what's happened in  
Littleton reminds us that the question before the voters will not 
be who's the most famous, who can raise the most money, it will be 
who's ready to be president,'' Alexander said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
