<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Predicts Cancer Relapses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some men who undergo surgery for prostate  
cancer have blood tests signaling they'll eventually relapse -- but 
until now, no one knew how long they'd survive or which patients 
needed aggressive treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	A new study, released Tuesday, identifies men at highest risk  
and shows those frightening test results don't always mean imminent 
death. 
</P>
<P>
	``Patients may live for years without having the cancer  
spread,'' Dr. Mario Eisenberger of Johns Hopkins University 
explained. ``We hope our (study) will help physicians and patients 
make a more sensible decision on whether they need treatment at 
all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His study was published in a special cancer edition of the  
Journal of the American Medical Association. 
</P>
<P>
	The journal also highlighted significant news for women: When a  
Pap smear cannot tell a woman's true risk of cervical cancer, a 
simple new test for a cancer-causing virus can accurately determine 
which women need treatment -- and which do not need to worry about 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	In the case of prostate cancer, surgically removing the  
walnut-sized gland often is a cure. But the cancer sometimes 
returns in other parts of the body. This metastatic disease is 
incurable; once men relapse, median survival is five years. 
</P>
<P>
	The first warning sign is a blood test that detects  
prostate-specific antigen, or PSA. Men with no prostates have no 
PSA unless some prostate cancer cells are still roaming their 
bodies. But PSA can be detected years before new tumors actually 
appear. Until now, doctors didn't know what to tell these 
frightened men. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisenberger's study of 1,997 surgery patients found it can take  
years between that first worrisome PSA test and cancer's return. 
Doctors can determine patient survival based on how soon PSA 
appeared after surgery, how fast PSA levels rose and whether 
initial prostate tumors were high-grade or low-grade. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, a 75-year-old man whose initial tumor was low-grade  
and whose PSA didn't return until four years after surgery probably 
won't relapse for more than 10 years. He may choose not to be 
treated -- healthy men that age have only a 10-year life expectancy 
anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	But men with high-grade tumors whose PSA rises within two years  
of surgery are at risk for relapsing in less than eight years, and 
might want treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	A complication: There is no good therapy. Suppressing  
testosterone, the main choice, can cause significant side effects. 
But Eisenberger said that if those who relapse quickly enter 
studies of experimental new therapies, scientists may learn faster 
which ones work. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, Kaiser Permanente researchers said testing for the  
virus that causes most cervical cancer is important for women whose 
Pap smears aren't clear. 
</P>
<P>
	Pap smears detect the earliest signs of cervical cancer. But  
some 2 million women annually have unclear results, where doctors 
can't tell if they're getting cancer or not. Those women can either 
get a surgical biopsy, or wait an anxious six months for a repeat 
Pap. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kaiser's study of 1,000 such women, testing for human  
papillomavirus, or HPV, proved 89 percent accurate in pinpointing 
women with precancerous cervical cells -- while repeat Pap tests 
were just 76 percent accurate. 
</P>
<P>
	A regular Pap smear won't yield enough cells for the extra HPV  
test. So the researchers recommended using a new type of Pap smear 
called ThinPrep that collects enough cells for both Pap and HPV 
testing at once. 
</P>
<P>
	But many insurance companies don't cover ThinPrep, which costs  
about $15 more than a regular Pap. Plus, Digene Corp.'s HPV test 
costs $35 to $50. Although the Kaiser study called HPV testing 
cost-effective, Kaiser said it would determine coverage on a 
case-by-case basis. 
</P>
<P>
	Also in Tuesday's journal:  
</P>
<P>
	--A Harvard-led study showed prostate cancer patients with low  
PSA levels have the best chance of being cured by radiation. The 
study offers the first guidelines for choosing the best 
radiation-therapy candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	--Georgetown University offered genetic testing to 208 members of  
families prone to a type of inherited colon cancer -- those who 
carried the high-risk genes then would know to get regular cancer 
checks proven to prolong life. But just 43 percent agreed to gene 
testing. People most likely to refuse had symptoms of depression 
and were less educated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
