<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 19:23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGwire Breaks Homerless Streak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Mark McGwire broke his homerless streak with a  
flourish Tuesday night, hitting a second-inning grand slam against 
Atlanta's Greg Maddux that sparked two bench-clearing situations. 
</P>
<P>
	The St. Louis slugger, who had not homered since April 18, came  
up with the bases loaded and two outs after the Cardinals already 
had two runs against Maddux, the Braves' four-time Cy Young winner. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire hit a 1-0 pitch from Maddux into Atlanta's right-field  
bullpen for his sixth homer of the season. That gave the Cardinals 
a 6-0 lead and broke a streak of 41 at-bats without a homer. 
</P>
<P>
	Maddux, who had never before given up six runs in an inning,  
lasted only 4 1-3 innings. He allowed 12 hits and eight runs -- 
equaling the most runs he's surrendered in a game during his 
brilliant career. 
</P>
<P>
	Two pitches after the homer, he plunked Ray Lankford on the  
shoulder, prompting both benches to empty. No punches were thrown, 
but home-plate umpire Larry Poncino warned the teams to avoid 
further trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, on the first pitch in the bottom of the second, Cardinals  
starter and ex-Brave Kent Mercker threw behind Andruw Jones. 
Mercker was ejected and both dugouts emptied again, though the 
teams managed to avoid fisticuffs for a second time. 
</P>
<P>
	On his way to a record-breaking 70 last year, McGwire's sixth  
homer came during a three-homer performance on April 14 -- St. 
Louis' 13th game of the season. He needed 25 games to hit No. 6 
this year, going the last 13 games without one. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire already eclipsed his longest homerless streak of 1998,  
when he twice went 29 at-bats without going deep. He wound up with 
an average of one homer every 7.3 at-bats. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the 12th grand slam of McGwire's career, the last coming  
on June 12 at Arizona. He went 3-for-5 in the game before being 
replaced by a pinch-runner in the eighth inning with the Cardinals 
leading 9-0. 
</P>
<P>
	Maddux has allowed only one other regular-season grand slam  
since coming up to the big leagues 13 years ago -- a base-clearing 
drive by Philadelphia's Benito Santiago on May 3, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 15:24:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Weren't Into Cuba This Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- In retrospect, the Baltimore Orioles would have  
been far better off saying farewell to the Cuban baseball team 
after their exhibition game in Havana five weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The rematch Monday night was a disaster for the Orioles from  
start to finish. Worse, the consequences of the embarrassing loss 
didn't end with the final pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles never really wanted to play Cuba in the middle of  
the regular season, and their indifference was evident early in the 
one-sided affair. After a rain delay of nearly an hour and a 
four-run second inning that put Cuba comfortably ahead, Baltimore 
went through the motions in a humbling 12-6 defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	``That wasn't a real great way to spend a day,'' said left  
fielder B.J. Surhoff, essentially summing up the feeling of 
virtually everyone in the organization except perhaps owner Peter 
Angelos, who strived for three years to make the home-and-home 
series a reality. 
</P>
<P>
	The first game in Havana on March 28 was different, in part  
because the Orioles had yet to start their season. Baltimore used 
its third starter, Scott Erickson, and managed to pull off a 3-2 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The rematch, however, came in the middle of a 12-game homestand  
and robbed the Orioles of one of only two off days in May. Orioles 
manager Ray Miller rested all his starting pitchers and went with 
Scott Kamieniecki, who was on the disabled list and admitted after 
the game, ``I just wasn't into it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kamieniecki didn't get past the second inning, so Miller had to  
reach into his bullpen early and often. He used both his long 
relievers, Doug Linton and Ricky Bones, leaving him short for 
Tuesday night's game against the Chicago White Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'll be OK with eight or 10 Tylenol,'' Linton quipped.  
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore trailed by nine runs before Delino DeShields hit a  
three-run homer in the ninth, but that did little to ease the 
humiliation of losing to a team whose collective salary isn't much 
more than what Baltimore's Albert Belle carries in his wallet. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle, by the way, went 0-for-3 and was 0-for-8 in the two  
games. 
</P>
<P>
	But he was one of several Orioles who experienced futility  
against the Cubans. First baseman Calvin Pickering made three 
errors in the rematch and reliever Gabe Molina gave up five runs in 
one inning. 
</P>
<P>
	The first game went off without a hitch, but the game at Camden  
Yards was marred by four people running onto the field. The last 
was slammed to the ground by second base umpire Cesar Valdes, who 
is Cuban. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as yesterday, I'm just going to forget about that,''  
Miller said. ``Five-and-a-half hours of baseball and wrestling 
matches is a bit much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the Orioles turned their attention to the White Sox, the  
Cubans celebrated a wonderful victory at home. But Baltimore police 
said Rigoberto Herrera, a coach who accompanied the team to the 
United States, asked for asylum Tuesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the lopsided loss, the affect it had on the team and the  
defection, Linton said the second game was a worthwhile event. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a step in the right direction,'' he said, ``politically  
and for baseball.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990504.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 18:42:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> City Council Wants A's Bids Details </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Less than a week before the deadline for  
choosing the group of investors that will be given the chance to 
buy the Oakland Athletics, city council members complained Tuesday 
they don't have enough information. 
</P>
<P>
	Public officials have until May 11 to select one of two groups  
vying for the right to purchase the A's for $122.4 million, and to 
pass that selection on to major league baseball for approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The city council and the Alameda County Board of Supervisors  
scheduled meetings this week to hear about the two groups and their 
bids. The city council meeting was Tuesday, with the county 
supervisors scheduled to meet on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The investors group including former A's executive Andy Dolich,  
Hall of Fame second baseman Joe Morgan and Bob Piccinini, the 
chairman of Modesto-based Save Mart Foods, made a presentation to 
the city council in which Dolich drew applause as he referred to 
the A's past greatness and the glory of baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	The other group includes former pitcher Steve Stone, now a  
broadcaster for the Chicago Cubs, and former A's coach and New York 
Yankees general manager Bob Watson. That group did not appear at 
Tuesday's meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Council members demanded more details about the two groups from  
Randy Vataha, the president of the Game Plan consulting firm that 
was hired by public officials to lead the search for prospective 
buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	``What concerns me today is I feel like I'm sitting at a pep  
rally and not a city council meeting,'' council member Jane Brunner 
said. ``I cannot make a decision without pieces of paper and a 
commitment. I need detail behind those general statements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vataha promised to deliver more information to council members  
before they hold another special meeting Monday, after which they 
are expected to recommend one of the two groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Vataha also said the new owners would be required to stay at the  
Oakland Coliseum only until the 2004 season, but that the two 
groups were chosen because they have promised a long-term 
commitment to staying in Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	The audience for the special meeting included Oakland Coliseum  
workers, some wearing A's caps and jackets. Several audience 
members arose to express their support for Dolich's group, saying 
it has deeper Oakland roots. 
</P>
<P>
	Ignacio de la Fuente, president of the city council, seemed to  
echo those feelings. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are sitting in a good position. We have two well-qualified  
groups,'' he said. ``But only one has people that work and live in 
this community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But other council members, mindful of the legal and financial  
problems that have ensued from the city's deal to bring the NFL's 
Raiders back to Oakland from Los Angeles, were much more cautious 
and said they want more details of the bids. 
</P>
<P>
	If neither of the investor groups buys the A's, current owners  
Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann would retain control of the team and 
have the right to sell or move the A's. San Jose has been mentioned 
as a city possibly interested in seeking the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Schott and Hofmann worked out a deal last fall that gave public  
officials a chance to sell the team at a predetermined price to a 
group of investors willing to keep the team in Oakland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
