<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Testimony in Starr Probe Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- One of President Clinton's private  
lawyers testified today that he sought an affidavit from Julie 
Hiatt Steele saying that Kathleen Willey asked her to lie to back 
up Mrs. Willey's story of a sexual advance by the president. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second day of Ms. Steele's trial, prosecutors summoned  
Mitch Ettinger to describe his visit to Ms. Steele in January 1998, 
while he was working on the president's defense in the Paula Jones 
sexual harassment lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Under sometimes contentious questioning, Ettinger said he never  
pressured Ms. Steele to sign the affidavit and insisted it wasn't 
crucial to the president's defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends of Ms. Steele have testified that she told them about  
the alleged incident between Mrs. Willey and Clinton prior to 1997. 
Clinton has denied any such incident. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele told investigators she first heard the allegation  
against Clinton when Mrs. Willey asked her to lie to back up her 
story to a Newsweek reporter. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele, 52, is charged with obstruction of justice and  
giving false statements, accused of lying to FBI agents and two 
grand juries in Kenneth Starr's investigation of the president. 
</P>
<P>
	Ettinger said Ms. Steele told him that Mrs. Willey had ``asked  
her to fabricate a story regarding Mr. Clinton and Ms. Willey to 
the effect that Mr. Clinton had improperly made sexual advances 
toward her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president's lawyers drafted an affidavit saying that, but  
Ms. Steele declined to sign it for a couple of weeks. Ettinger said 
he didn't know of anyone working for the president pressed her to 
sign it. She eventually did. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors have argued that Ms. Steele lied to ally herself  
with the president; defense attorneys maintain she is telling the 
truth. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Highsmith, a witness who said she had been Ms. Steele's  
best friend, said, ``Julie told me she was afraid it was to her 
detriment if she took a position against the president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Highsmith also testified Monday that she was called  
repeatedly by Ms. Steele last summer, around the time she gave 
grand jury testimony in Starr's investigation that contradicted Ms. 
Steele's testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	``Julie wanted to know if I had testified. ... She wanted to  
know what the grand jury wanted to know. ... I wanted to avoid that 
conversation,'' but ended up telling her, Mrs. Highsmith said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mrs. Highsmith admitted on cross-examination today that she  
had changed her story on a crucial point involving Ms. Steele and 
remembered new information last November that she hadn't recalled 
in her first half-dozen interviews with investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	Her new memory was that Ms. Steele told her in November 1997  
that she first heard Mrs. Willey's story about Clinton in 1994, the 
year after it happened. 
</P>
<P>
	Highsmith said she forgot the details after she ``started a new  
life'' by moving to Colorado and it came back to her after 
refreshing her memory for the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey, who was expected to testify today, says she  
confided the alleged Clinton advance to Ms. Steele hours after it 
occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	The discrepancy is one factor that made it impossible for Starr  
to send an impeachment referral on the Willey matter to the House 
last year along with his referral on the Monica Lewinsky affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking in a soft voice, Mrs. Highsmith testified to the  
federal jury that in September 1996, Mrs. Willey related the 
alleged Clinton advance to her and to Ms. Steele over lunch. Mrs. 
Highsmith said she was shocked, but that there was ``not a big 
reaction'' from Ms. Steele. 
</P>
<P>
	Under questioning by Steele lawyer Eric Dubelier, Mrs. Highsmith  
admitted that she initially told Starr's investigators that the 
first time she ever spoke to Ms. Steele about Mrs. Willey's 
allegation was in January or February 1998. In that initial FBI 
interview on June 26, 1998, Mrs. Highsmith stated there was no 
discussion at the 1996 luncheon of any alleged sexual advance by 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the time that was the way I recalled it,'' said Mrs.  
Highsmith. ``That is what I said the first time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Highsmith admitted she called Starr's investigators back  
the next day and said the first time she'd heard of the Willey 
incident was in a November 1997 phone call from Ms. Steele. She 
changed her story again when testifying to Starr's grand jury in 
Alexandria, Va., six weeks later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
