<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Chief Urges E-Trade Warnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government's top securities regulator,  
concerned about the booming electronic trading business, today 
urged online brokerage firms to warn their clients of trading 
risks. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange  
Commission, made the request in a speech at the National Press 
Club. 
</P>
<P>
	``To every online firm, I challenge you to meaningfully  
communicate with your customers,'' Levitt said. ``Talk in realistic 
terms; let them know their options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said an SEC review of online brokerage account agreements  
found that ``almost none'' of them discuss trading risks or what 
customers should do if there is a computer system outage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Explaining clearly to customers ... would go a long way toward  
reducing the complaints pouring into the SEC, Congress and firms,'' 
Levitt suggested. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC chief also said online firms need to ensure they have  
adequate computer system capacity to handle the flood of new 
customers, asserting that the brokers have a legal obligation to 
provide efficient execution of trading orders. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Levitt expressed concern about some online firms'  
advertisements, saying they more closely resemble commercials for 
the lottery by promising quick riches. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt's remarks came as securities regulators investigate  
online brokerage firms and day-trading companies nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation by the SEC and the National Association of  
Securities Dealers, a self-policing brokers' group, has been 
conducted over the past two months or so. The auditors are looking 
for possible violations of securities laws as well as examining how 
well the firms execute customers' orders and warn them of trading 
risks. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt said SEC auditors already have inspected online firms  
representing 80 percent of the electronic trading market. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters say that by year's end, 10 million amateur investors  
will be doing at least occasional trading over the Internet, and 
online customers will account for about a quarter of all retail 
stock trades. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest online brokerages include Charles Schwab, E-Trade  
Group, Ameritrade, Datek Online, DLJdirect and Discover Brokerage. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related move, Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., is proposing  
increasing the SEC's budget, now at $337.4 million, by $5.5 million 
next year to police against investment fraud over the Internet, a 
Senate aide said today. Gregg is chairman of a Senate 
Appropriations subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC has asked for an increase of $11 million.  
</P>
<P>
	The world of online day-trading is much smaller than the online  
brokerage business, but also growing fast. Day-traders scope out 
stocks, especially in high-tech companies, solely for sharp price 
swings, buying and selling them quickly to profit from short-term 
movements in price. 
</P>
<P>
	Day-trading companies sell training courses and special software  
programs to ordinary investors who want to try the risky, 
lightning-speed practice. 
</P>
<P>
	State securities regulators also have been scrutinizing  
day-trading firms and a handful of them, particularly in 
Massachusetts, have filed fraud charges. 
</P>
<P>
	William Galvin, Massachusetts' secretary of state, announced  
Monday a settlement with All-Tech Investment Group Inc. in which 
the big day-trading firm agreed to pay a $50,000 fine and reimburse 
customers $228,000. All-Tech neither admitted to nor denied 
wrongdoing in the settlement, but agreed not to sign up any new 
customers in the state for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Operators of the day-trading firms acknowledge they're not for  
everyone, but they contend state regulators are unfairly tarnishing 
the industry because of a few rogue firms that may have misled 
investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The NASD, which operates the Nasdaq Stock Market, has been  
considering since March a new rule that would require day-trading 
firms to screen investors and warn them in writing of the risks. 
</P>
<P>
	In related moves Monday, state securities regulators announced  
they have formed a task force to examine online trading issues such 
as advertising and customer order processing. And the Securities 
Industry Association issued a brochure for investors titled 
``Online Investing Tips.'' It is available on the trade group's Web 
site at www.sia.com. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
