<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Results on Presidential Races </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some results from polls released Tuesday on the presidential  
campaigns, nationally and in New Hampshire. When results don't 
total 100 percent, the remainder didn't know or declined to answer. 

</P>
<P>
	 *NATIONAL (CNN-USA Today-Gallup)    	

</P>
<P>
	Asked of Democrats: Which one of these candidates would you be  
most likely to support for the Democratic nomination for president 
in the year 2000? 
</P>
<P>
	Al Gore, 66 percent; Bill Bradley, 23 percent. In a poll last  
month, Gore led Bradley by 20 points. 

</P>
<P>
	Asked of Republicans: Which of these candidates would you be  
most likely to support for the Republican nomination for president 
in the year 2000? 
</P>
<P>
	George W. Bush, 42 percent; Elizabeth Dole, 24 percent; Steve  
Forbes, 6 percent; Dan Quayle, 6 percent; Patrick Buchanan, 5 
percent; John McCain, 4 percent; Lamar Alexander, 3 percent; Gary 
Bauer, 3 percent; John Kasich, 1 percent; Bob Smith, 1 percent. 
Bush led Dole by 53 percent to 16 percent in a poll last month. 

</P>
<P>
	Asked of all: If Vice President Al Gore were the Democratic  
Party's candidate and Texas Gov. George W. Bush were the Republican 
Party's candidate, who would you be more likely to vote for? 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, 56 percent; Gore, 40 percent. This is about the same lead  
Bush has had over Gore since February. 

</P>
<P>
	 *NEW HAMPSHIRE (University of New Hampshire for WMUR-CNN)    	

</P>
<P>
	Asked of New Hampshire Republicans: If you were voting in the  
2000 New Hampshire primary for president today, would you vote for 
...
</P>
<P>
	George W. Bush, 37 percent; Elizabeth Dole, 16 percent; John  
McCain, 14 percent; Pat Buchanan, 7 percent; Steve Forbes, 6 
percent; Lamar Alexander, 5 percent; Dan Quayle, 4 percent; Bob 
Smith, 2 percent; John Kasich, 1 percent. Bush and Dole were in a 
statistical tie in a poll taken in January. 

</P>
<P>
	Asked of New Hampshire Democrats: If you were voting in the 2000  
New Hampshire primary for president today, would you vote for ... 
</P>
<P>
	Al Gore, 68 percent; Bill Bradley, 23 percent.  

</P>
<P>
	The CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll of 1,014 adults taken Friday  
through Sunday has an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage 
points. The error margin of subsamples of 411 Republicans and 492 
Democrats is plus or minus 5 percentage points. The New Hampshire 
poll taken April 26-May 2 of 279 likely Republican voters had an 
error margin of plus or minus 6 percentage points, and the poll of 
202 likely Democratic voters had an error margin of plus or minus 7 
percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
